nue]\n|}\nMap source: [[Lehigh County, Pennsylvania|Lehigh County, PA]] [http://www.lehighcounty.org web site]\n\n===Current Officials===\n\n====Township====\n\n=====Mayor=====\n*Michael P. Harakal Jr. (D; term April 2018 -2019 $87,433.07 {2016}, $89,618.90 {2017},$91,859.37 {2018}, $94,155.85 {2019} E code 360\n\n=====Township Treasurer=====\n*Colleen Gober 2019-2011 (D); Township Compensation $35,919.30 {2014}, $36,278.49 (2015) $37,004.06 (2016) $$37,374.10 (2017);This does not include compensation from the Whitehall Coplay School District\n\n===== Township Commissioners=====\n*Phillip J. Ginder, President Term 2019-2023 (D; $4,125<ref>{{cite web|title=\u00a7 1-7. Compensation of Commissioners.|url=http://www.ecode360.com/13153947?all=true#13153985|publisher=eCode360.com|accessdate=15 May 2012}}</ref>); \n*Joseph J. Marx Jr., Vice President Term 2017-2021 (D;$4,125); \n*Thomas Slonaker, Secretary Term 2017-2021 (D;$4,125); \n*Randy Atiyeh Term 2019-2023 (D; $4,125);\n*Michael Dee, Term 2020-2021 (D:$4,125); \n*Charles G. Fisher, Term 2019-2023 (D;$4,125); \n*Jeffrey Warren Term 2019-2023 (D;$4,125);\n\n====Lehigh County====\n\n=====County Executive=====\nPhillips Armstrong (D; $75,000); 2018-2021\n\n=====County Commissioners=====\n*1st County District\n**Marc J. Grammes (R);\n::Whitehall Districts: 2, 4\u201312 (plus others outside Whitehall)\n*4th County District\n**Daniel K. McCarthy, Vice Chair (D;);\n::Whitehall Districts: 1, 3 (plus others outside Whitehall)\n'''{{As of|2014|lc=y}} Whitehall entirely in 1st county District'''\n\n====Pennsylvania====\n\n=====Senate=====\n*18th State Senatorial District: [http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/home/member_information/senate_bio.cfm?id=179 Lisa Boscola] (D; $85,536); 2013-2018 ([http://www.senatorboscola.com/district_info.htm District map])\n\n=====State House=====\n*133rd State Legislative District\n**Jeanne McNeill (D; $87,180); 2017-2018\n::Whitehall Districts: 2\u20136, 8\u20139 (plus others outside Whitehall)\n*183rd State Legislative District\n**Zach Mako (R; $87,180); 2017-2018\n::Whitehall Districts: 1, 7, 10\u201312 (plus others outside Whitehall)\n\n====Federal====\n\n=====Senate=====\n*Senior Senator: [[Bob Casey, Jr.]] (D; $174,000); 2024\n*Junior Senator: [[Pat Toomey]] (R; $174,000); 2022\n\n=====House=====\n*7th District of Pennsylvania: [[Susan Wild]] (D; $174,000); 2020 ([http://www.govtrack.us/congress/findyourreps.xpd?state=PA&district=7 District map])\n\n====Sources====\n*[http://www.lwvlv.org/govdir_lehigh.htm#WHITEHALL%20TOWNSHIP League of Women Voters of the Lehigh Valley]\n*[http://www.lehighcounty.org Lehigh County Web Site]\n\n==Transportation==\nThe township's main north-south road is MacArthur Road ([[Pennsylvania Route 145|PA 145]]), which has an interchange with [[U.S. Route 22 in Pennsylvania|US 22]] in the south and crosses [[Pennsylvania Route 329|PA 329]] in the north. PA 145 heads south into [[Allentown, Pennsylvania|Allentown]] and north to [[Walnutport, Pennsylvania|Walnutport]]. US 22 passes east-west through the southern portion of Whitehall Township on a freeway called the Lehigh Valley Thruway, with interchanges at PA 145 and Fullerton Avenue. US 22 leads west to connections with [[Pennsylvania Route 309|PA 309]], [[Interstate 476|I-476]] ([[Pennsylvania Turnpike]] Northeast Extension), and [[Interstate 78 in Pennsylvania|I-78]] and east to [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]] and [[Easton, Pennsylvania|Easton]]. PA 329 passes east-west through the northern portion of Whitehall Township on Main Street, leading west to [[Schnecksville, Pennsylvania|Schnecksville]] and east to [[Northampton, Pennsylvania|Northampton]] and [[Bath, Pennsylvania|Bath]].<ref name=PennDOTLehigh>{{cite map|publisher=PennDOT|title=Lehigh County, Pennsylvania Highway Map|url=http://www.dot7.state.pa.us/BPR_pdf_files/Maps/GHS/Roadnames/lehigh_GHSN.PDF|year=2012|accessdate=April 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Lehigh and Northampton Transportation Authority|LANTA]] provides bus service in Whitehall Township, with several routes serving the MacArthur Road retail corridor and a transfer center located at the [[Lehigh Valley Mall]]. The bus routes connect the township with Allentown, Bethlehem, and other points in the Lehigh Valley.<ref>{{cite map|title=System Map|publisher=LANTA|url=http://www.lantabus.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/05sep2016_system_map_jpeg_3000px.jpeg|accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.whitehalltownship.com/ Whitehall Township]\n*[http://whitehallhistoricalsociety.org/ Whitehall Historical Preservation Association Official Web Site]\n\n{{Lehigh Valley}}\n{{Lehigh County, Pennsylvania}}\n{{PA Home Rule Municipality}}\n{{New York metropolitan area}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places on the Lehigh River]]\n[[Category:Townships in Lehigh County, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "107.77.203.26", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSources:Who knows?)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitehall_Township,_Lehigh_County,_Pennsylvania"}
{"title_page": "Urban rail transit in Canada", "text_new": "{{short description|List of Canadian passenger rail systems confined to urban areas}}\n[[Urban rail transit]] in Canada encompasses a broad range of rail mass transit systems, including [[commuter rail]], [[rapid transit]], [[light rail]], and [[streetcar]] systems.\n\n==Terminology==\n{{detail|Passenger rail terminology}}\n* '''Commuter rail''' refers to urban passenger train service between a central city and its suburbs. Three such systems exist in Canada.\n* '''Airport rail link''' refers to rail transport between a central city and its airport. The [[Union Pearson Express]] is the only dedicated airport rail link in Canada. The [[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]] light metro system also serves as an airport rail link.\n* '''Subway''' refers to a rapid transit system using heavy rail with steel wheels. The [[Toronto subway]] is the only such system in Canada.\n* '''Rubber-tired metro''' refers to a rapid transit system using heavy rail with rubber tires. The [[Montreal Metro]] is the only such system in Canada.\n* '''Light metro''' refers to a rapid transit system using intermediate or medium-capacity rail. The SkyTrain is the only full light metro system in Canada. The Toronto subway system includes one light metro line.\n* '''Light rail''' refers to a rail transit system using light rail vehicles in a dedicated [[Right-of-way (transportation)|right-of-way]]. Four such systems exist in Canada.\n* '''Streetcar''' refers to a rail transit system using light rail vehicles entirely or mostly on streets providing local service in mixed traffic. The [[Toronto streetcar system|Toronto streetcar]] is the only such system in Canada.\n* '''People mover''' refers to a small-scale [[automated guideway transit]] system. The [[Link Train]] is the only such system in Canada.\n\n==Existing systems==\n''Italics'' indicate a line under construction.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Region\n!System\n!Average weekday</br>ridership (Q4 2019)<ref name=\"Q4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/2019-Q4-Ridership-APTA.pdf|title=PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION RIDERSHIP REPORT: Fourth Quarter 2019|date=February 27, 2020|website=American Public Transit Association|url-status=live|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n!Technology\n!Lines\n!Stations\n!System length\n!Stations under construction\n!System length</br>under construction\n|-\n|[[Calgary]], Alberta\n|[[CTrain]]\n|{{nts|313800}}\n|[[Light rail]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|calgary|red}} [[Red Line (Calgary)|Red Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|calgary|blue}} [[Blue Line (Calgary)|Blue Line]]\n|45\n|{{Convert|59.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Edmonton]], Alberta\n|[[Edmonton Light Rail Transit|Edmonton LRT]]\n|{{nts|110786}}<br>(2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edmonton.ca/transportation/PDF/2018-LRT-Passenger-Count-Report.pdf|title=2018 LRT Passenger Count Report|date=March 2019|website=City of Edmonton|url-status=live|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Light rail]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|edmonton|capital}} [[Capital Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|edmonton|metro}} [[Metro Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|edmonton|valley}} ''[[Valley Line (Edmonton)|Valley Line]]''\n|18\n|{{Convert|24.3|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|12\n|{{Convert|13.1|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Greater Montreal]], Quebec\n|[[Exo (public transit)|Exo]]\n|{{nts|68500}}<br>(Q3 2019)<ref name=\"Q3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/2019-Q3-Ridership-APTA.pdf|title=PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION RIDERSHIP REPORT: Fourth Quarter 2019|date=November 27, 2019|website=American Public Transit Association|url-status=live|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Commuter rail]]\n|\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Candiac|x}} [[Candiac line|Candiac]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Deux-Montagnes|x}} [[Deux-Montagnes line|Deux-Montagnes]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Vaudreuil-Hudson|x}} [[Vaudreuil-Hudson line|Vaudreuil-Hudson]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Mascouche|x}}