olinx|url-status=live|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Airport rail link]]\n|{{rail-interchange|toronto|up}} [[Union Pearson Express|UP Express]]\n|4\n|{{Convert|23.3|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Toronto subway]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{nts|1603300}}\n|[[Rapid transit|Subway]]\n|\n{{nowrap|{{rail-interchange|toronto|1}} [[Line 1 Yonge\u2013University]]}}<br>\n{{nowrap|{{rail-interchange|toronto|2}} [[Line 2 Bloor\u2013Danforth]]}}<br>\n{{rail-interchange|toronto|4}} [[Line 4 Sheppard]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|75\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{Convert|76.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|39\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{Convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|[[Medium-capacity rail system|Light metro]]\n|{{rail-interchange|toronto|3}} [[Line 3 Scarborough]]\n|-\n|[[Light rail]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|toronto|5}} ''[[Line 5 Eglinton]]''<br>\n{{rail-interchange|toronto|6}} ''[[Line 6 Finch West]]''\n|-\n|[[Toronto streetcar system|Toronto streetcar]]\n|{{nts|530600}}\n|[[Tram|Streetcar]]\n|[[Toronto_streetcar_system#Routes|List]]\n|685\n|{{Convert|83|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Link Train]]\n|\n|[[People mover]]\n|\u2013\n|3\n|{{Convert|1.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Metro Vancouver Regional District|Metro Vancouver]], British Columbia\n|[[West Coast Express]]\n|{{nts|10300}}\n|[[Commuter rail]]\n|{{rail-interchange|vancouver|wce}} [[West Coast Express]]\n|8\n|{{Convert|69|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]]\n|{{nts|512400}}\n|[[Medium-capacity rail system|Light metro]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|vancouver|expo}} [[Expo Line (SkyTrain)|Expo Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|vancouver|millennium}} [[Millennium Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|vancouver|canada}} [[Canada Line]]\n|53\n|{{Convert|79.6|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region]], Ontario\n|[[Ion rapid transit|Ion]]\n|\u2013\n|[[Light rail]]\n|{{rail-interchange|waterloo|ion}} [[Ion rapid transit|Ion]]\n|19\n|{{Convert|19|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|}\n\n===Calgary===\n[[File:Calgary_Transit_S200.jpg|right|thumb|Siemens S200 train at the [[CTrain]]'s [[Saddletowne station]]]]\n{{main|CTrain}}\n[[Calgary Transit]]'s CTrain network, which started operation in 1981, now has the second highest weekday ridership of any light rail transit system in North America, carrying over 312,000 passengers per weekday in the fourth quarter of 2018. There are [[CTrain#List of CTrain stations|45 stations]] in operation in the {{convert|60|km|mi|adj=on}} [[CTrain]] light rail system,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calgary.ca/Transportation/TI/Pages/Transit-projects/Northwest-LRT-Extension-to-Rocky-Ridge---Tuscany.aspx |title=Northwest LRT extension to Rocky Ridge/Tuscany |work=Calgary Transit |publisher=The City of Calgary |year=2014 |accessdate=August 4, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824224447/http://www.calgary.ca/Transportation/TI/Pages/Transit-projects/Northwest-LRT-Extension-to-Rocky-Ridge---Tuscany.aspx |archivedate=August 24, 2012}}</ref> After starting by running on one leg in 1981, the system has expanded and now has four legs radiating out into Calgary's suburbs in different directions. The legs have been organized into two routes (identified as the Red Line and the Blue Line) that connect the four legs via shared tracks in a downtown [[transit mall]]. The existing four legs of the system, as built in chronological order, are the South leg (1981), the Northeast leg (1985), the Northwest leg (1987), and the West leg (2012). \n* The Downtown Transit Mall along 7th Avenue South is shared by the Red and Blue lines.\n* The [[Red Line (Calgary)|Red Line]] connects the South and Northwest legs via the downtown transit mall.\n* The [[Blue Line (Calgary)|Blue Line]] connects the Northeast and West legs via the downtown transit mall.\nThe [[Green Line (Calgary)|Green Line]] is a planned line that would connect new Southeast and North legs via a downtown tunnel.<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite web |url=http://www.calgary.ca/Transportation/TI/Pages/Transit-projects/Green-line/vision.aspx |title=Vision for Green Line |publisher=Calgary Transit | access-date = May 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Edmonton===\n[[File:Bay-Enterprise Square LRT Station (20581703943).jpg|right|thumb|Siemens SD-160 train at the [[Edmonton LRT]]'s [[Bay/Enterprise Square station]]]]\n{{main|Edmonton LRT}}\nThe [[Edmonton Transit System]]'s LRT system consisted of only one line from its opening in 1978 to 2015. The current {{convert|24.3|km|mi|adj=on}} system includes the original [[Capital Line]] and the new [[Metro Line]], sharing most of their route. The first phase of the [[Valley Line (Edmonton)|Valley Line]] is under construction.\n* The Capital Line runs roughly north-south, between northeast Edmonton and the [[Century Park station (Edmonton)|Century Park]] community, with a mix of tunnels and at-grade track. Six stations are underground, while the remaining nine are at-grade.\n* The Metro Line is interlined with the Capital Line from Century Park and through the underground portions before branching northwest towards [[NAIT station|NAIT]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/2015/01/21/edmontons-metro-line-now-set-to-open-in-spring |title=Edmonton's Metro Line now set to open in spring |accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Sun130509\">{{cite web |last=Dykstra |first=Matt |title=Edmonton city crews promise to finish north extension of LRT line to NAIT by next spring |url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/2013/05/09/edmonton-city-crews-promise-to-finish-north-extension-of-lrt-line-to-nait-by-next-spring |work=Edmonton Sun |accessdate=August 26, 2013 |date=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* The Valley Line is currently under construction. The low-floor line will travel southeast from downtown towards [[Mill Woods Town Centre, Edmonton (community)|Mill Woods]].<ref name=\"ValleyPage\">{{cite news |url=http://www.edmonton.ca/transportation/ets/future_transit/southeast-to-west-lrt-mill-woods-to-lewis-farms.aspx |title=Valley Line (SE to West LRT): Mill Woods to Lewis Farms |publisher=[[Edmonton Transit System]] |year=2015 |accessdate=June 16, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150515191330/http://www.edmonton.ca/transportation/ets/future_transit/southeast-to-west-lrt-mill-woods-to-lewis-farms.aspx |archivedate=May 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ValleyVideo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QTCDue8Lf0g |title=Valley Line LRT Animation |publisher=City of Edmonton |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref>\nExtensions to the Capital, Metro, and Valley lines have been approved. The construction of the new Energy and Festival lines have been proposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edmonton.ca/projects_plans/transit/lrt-network-plan.aspx|title=Building LRT|website=City of Edmonton|url-status=live|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n===Montreal===\n[[File:AMTSBLG.JPG|right|thumb|An [[Exo (public transit)|Exo]] train on the [[Mont-Saint-Hilaire line]].]]\n{{main|Exo (public transit)|Montreal Metro}}\nExo operates six commuter rail lines in Greater Montreal, including the [[Island of Montreal]], [[North Shore (Montreal)|Montreal]], and [[South Shore (Montreal)|South Shore]]. Each lines terminate at [[Montreal Central Station]] or [[Lucien-L'Allier station (Exo)|Lucien-L'Allier]], both in downtown Montreal with connections to the metro system. Exo owns the [[Mount Royal Tunnel]] and [[Deux-Montagnes line]], while most of the rest of the system is run on [[Canadian National Railway|Canadian National]] or [[Canadian Pacific Railway|Canadian Pacific]] trackage. The [[R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain]] light metro system is set to takeover the Mount Royal Tunnel and Deux-Montagnes line.\n\n[[File:Metro de la Concorde.jpg|right|thumb|[[Montreal Metro]] train arriving at [[De La Concorde station]].]]\nThe Montreal Metro is Canada's second busiest rail transit system. Drawing inspiration from the [[Paris M\u00e9tro]], it uses [[Rubber-tyred metro|rubber-tired metro]] technology, the only such system in Canada. The {{convert|69.2|km|abbr=on}} system has 68 stations on four lines, which serve the north, east, and central portions of the [[Island of Montreal]], as well as the suburbs of [[Laval, Quebec|Laval]] and [[Longueuil]]. The metro began in 1966 with the east-west [[Green Line (Montreal Metro)|Green Line]] and north-south [[Orange Line (Montreal Metro)|Orange Line]].<ref>{{cite web |title=An underground railway project in 1910 |url=http://www.stm.info/english/en-bref/a-project.htm |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de transport de Montr\u00e9al |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070901223559/http://stm.info/English/en-bref/a-project.htm |archivedate=2007-09-01}}</ref>  A series of expansions since 1966 have expanded the original lines and added the [[Yellow Line (Montreal Metro)|Yellow]] and [[Blue Line (Montreal Metro)|Blue]] lines.\n* The Green Line is a {{convert|22.1|km|abbr=on}} line that runs northeast to southwest between [[Angrignon station|Agrignon]] and [[Honor\u00e9-Beaugrand station|Honor\u00e9-Beaugrand]]. The two ends are connected through a central section that runs under [[De Maisonneuve Boulevard]] in downtown Montreal.\n* The Orange Line is a {{convert|30.0|km|abbr=on}} U-shaped line. The central section runs through downtown Montreal, south of the Green Line's alignment. The two legs connect to [[C\u00f4te-Vertu station|C\u00f4te-Vertu]] in the northwest and [[Montmorency station (Montreal Metro)|Montmorency]] in Laval, northeast of Montreal.\n* The Yellow Line {{convert|4.25|km|abbr=on}} line. It connects to the Green and Orange lines at [[Berri-UQAM station]], the system's busiest station, and crossed under the [[Saint Lawrence River]] to connect [[Saint Helen's Island]] and Longueuil.\n* The Blue Line is a {{convert|9.7|km|abbr=on}} line. It runs in a northeast to southwest alignment north of the Green Line, connecting the east island with both legs of the Orange Line.\nAn eastward extension of the Blue Line is planned.\n\n===Ottawa===\n[[Image:otrain.jpg|thumb|[[Trillium Line]] train on Ottawa's [[O-Train]].]]\n{{main|O-Train}}\nThe [[O-Train]] began in 2001 as a light rail pilot project to supplement its [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Transitway]] bus rapid transit system. This original line, now known as the [[Trillium Line]] was relatively inexpensive to construct ($21&nbsp;million) due to its single-track route along a little used freight-rail right of way and use of [[diesel multiple unit]]s (DMUs) to avoid the cost of building [[overhead lines]] along the tracks. The [[Confederation Line]] opened in September 2019, replacing portions of the Transitway with an underground tunnel through downtown.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/o-train-name-approved-for-ottawa-light-rail-system-1.2769049 |title=O-Train name approved for Ottawa light rail system |newspaper=[[CBC News Network]] |date=September 17, 2014 |accessdate=December 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obj.ca/article/confederation-line-lrt-service-start-september-watson|title=Confederation Line LRT service to start in September: Watson|work=Ottawa Business Journal|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Confederation Line]], (Line 1) is a light rail line which runs east\u2013west from [[Blair station|Blair]] to [[Tunney's Pasture station|Tunney's Pasture]] connecting to the Transitway at each terminus and with the [[Trillium Line]] at [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview]]. The line runs both underground and on the surface and is completely grade-separated. There is a tunnel downtown with three underground stations.<ref name=\"CityConfLine\">{{cite news|url=http://ottawa.ca/en/residents/transportation-and-parking/oc-transpo-and-public-transit/confederation-line|title=Confederation Line|accessdate=June 15, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613042210/http://ottawa.ca/en/residents/transportation-and-parking/oc-transpo-and-public-transit/confederation-line|archivedate=June 13, 2015|publisher=City of Ottawa|year=2015}}</ref>\n* The [[Trillium Line]], (Line 2) is an {{convert|8|km|abbr=on}} diesel light rail line running north to south from [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview station]] to [[Greenboro station]] connecting with Confederation Line at its northern terminus and Transitway at its southern terminus. There are three passing sidings along the single-track line.\nStage 2 of Ottawa's O-Train expansion is currently under construction, which will expand the Confederation Line east and west and the Trillium Line in the south.\n\n===Toronto===\n[[File:GO_Transit_Bombardier_Bilevel_CEM_322.JPG|right|thumb|A [[GO Transit]] train at [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]]]\n{{main|GO Transit|Union Pearson Express|Toronto subway|Toronto streetcar system|Link Train}}\n[[GO Transit]] operates commuter rail services in the Greater [[Golden Horseshoe]], including the metropolitan areas of Toronto, Hamilton, Kitchener, Niagara, Oshawa, Barrie, and Guelph. Each of its seven lines terminate at [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] in downtown Toronto. With 217,500 average weekday riders, it is Canada's busiest commuter rail service, and the fifth busiest in North America. The [[GO Transit Regional Express Rail|GO Expansion]] project currently underway will bring electrification, new trackage, bridges, and tunnels to the system, allowing for two-way all-day service with 15 minute frequencies to sections of five of its lines.\n\n[[File:Union Pearson Express.JPG|right|thumb|A [[Union Pearson Express|UP Express]] train at [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]]]\nGO Transit's parent agency, [[Metrolinx]], also operates the [[Union Pearson Express]], an [[airport rail link]] between Union Station and [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]]. It opened in advance of the [[2015 Pan American Games]], sharing most of its routing with GO's [[Kitchener line]] before travelling along a {{convert|3.3|km|abbr=on}} rail spur to the airport. At the airport, the line connects with the [[Link Train]], a free people mover transporting passenger between the airport's terminals and parking garage.\n\n[[File:St George TTC Rocket.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Toronto Rocket]] subway train at St. George station]]\nThe [[Toronto Transit Commission]]'s {{convert|76.9|km|abbr=on}} [[Toronto subway|subway]] is Canada's oldest rapid transit system, having opened as the \"Yonge subway\" in 1954.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toronto.ca/archives/canada_first_subway/index_subway.htm |title=Canada's First Subway |publisher=City of Toronto |accessdate=2007-02-25}}</ref> It is also Canada's busiest system, with 1,603,300 average weekday riders.<ref name=\"Q4\"/> It is an intermodal system, with three subway lines and one [[Medium-capacity rail system|light metro]] line, with a total of 75 stations, the most of any Canadian system. The system connects each of Toronto's community council areas and [[Amalgamation of Toronto|former municipalities]], as well as the suburb of [[Vaughan]].\n*[[Line 1 Yonge\u2013University]] is Toronto's oldest, longest, and busiest. It forms a U-shape, with [[Union station (TTC)|Union station]], at its base, connecting to Toronto's intercity and commuter rail hub,. The eastern leg travels north along [[Yonge Street]] to [[Finch station|Finch]]. The western leg travels northwest, connecting to the [[University of Toronto]] and [[York University]], before terminating at [[Vaughan Metropolitan Centre station|Vaughan Metropolitan Centre]].\n*[[Line 2 Bloor\u2013Danforth]] is an east-west line, running primarily along its two namesakes, [[Bloor Street]] and [[Danforth Avenue]]. The line connects the east and western suburbs with Line 1 and downtown Toronto.\n*[[Line 3 Scarborough]] is a light metro line. It connects the former municipality of [[Scarborough, Ontario|Scarborough]] with Line 2 at its terminus at [[Kennedy station]]. The line is planned to be replaced with an extension of Line 2.<ref name=\"star\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2020/03/05/eight-major-transit-projects-are-underway-in-the-gta-heres-where-theyre-at-right-now.html|title=Eight major transit projects are underway in the GTA \u2014 here\u2019s where they\u2019re at right now|last=Hall|first=Joseph|date=March 5, 2020|website=Toronto Star|url-status=live|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Line 4 Sheppard]] is the shortest line on the system, with five stations along [[Sheppard Avenue]] in [[North York]]. It connects to Line 1 at [[Sheppard\u2013Yonge station]].\n[[Line 5 Eglinton]] and [[Line 6 Finch West]] are both light rail lines under construction. The two lines will be fully integrated with the subway system upon opening in 2021.<ref name=\"star\"/>\n\n[[File:King Street Pilot Project - Planters & furniture near Charlotte St.jpg|right|thumb|[[504 King]] streetcar operating along the [[King Street Transit Priority Corridor]]]]\nToronto also operates a [[Toronto streetcar system|streetcar system]]. Unlike light rail, the majority of the ten routes operate in mixed traffic and all make frequent stops. Three routes operate in a dedicated right-of-way:\n* [[510 Spadina]] running between [[Spadina station]] and [[Union station (TTC)|Union station]].\n* [[509 Harbourfront]] running between Union station and [[Exhibition Place]] via [[Queens Quay station]].\n* [[512 St. Clair]] running along [[St. Clair Avenue]] West between [[St. Clair station]] and [[Gunns Loop]] via [[St. Clair West station]].\nThe central section of the [[504 King]] route runs along the [[King Street Transit Priority Corridor]]. The proposed [[East Bayfront LRT]] would be a fourth streetcar line operating in a dedicated right-of-way.\n\n===Vancouver===\n{{main|West Coast Express|SkyTrain (Vancouver)}}\nThe [[West Coast Express]] is a commuter rail line operated by [[TransLink (British Columbia)|TransLink]]. The {{Convert|69|km|mi|abbr=on}} line runs from [[Waterfront station (Vancouver)|Waterfront station]] in downtown Vancouver to [[Mission, British Columbia|Mission]], with six stations in between. The line only operates during peak hours on weekdays, with five trains in each direction. It is Canada's least used urban rail transit system.<ref name=\"Q4\"/>\n\n[[File:29th Avenue platform level (20190626 123343).jpg|thumb|rightalt=Vancouver SkyTrain at 29th Avenue station platform|The longest rapid transit system in Canada by track length is the Vancouver [[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]].]]\nThe SkyTrain is TransLink's fully-automated light metro system. The system opened in 1985 for the [[Expo 86]]. This original portion, now known as the [[Expo Line (SkyTrain)|Expo Line]], is also joined by the [[Millennium Line|Millennium]] and [[Canada Line|Canada]] lines, making it Canada's longest by track length, at {{convert|79.6|km|abbr=on}}. The system serves Vancouvers and many of its surrounding municipalities in the [[Metro Vancouver Regional District]].\n*The [[Expo Line (SkyTrain)|Expo Line]] is named after Expo 86, for which it was originally constructed. It connects [[Waterfront station (Vancouver)|Waterfront station]], an intermodal transit station in Downtown Vancouver, with [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]]. Since 2016, a second branch of the line connects to the Millennium Line in [[Burnaby]].<ref name=\"Evergreen\">{{cite web |url=http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/vancouver/ |title=Vancouver SkyTrain, Canada |website=Railway-Technology.com |accessdate=2015-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.news1130.com/2016/12/02/evergreen-extension-opening-today/ |title=Evergreen Extension opening today |date=2016-12-02 |website=NEWS 1130|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n*The [[Millenium Line]] is named after the [[3rd millennium]] in which it was opened. Originally, it operated as a branch service of the Expo Line, following its alignment from Waterfront to [[Columbia station (SkyTrain)|Columbia station]], before branching off. The opening of the [[Evergreen Extension]] in 2016 brought its current alignment, running roughly east-west from [[VCC\u2013Clark station]] in Vancouver to [[Lafarge Lake\u2013Douglas station]] in [[Coquitlam]].<ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> An [[Millennium Line Broadway extension|additional extension]] is planned along [[Broadway (Vancouver)|Broadway]] to [[Arbutus station]].\n*The [[Canada Line]] was built in advance of the [[2010 Winter Olympics]]. It uses distinct technology from the rest of the system, and runs south from Waterfront station to the [[Vancouver International Airport|airport]] and [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]].\n\n===Waterloo===\n[[File:Ion Flexity Freedom 514 service livery.jpg|thumb|Ion LRV on Northfield Drive in Waterloo]]\n{{main|Ion rapid transit}}\nThe first phase of the {{convert|19|km|adj=on}} LRT system runs from [[Conestoga station]] in [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] to [[Fairway station]] in [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]. It opened to the public on June 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grt.ca/en/ion-light-rail.aspx |title=ION light rail |date=April 16, 2019 |website=grt.ca |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> The system operates in reserved lanes on public streets and on private rights of way. [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region, Ontario]] has also approved plans for a light rail extension to the [[Ainslie St. Transit Terminal]] in [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]], as phase two of Ion.<ref name=\"Irj2013-07-12\">{{cite journal |first=Douglas John |last=Bowen |url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/light-rail/waterloo-opts-for-bombardier-lrvs.html?channel=542 |title=Waterloo opts for Bombardier LRVs |journal=[[International Railway Journal]] |date=July 12, 2013 |accessdate=July 13, 2013 |archivedate=July 13, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.railjournal.com%2Findex.php%2Flight-rail%2Fwaterloo-opts-for-bombardier-lrvs.html%3Fchannel%3D542&date=2013-07-13 |url-status=live |quote=The first of the Flexity Freedom LRV are due to be delivered in mid-2016, and will be used on the 19km, 16-station line from Conestoga Mall in Waterloo to Fairview Park Mall in Kitchener. The $C 92.4m ($US 89.2m) contract will include an option for 16 additional vehicles.}}</ref>\n\n==In development==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! City or region\n! Line \n! Construction start \n! Expected opening\n! Stations\n! Line length\n! Status\n|-\n| [[Calgary]]\n| [[Green Line (Calgary)|Green Line (stage 1)]]{{efn|name=Green|Only phase 1 which spans from 16 Avenue N to 126 Avenue SE (About 14 stations and {{convert|20|km}}).}}\n| 2020\n| 2026{{efn|Depends on delivery of funding promised by federal and provincial governments during recent elections.}}\n| {{nts|14}}{{efn|name=Stations|When fully complete the Green Line will have 28 Stations}}\n| {{convert|20|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}{{efn|name=Km|When the Green Line is complete it will be {{convert|48|km}} long.}}\n| Planned\n|-\n| [[Edmonton]]\n| [[Valley Line (Edmonton)|Valley Line Southeast]]{{efn|name=Valley|Data for Valley Line phase 1 only from Mill Woods to 102 Street.}}\n| 2016<ref name=\"ValleyPage\" />\n| 2020<ref name=\"ValleyPage\" />\n| {{nts|12}}<ref name=\"ValleyVideo\" />\n| {{convert|13.1|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}<ref name=\"ValleyVideo\" />\n| Under construction<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edmonton.ca/ets/transit_projects/southeast-to-west-lrt-mill-woods-to-lewis-farms.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=June 16, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209095715/http://www.edmonton.ca/ets/transit_projects/southeast-to-west-lrt-mill-woods-to-lewis-farms.aspx |archivedate=February 9, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| Edmonton\n| [[Valley Line (Edmonton)|Valley Line West]]\n|2020\n|2025{{efn|name=phased|Council is looking into the possibility of opening the line in phases between 2020 and 2025. For example the first parts of the line closer to downtown could open in 2020 while sections near the end of line could open closer to 2025 .}}\n| {{nts|16}}\n| {{convert|14|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Planned\n|-\n| [[Gatineau]]\n| [[Gatineau LRT]]\n| \n| 2028\n| {{nts|30}}\n| {{convert|26|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Proposed\n|-\n| [[Montreal]]\n| [[R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain]]\n| 2018\n| 2021\u20132023\n| {{nts|26}}\n| {{convert|67|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Under construction\n|-\n|[[Ottawa]]\n|[[Confederation Line#Stage 2 extension|Confederation Line (Stage 2)]]\n|2019\n|2024\u20132025\n|{{nts|16}}{{efn|When Stage 2 is complete, the Confederation Line will have 29 stations.}}\n|{{convert|26.5|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}{{efn|When Stage 2 is complete, the Confederation Line will be {{convert|39|km}} long.}}\n| Under construction<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/news/stage-2-o-train-light-rail-transit-project-construction-summary-east-extension-june-through-december-2019/|title=Stage 2 O-Train Light Rail Transit Project Construction Summary|work=City of Ottawa|date=September 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|Ottawa\n|[[Trillium Line#Stage 2|Trillium Line (Stage 2)]] \n|2019\n|2022\n|{{nts|8}}{{efn|When Stage 2 is complete, the Trillium Line will have 13 stations.}}\n|{{convert|14|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}{{efn|When Stage 2 is complete, the Trillium Line will be {{convert|22|km}} long.}}\n| Under construction<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/city-of-ottawa-receives-update-on-the-latest-of-stage-2-of-lrt-1.4586729|title=City of Ottawa receives update on the latest of Stage 2 of LRT|work=CTV News|date=September 10, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]]\n| [[Hurontario LRT]]\n| 2020<ref name=\"update\">https://www.railwayage.com/news/ontario-lrt-update/</ref>\n| 2024\n| {{nts|19}}\n| {{convert|18|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}<ref name=\"Metro-2015-10-28\" />\n| Planned\n|-\n| [[Quebec City]]\n| [[Quebec City Tramway]]\n| \n| 2026\n| {{nts|35}}\n| {{convert|23|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Planned\n|-\n| [[Toronto]]\n| [[Line 5 Eglinton]]\n| 2011\n| 2022<ref name=\"CBC-delay-2022\">{{cite web |title=Eglinton Crosstown LRT won't be ready until 'well into 2022,' Metrolinx says |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/eglinton-crosstown-lrt-open-2022-1.5466847 |website=CBC News |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{nts|26}}\n| {{convert|19|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Under construction\n|-\n| Toronto\n| [[Line 6 Finch West]]\n| 2019<ref name=\"update\" />\n| 2023\n| {{nts|18}}\n| {{convert|11|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Under construction\n|}\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n===Gatineau===\n{{main|Gatineau LRT}}\n[[Gatineau]], [[Quebec]] is proposing a {{convert|26|km|adj=on}} LRT system that would connect with Ottawa's O-Train system.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gatineau reveals $2.1B LRT plan, eyes 2028 launch |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/gatineau-aylmer-ottawa-light-rail-1.4713843 |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |work=CBC News |date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n===Montreal===\n{{main|R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain}}\nThe [[R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain]] is a light metro line under construction in Montreal. It is set to open in phases beginning in 2021. When completed, it will comprise of a central section connecting to the Green, Orange, and Blue metro lines, with four branches with service to the [[North Shore (Montreal)|North Shore]], [[West Island]], [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau International Airport|airport]], and [[South Shore (Montreal)|South Shore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citymetric.com/transport/r-seau-express-m-tropolitain-multi-billion-dollar-light-rail-project-montreal-never-asked|title=The R\u00e9seau Express M\u00e9tropolitain: the multi-billion dollar light rail project Montreal never asked for|last=Noakes|first=Taylor|date=November 13, 2019|website=CityMetric|url-status=live|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n===Peel Region===\n{{main|Hurontario LRT}}\nThe Hurontario LRT is a proposed {{convert|17.6|km|adj=on}} light rail line largely financed by the province of [[Ontario]] to run on the surface along [[Hurontario Street]] from [[Port Credit GO Station]] in [[Mississauga]] to Steeles Avenue in [[Brampton]]. On October 28, 2015, Brampton City Council cancelled the proposed {{convert|5.6|km|adj=on}} section of the line along [[Main Street (Brampton)|Main Street]] in [[Brampton]] to [[Brampton GO Station]].<ref name=\"Metro-2015-10-28\">{{cite news |url=http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2015/10/28/brampton-council-rejects-lrt.html |title=Brampton council votes to reject provincially approved LRT |newspaper=Metro News |date=October 28, 2015 |accessdate=October 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208153340/http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2015/10/28/brampton-council-rejects-lrt.html |archive-date=December 8, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On March 21, 2019, Metrolinx announced that the most of the downtown loop would be deferred to a later date due to financial restrictions, although a short spur and stop on Rathburn would remain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/03/21/metrolinx-scraps-portion-of-hurontario-lrt-in-effort-to-cut-costs.html |title=Metrolinx scraps portion of Hurontario LRT in effort to cut costs {{!}} The Star|website=Toronto Star |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n===Quebec City===\n{{main|Quebec City Tramway}}\nThe Quebec City Tramway is a planned light rail transit line in Quebec City set to open in 2026. It will link [[Charlesbourg, Quebec City|Charlesbourg]] to [[Cap-Rouge, Quebec City|Cap Rouge]], passing through [[Parliament Hill (Quebec City)|Quebec Parliament Hill]]. The {{convert|23|km|adj=on}} line will include a {{convert|3.5|km|adj=on}} underground segment, with the rest of the line being on the surface.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/mayor-premier-unveil-plans-for-3-billion-tramway-for-quebec-city|title=Mayor, premier unveil plans for $3-billion tramway for Quebec City|date=March 16, 2018|work=Montreal Gazette|access-date=July 8, 2019|agency=Presse Canadienne}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of bus rapid transit systems in the Americas#Canada]]\n*[[Public transport in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian passenger rail systems}}\n\n[[Category:Transport in Canada]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|List of Canadian passenger rail systems confined to urban areas}}\n[[Urban rail transit]] in Canada encompasses a broad range of rail mass transit systems, including [[commuter rail]], [[rapid transit]], [[light rail]], and [[streetcar]] systems.\n\n==Terminology==\n{{detail|Passenger rail terminology}}\n* '''Commuter rail''' refers to urban passenger train service between a central city and its suburbs. Three such systems exist in Canada.\n* '''Airport rail link''' refers to rail transport between a central city and its airport. The [[Union Pearson Express]] is the only dedicated airport rail link in Canada. The [[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]] light metro system also serves as an airport rail link.\n* '''Subway''' refers to a rapid transit system using heavy rail with steel wheels. The [[Toronto subway]] is the only such system in Canada.\n* '''Rubber-tired metro''' refers to a rapid transit system using heavy rail with rubber tires. The [[Montreal Metro]] is the only such system in Canada.\n* '''Light metro''' refers to a rapid transit system using intermediate or medium-capacity rail. The SkyTrain is the only full light metro system in Canada. The Toronto subway system includes one light metro line.\n* '''Light rail''' refers to a rail transit system using light rail vehicles in a dedicated [[Right-of-way (transportation)|right-of-way]]. Four such systems exist in Canada.\n* '''Streetcar''' refers to a rail transit system using light rail vehicles entirely or mostly on streets providing local service in mixed traffic. The [[Toronto streetcar system|Toronto streetcar]] is the only such system in Canada.\n* '''People mover''' refers to a small-scale [[automated guideway transit]] system. The [[Link Train]] is the only such system in Canada.\n\n==Existing systems==\n''Italics'' indicate a line under construction.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Region\n!System\n!Average weekday</br>ridership (Q4 2019)<ref name=\"Q4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/2019-Q4-Ridership-APTA.pdf|title=PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION RIDERSHIP REPORT: Fourth Quarter 2019|date=February 27, 2020|website=American Public Transit Association|url-status=live|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n!Technology\n!Lines\n!Stations\n!System length\n!Stations under construction\n!System length</br>under construction\n|-\n|[[Calgary]], Alberta\n|[[CTrain]]\n|{{nts|313800}}\n|[[Light rail]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|calgary|red}} [[Red Line (Calgary)|Red Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|calgary|blue}} [[Blue Line (Calgary)|Blue Line]]\n|45\n|{{Convert|59.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Edmonton]], Alberta\n|[[Edmonton Light Rail Transit|Edmonton LRT]]\n|{{nts|110786}}<br>(2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edmonton.ca/transportation/PDF/2018-LRT-Passenger-Count-Report.pdf|title=2018 LRT Passenger Count Report|date=March 2019|website=City of Edmonton|url-status=live|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Light rail]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|edmonton|capital}} [[Capital Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|edmonton|metro}} [[Metro Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|edmonton|valley}} ''[[Valley Line (Edmonton)|Valley Line]]''\n|18\n|{{Convert|24.3|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|12\n|{{Convert|13.1|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Greater Montreal]], Quebec\n|[[Exo (public transit)|Exo]]\n|{{nts|68500}}<br>(Q3 2019)<ref name=\"Q3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.apta.com/wp-content/uploads/2019-Q3-Ridership-APTA.pdf|title=PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION RIDERSHIP REPORT: Fourth Quarter 2019|date=November 27, 2019|website=American Public Transit Association|url-status=live|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Commuter rail]]\n|\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Candiac|x}} [[Candiac line|Candiac]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Deux-Montagnes|x}} [[Deux-Montagnes line|Deux-Montagnes]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Vaudreuil-Hudson|x}} [[Vaudreuil-Hudson line|Vaudreuil-Hudson]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Mascouche|x}} [[Mascouche line|Mascouche]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Mont-Saint-Hilaire|x}} [[Mont-Saint-Hilaire line|Mont-Saint-Hilaire]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|rail|Saint-Jerome|x}} [[Saint-Jerome line|Saint-Jerome]]\n|62\n|{{Convert|234.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Montreal Metro]]\n|{{nts|1421200}}\n|[[Rubber-tyred metro|Rubber-tired metro]]\n|\n{{rint|montreal|metro|1}} [[Green Line (Montreal Metro)|Green Line]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|metro|2}} [[Orange Line (Montreal Metro)|Orange Line]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|metro|4}} [[Yellow Line (Montreal Metro)|Yellow Line]]<br>\n{{rint|montreal|metro|5}} [[Blue Line (Montreal Metro)|Blue Line]]\n|68\n|{{Convert|69.2|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Ottawa]], Ontario\n|[[O-Train]]\n|{{nts|13000}}<br>(Q3 2019)<ref name=\"Q3\"/>\n|[[Light rail]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|ottawa|1}} [[Confederation Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|ottawa|2}} [[Trillium Line]]\n|18\n|{{Convert|20.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|24\n|{{Convert|40.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"7\"|[[Greater Toronto Area]], Ontario\n|[[GO Transit]]\n|{{nts|230500}}\n|[[Commuter rail]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|gotransit|rail|A|x}} [[Lakeshore West line|Lakeshore West]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|gotransit|rail|B|x}} [[Lakeshore East line|Lakeshore East]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|gotransit|rail|C|x}} [[Milton line|Milton]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|gotransit|rail|D|x}} [[Kitchener line|Kitchener]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|gotransit|rail|E|x}} [[Barrie line|Barrie]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|gotransit|rail|F|x}} [[Richmond Hill line|Richmond Hill]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|gotransit|rail|G|x}} [[Stouffville line|Stouffville]]\n|68\n|{{Convert|522.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|4\n||{{Convert|4|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|[[Union Pearson Express]]\n|{{nts|11500}}<br>(April 2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metrolinx.files.wordpress.com/2019/06/click-here-to-view-the-map-in-detail.pdf|title=YEAR-OVER-YEAR (YoY) RIDERSHIP PERFORMANCE: GO Train and UP Express April 2019 Compared to April 2018|website=Metrolinx|url-status=live|access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Airport rail link]]\n|{{rail-interchange|toronto|up}} [[Union Pearson Express|UP Express]]\n|4\n|{{Convert|23.3|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Toronto subway]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{nts|1603300}}\n|[[Rapid transit|Subway]]\n|\n{{nowrap|{{rail-interchange|toronto|1}} [[Line 1 Yonge\u2013University]]}}<br>\n{{nowrap|{{rail-interchange|toronto|2}} [[Line 2 Bloor\u2013Danforth]]}}<br>\n{{rail-interchange|toronto|4}} [[Line 4 Sheppard]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|75\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{Convert|76.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|rowspan=\"3\"|39\n|rowspan=\"3\"|{{Convert|30|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|[[Medium-capacity rail system|Light metro]]\n|{{rail-interchange|toronto|3}} [[Line 3 Scarborough]]\n|-\n|[[Light rail]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|toronto|5}} ''[[Line 5 Eglinton]]''<br>\n{{rail-interchange|toronto|6}} ''[[Line 6 Finch West]]''\n|-\n|[[Toronto streetcar system|Toronto streetcar]]\n|{{nts|530600}}\n|[[Tram|Streetcar]]\n|[[Toronto_streetcar_system#Routes|List]]\n|685\n|{{Convert|83|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Link Train]]\n|\n|[[People mover]]\n|\u2013\n|3\n|{{Convert|1.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Metro Vancouver Regional District|Metro Vancouver]], British Columbia\n|[[West Coast Express]]\n|{{nts|10300}}\n|[[Commuter rail]]\n|{{rail-interchange|vancouver|wce}} [[West Coast Express]]\n|8\n|{{Convert|69|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]]\n|{{nts|512400}}\n|[[Medium-capacity rail system|Light metro]]\n|\n{{rail-interchange|vancouver|expo}} [[Expo Line (SkyTrain)|Expo Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|vancouver|millennium}} [[Millennium Line]]<br>\n{{rail-interchange|vancouver|canada}} [[Canada Line]]\n|53\n|{{Convert|79.6|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|-\n|[[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region]], Ontario\n|[[Ion rapid transit|Ion]]\n|\u2013\n|[[Light rail]]\n|{{rail-interchange|waterloo|ion}} [[Ion rapid transit|Ion]]\n|19\n|{{Convert|19|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|\u2013\n|\u2013\n|}\n\n===Calgary===\n[[File:Calgary_Transit_S200.jpg|right|thumb|Siemens S200 train at the [[CTrain]]'s [[Saddletowne station]]]]\n{{main|CTrain}}\n[[Calgary Transit]]'s CTrain network, which started operation in 1981, now has the second highest weekday ridership of any light rail transit system in North America, carrying over 312,000 passengers per weekday in the fourth quarter of 2018. There are [[CTrain#List of CTrain stations|45 stations]] in operation in the {{convert|60|km|mi|adj=on}} [[CTrain]] light rail system,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.calgary.ca/Transportation/TI/Pages/Transit-projects/Northwest-LRT-Extension-to-Rocky-Ridge---Tuscany.aspx |title=Northwest LRT extension to Rocky Ridge/Tuscany |work=Calgary Transit |publisher=The City of Calgary |year=2014 |accessdate=August 4, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824224447/http://www.calgary.ca/Transportation/TI/Pages/Transit-projects/Northwest-LRT-Extension-to-Rocky-Ridge---Tuscany.aspx |archivedate=August 24, 2012}}</ref> After starting by running on one leg in 1981, the system has expanded and now has four legs radiating out into Calgary's suburbs in different directions. The legs have been organized into two routes (identified as the Red Line and the Blue Line) that connect the four legs via shared tracks in a downtown [[transit mall]]. The existing four legs of the system, as built in chronological order, are the South leg (1981), the Northeast leg (1985), the Northwest leg (1987), and the West leg (2012). \n* The Downtown Transit Mall along 7th Avenue South is shared by the Red and Blue lines.\n* The [[Red Line (Calgary)|Red Line]] connects the South and Northwest legs via the downtown transit mall.\n* The [[Blue Line (Calgary)|Blue Line]] connects the Northeast and West legs via the downtown transit mall.\nThe [[Green Line (Calgary)|Green Line]] is a planned line that would connect new Southeast and North legs via a downtown tunnel.<ref name=\"Green\">{{cite web |url=http://www.calgary.ca/Transportation/TI/Pages/Transit-projects/Green-line/vision.aspx |title=Vision for Green Line |publisher=Calgary Transit | access-date = May 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Edmonton===\n[[File:Bay-Enterprise Square LRT Station (20581703943).jpg|right|thumb|Siemens SD-160 train at the [[Edmonton LRT]]'s [[Bay/Enterprise Square station]]]]\n{{main|Edmonton LRT}}\nThe [[Edmonton Transit System]]'s LRT system consisted of only one line from its opening in 1978 to 2015. The current {{convert|24.3|km|mi|adj=on}} system includes the original [[Capital Line]] and the new [[Metro Line]], sharing most of their route. The first phase of the [[Valley Line (Edmonton)|Valley Line]] is under construction.\n* The Capital Line runs roughly north-south, between northeast Edmonton and the [[Century Park station (Edmonton)|Century Park]] community, with a mix of tunnels and at-grade track. Six stations are underground, while the remaining nine are at-grade.\n* The Metro Line is interlined with the Capital Line from Century Park and through the underground portions before branching northwest towards [[NAIT station|NAIT]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/2015/01/21/edmontons-metro-line-now-set-to-open-in-spring |title=Edmonton's Metro Line now set to open in spring |accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Sun130509\">{{cite web |last=Dykstra |first=Matt |title=Edmonton city crews promise to finish north extension of LRT line to NAIT by next spring |url=http://www.edmontonsun.com/2013/05/09/edmonton-city-crews-promise-to-finish-north-extension-of-lrt-line-to-nait-by-next-spring |work=Edmonton Sun |accessdate=August 26, 2013 |date=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n* The Valley Line is currently under construction. The low-floor line will travel southeast from downtown towards [[Mill Woods Town Centre, Edmonton (community)|Mill Woods]].<ref name=\"ValleyPage\">{{cite news |url=http://www.edmonton.ca/transportation/ets/future_transit/southeast-to-west-lrt-mill-woods-to-lewis-farms.aspx |title=Valley Line (SE to West LRT): Mill Woods to Lewis Farms |publisher=[[Edmonton Transit System]] |year=2015 |accessdate=June 16, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150515191330/http://www.edmonton.ca/transportation/ets/future_transit/southeast-to-west-lrt-mill-woods-to-lewis-farms.aspx |archivedate=May 15, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ValleyVideo\">{{cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QTCDue8Lf0g |title=Valley Line LRT Animation |publisher=City of Edmonton |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref>\nExtensions to the Capital, Metro, and Valley lines have been approved. The construction of the new Energy and Festival lines have been proposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edmonton.ca/projects_plans/transit/lrt-network-plan.aspx|title=Building LRT|website=City of Edmonton|url-status=live|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n===Montreal===\n[[File:AMTSBLG.JPG|right|thumb|An [[Exo (public transit)|Exo]] train on the [[Mont-Saint-Hilaire line]].]]\n{{main|Exo (public transit)|Montreal Metro}}\nExo operates six commuter rail lines in Greater Montreal, including the [[Island of Montreal]], [[North Shore (Montreal)|Montreal]], and [[South Shore (Montreal)|South Shore]]. Each lines terminate at [[Montreal Central Station]] or [[Lucien-L'Allier station (Exo)|Lucien-L'Allier]], both in downtown Montreal with connections to the metro system. Exo owns the [[Mount Royal Tunnel]] and [[Deux-Montagnes line]], while most of the rest of the system is run on [[Canadian National Railway|Canadian National]] or [[Canadian Pacific Railway|Canadian Pacific]] trackage. The [[R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain]] light metro system is set to takeover the Mount Royal Tunnel and Deux-Montagnes line.\n\n[[File:Metro de la Concorde.jpg|right|thumb|[[Montreal Metro]] train arriving at [[De La Concorde station]].]]\nThe Montreal Metro is Canada's second busiest rail transit system. Drawing inspiration from the [[Paris M\u00e9tro]], it uses [[Rubber-tyred metro|rubber-tired metro]] technology, the only such system in Canada. The {{convert|69.2|km|abbr=on}} system has 68 stations on four lines, which serve the north, east, and central portions of the [[Island of Montreal]], as well as the suburbs of [[Laval, Quebec|Laval]] and [[Longueuil]]. The metro began in 1966 with the east-west [[Green Line (Montreal Metro)|Green Line]] and north-south [[Orange Line (Montreal Metro)|Orange Line]].<ref>{{cite web |title=An underground railway project in 1910 |url=http://www.stm.info/english/en-bref/a-project.htm |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de transport de Montr\u00e9al |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070901223559/http://stm.info/English/en-bref/a-project.htm |archivedate=2007-09-01}}</ref>  A series of expansions since 1966 have expanded the original lines and added the [[Yellow Line (Montreal Metro)|Yellow]] and [[Blue Line (Montreal Metro)|Blue]] lines.\n* The Green Line is a {{convert|22.1|km|abbr=on}} line that runs northeast to southwest between [[Angrignon station|Agrignon]] and [[Honor\u00e9-Beaugrand station|Honor\u00e9-Beaugrand]]. The two ends are connected through a central section that runs under [[De Maisonneuve Boulevard]] in downtown Montreal.\n* The Orange Line is a {{convert|30.0|km|abbr=on}} U-shaped line. The central section runs through downtown Montreal, south of the Green Line's alignment. The two legs connect to [[C\u00f4te-Vertu station|C\u00f4te-Vertu]] in the northwest and [[Montmorency station (Montreal Metro)|Montmorency]] in Laval, northeast of Montreal.\n* The Yellow Line {{convert|4.25|km|abbr=on}} line. It connects to the Green and Orange lines at [[Berri-UQAM station]], the system's busiest station, and crossed under the [[Saint Lawrence River]] to connect [[Saint Helen's Island]] and Longueuil.\n* The Blue Line is a {{convert|9.7|km|abbr=on}} line. It runs in a northeast to southwest alignment north of the Green Line, connecting the east island with both legs of the Orange Line.\nAn eastward extension of the Blue Line is planned.\n\n===Ottawa===\n[[Image:otrain.jpg|thumb|[[Trillium Line]] train on Ottawa's [[O-Train]].]]\n{{main|O-Train}}\nThe [[O-Train]] began in 2001 as a light rail pilot project to supplement its [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Transitway]] bus rapid transit system. This original line, now known as the [[Trillium Line]] was relatively inexpensive to construct ($21&nbsp;million) due to its single-track route along a little used freight-rail right of way and use of [[diesel multiple unit]]s (DMUs) to avoid the cost of building [[overhead lines]] along the tracks. The [[Confederation Line]] opened in September 2019, replacing portions of the Transitway with an underground tunnel through downtown.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/o-train-name-approved-for-ottawa-light-rail-system-1.2769049 |title=O-Train name approved for Ottawa light rail system |newspaper=[[CBC News Network]] |date=September 17, 2014 |accessdate=December 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obj.ca/article/confederation-line-lrt-service-start-september-watson|title=Confederation Line LRT service to start in September: Watson|work=Ottawa Business Journal|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n* The [[Confederation Line]], (Line 1) is a light rail line which runs east\u2013west from [[Blair station|Blair]] to [[Tunney's Pasture station|Tunney's Pasture]] connecting to the Transitway at each terminus and with the [[Trillium Line]] at [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview]]. The line runs both underground and on the surface and is completely grade-separated. There is a tunnel downtown with three underground stations.<ref name=\"CityConfLine\">{{cite news|url=http://ottawa.ca/en/residents/transportation-and-parking/oc-transpo-and-public-transit/confederation-line|title=Confederation Line|accessdate=June 15, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613042210/http://ottawa.ca/en/residents/transportation-and-parking/oc-transpo-and-public-transit/confederation-line|archivedate=June 13, 2015|publisher=City of Ottawa|year=2015}}</ref>\n* The [[Trillium Line]], (Line 2) is an {{convert|8|km|abbr=on}} diesel light rail line running north to south from [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview station]] to [[Greenboro station]] connecting with Confederation Line at its northern terminus and Transitway at its southern terminus. There are three passing sidings along the single-track line.\nStage 2 of Ottawa's O-Train expansion is currently under construction, which will expand the Confederation Line east and west and the Trillium Line in the south.\n\n===Toronto===\n[[File:GO_Transit_Bombardier_Bilevel_CEM_322.JPG|right|thumb|A [[GO Transit]] train at [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]]]\n{{main|GO Transit|Union Pearson Express|Toronto subway|Toronto streetcar system|Link Train}}\n[[GO Transit]] operates commuter rail services in the Greater [[Golden Horseshoe]], including the metropolitan areas of Toronto, Hamilton, Kitchener, Niagara, Oshawa, Barrie, and Guelph. Each of its seven lines terminate at [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]] in downtown Toronto. With 217,500 average weekday riders, it is Canada's busiest commuter rail service, and the fifth busiest in North America. The [[GO Transit Regional Express Rail|GO Expansion]] project currently underway will bring electrification, new trackage, bridges, and tunnels to the system, allowing for two-way all-day service with 15 minute frequencies to sections of five of its lines.\n\n[[File:Union Pearson Express.JPG|right|thumb|A [[Union Pearson Express|UP Express]] train at [[Union Station (Toronto)|Union Station]]]]\nGO Transit's parent agency, [[Metrolinx]], also operates the [[Union Pearson Express]], an [[airport rail link]] between Union Station and [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]]. It opened in advance of the [[2015 Pan American Games]], sharing most of its routing with GO's [[Kitchener line]] before travelling along a {{convert|3.3|km|abbr=on}} rail spur to the airport. At the airport, the line connects with the [[Link Train]], a free people mover transporting passenger between the airport's terminals and parking garage.\n\n[[File:St George TTC Rocket.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Toronto Rocket]] subway train at St. George station]]\nThe [[Toronto Transit Commission]]'s {{convert|76.9|km|abbr=on}} [[Toronto subway|subway]] is Canada's oldest rapid transit system, having opened as the \"Yonge subway\" in 1954.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.toronto.ca/archives/canada_first_subway/index_subway.htm |title=Canada's First Subway |publisher=City of Toronto |accessdate=2007-02-25}}</ref> It is also Canada's busiest system, with 1,603,300 average weekday riders.<ref name=\"Q4\"/> It is an intermodal system, with three subway lines and one [[Medium-capacity rail system|light metro]] line, with a total of 75 stations, the most of any Canadian system. The system connects each of Toronto's community council areas and [[Amalgamation of Toronto|former municipalities]], as well as the suburb of [[Vaughan]].\n*[[Line 1 Yonge\u2013University]] is Toronto's oldest, longest, and busiest. It forms a U-shape, with [[Union station (TTC)|Union station]], at its base, connecting to Toronto's intercity and commuter rail hub,. The eastern leg travels north along [[Yonge Street]] to [[Finch station|Finch]]. The western leg travels northwest, connecting to the [[University of Toronto]] and [[York University]], before terminating at [[Vaughan Metropolitan Centre station|Vaughan Metropolitan Centre]].\n*[[Line 2 Bloor\u2013Danforth]] is an east-west line, running primarily along its two namesakes, [[Bloor Street]] and [[Danforth Avenue]]. The line connects the east and western suburbs with Line 1 and downtown Toronto.\n*[[Line 3 Scarborough]] is a light metro line. It connects the former municipality of [[Scarborough, Ontario|Scarborough]] with Line 2 at its terminus at [[Kennedy station]]. The line is planned to be replaced with an extension of Line 2.<ref name=\"star\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2020/03/05/eight-major-transit-projects-are-underway-in-the-gta-heres-where-theyre-at-right-now.html|title=Eight major transit projects are underway in the GTA \u2014 here\u2019s where they\u2019re at right now|last=Hall|first=Joseph|date=March 5, 2020|website=Toronto Star|url-status=live|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> \n*[[Line 4 Sheppard]] is the shortest line on the system, with five stations along [[Sheppard Avenue]] in [[North York]]. It connects to Line 1 at [[Sheppard\u2013Yonge station]].\n[[Line 5 Eglinton]] and [[Line 6 Finch West]] are both light rail lines under construction. The two lines will be fully integrated with the subway system upon opening in 2021.<ref name=\"star\"/>\n\n[[File:King Street Pilot Project - Planters & furniture near Charlotte St.jpg|right|thumb|[[504 King]] streetcar operating along the [[King Street Transit Priority Corridor]]]]\nToronto also operates a [[Toronto streetcar system|streetcar system]]. Unlike light rail, the majority of the ten routes operate in mixed traffic and all make frequent stops. Three routes operate in a dedicated right-of-way:\n* [[510 Spadina]] running between [[Spadina station]] and [[Union station (TTC)|Union station]].\n* [[509 Harbourfront]] running between Union station and [[Exhibition Place]] via [[Queens Quay station]].\n* [[512 St. Clair]] running along [[St. Clair Avenue]] West between [[St. Clair station]] and [[Gunns Loop]] via [[St. Clair West station]].\nThe central section of the [[504 King]] route runs along the [[King Street Transit Priority Corridor]]. The proposed [[East Bayfront LRT]] would be a fourth streetcar line operating in a dedicated right-of-way.\n\n===Vancouver===\n{{main|West Coast Express|SkyTrain (Vancouver)}}\nThe [[West Coast Express]] is a commuter rail line operated by [[TransLink (British Columbia)|TransLink]]. The {{Convert|69|km|mi|abbr=on}} line runs from [[Waterfront station (Vancouver)|Waterfront station]] in downtown Vancouver to [[Mission, British Columbia|Mission]], with six stations in between. The line only operates during peak hours on weekdays, with five trains in each direction. It is Canada's least used urban rail transit system.<ref name=\"Q4\"/>\n\n[[File:29th Avenue platform level (20190626 123343).jpg|thumb|rightalt=Vancouver SkyTrain at 29th Avenue station platform|The longest rapid transit system in Canada by track length is the Vancouver [[SkyTrain (Vancouver)|SkyTrain]].]]\nThe SkyTrain is TransLink's fully-automated light metro system. The system opened in 1985 for the [[Expo 86]]. This original portion, now known as the [[Expo Line (SkyTrain)|Expo Line]], is also joined by the [[Millennium Line|Millennium]] and [[Canada Line|Canada]] lines, making it Canada's longest by track length, at {{convert|79.6|km|abbr=on}}. The system serves Vancouvers and many of its surrounding municipalities in the [[Metro Vancouver Regional District]].\n*The [[Expo Line (SkyTrain)|Expo Line]] is named after Expo 86, for which it was originally constructed. It connects [[Waterfront station (Vancouver)|Waterfront station]], an intermodal transit station in Downtown Vancouver, with [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]]. Since 2016, a second branch of the line connects to the Millennium Line in [[Burnaby]].<ref name=\"Evergreen\">{{cite web |url=http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/vancouver/ |title=Vancouver SkyTrain, Canada |website=Railway-Technology.com |accessdate=2015-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.news1130.com/2016/12/02/evergreen-extension-opening-today/ |title=Evergreen Extension opening today |date=2016-12-02 |website=NEWS 1130|access-date=2016-12-02}}</ref>\n*The [[Millenium Line]] is named after the [[3rd millennium]] in which it was opened. Originally, it operated as a branch service of the Expo Line, following its alignment from Waterfront to [[Columbia station (SkyTrain)|Columbia station]], before branching off. The opening of the [[Evergreen Extension]] in 2016 brought its current alignment, running roughly east-west from [[VCC\u2013Clark station]] in Vancouver to [[Lafarge Lake\u2013Douglas station]] in [[Coquitlam]].<ref name=\"Evergreen\"/> An [[Millennium Line Broadway extension|additional extension]] is planned along [[Broadway (Vancouver)|Broadway]] to [[Arbutus station]].\n*The [[Canada Line]] was built in advance of the [[2010 Winter Olympics]]. It uses distinct technology from the rest of the system, and runs south from Waterfront station to the [[Vancouver International Airport|airport]] and [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]].\n\n===Waterloo===\n[[File:Ion Flexity Freedom 514 service livery.jpg|thumb|Ion LRV on Northfield Drive in Waterloo]]\n{{main|Ion rapid transit}}\nThe first phase of the {{convert|19|km|adj=on}} LRT system runs from [[Conestoga station]] in [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] to [[Fairway station]] in [[Kitchener, Ontario|Kitchener]]. It opened to the public on June 21, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grt.ca/en/ion-light-rail.aspx |title=ION light rail |date=April 16, 2019 |website=grt.ca |accessdate=April 26, 2019}}</ref> The system operates in reserved lanes on public streets and on private rights of way. [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo Region, Ontario]] has also approved plans for a light rail extension to the [[Ainslie St. Transit Terminal]] in [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]], as phase two of Ion.<ref name=\"Irj2013-07-12\">{{cite journal |first=Douglas John |last=Bowen |url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/light-rail/waterloo-opts-for-bombardier-lrvs.html?channel=542 |title=Waterloo opts for Bombardier LRVs |journal=[[International Railway Journal]] |date=July 12, 2013 |accessdate=July 13, 2013 |archivedate=July 13, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.railjournal.com%2Findex.php%2Flight-rail%2Fwaterloo-opts-for-bombardier-lrvs.html%3Fchannel%3D542&date=2013-07-13 |url-status=live |quote=The first of the Flexity Freedom LRV are due to be delivered in mid-2016, and will be used on the 19km, 16-station line from Conestoga Mall in Waterloo to Fairview Park Mall in Kitchener. The $C 92.4m ($US 89.2m) contract will include an option for 16 additional vehicles.}}</ref>\n\n==In development==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! City or region\n! Line \n! Construction start \n! Expected opening\n! Stations\n! Line length\n! Status\n|-\n| [[Calgary]]\n| [[Green Line (Calgary)|Green Line (stage 1)]]{{efn|name=Green|Only phase 1 which spans from 16 Avenue N to 126 Avenue SE (About 14 stations and {{convert|20|km}}).}}\n| 2020\n| 2026{{efn|Depends on delivery of funding promised by federal and provincial governments during recent elections.}}\n| {{nts|14}}{{efn|name=Stations|When fully complete the Green Line will have 28 Stations}}\n| {{convert|20|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}{{efn|name=Km|When the Green Line is complete it will be {{convert|48|km}} long.}}\n| Planned\n|-\n| [[Edmonton]]\n| [[Valley Line (Edmonton)|Valley Line Southeast]]{{efn|name=Valley|Data for Valley Line phase 1 only from Mill Woods to 102 Street.}}\n| 2016<ref name=\"ValleyPage\" />\n| 2020<ref name=\"ValleyPage\" />\n| {{nts|12}}<ref name=\"ValleyVideo\" />\n| {{convert|13.1|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}<ref name=\"ValleyVideo\" />\n| Under construction<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edmonton.ca/ets/transit_projects/southeast-to-west-lrt-mill-woods-to-lewis-farms.aspx |title=Archived 