update on the latest of Stage 2 of LRT|work=CTV News|date=September 10, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Regional Municipality of Peel|Peel Region]]\n| [[Hurontario LRT]]\n| 2020<ref name=\"update\">https://www.railwayage.com/news/ontario-lrt-update/</ref>\n| 2024\n| {{nts|19}}\n| {{convert|18|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}<ref name=\"Metro-2015-10-28\" />\n| Planned\n|-\n| [[Quebec City]]\n| [[Quebec City Tramway]]\n| \n| 2026\n| {{nts|35}}\n| {{convert|23|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Planned\n|-\n| [[Toronto]]\n| [[Line 5 Eglinton]]\n| 2011\n| 2022<ref name=\"CBC-delay-2022\">{{cite web |title=Eglinton Crosstown LRT won't be ready until 'well into 2022,' Metrolinx says |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/eglinton-crosstown-lrt-open-2022-1.5466847 |website=CBC News |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |date=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{nts|26}}\n| {{convert|19|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Under construction\n|-\n| Toronto\n| [[Line 6 Finch West]]\n| 2019<ref name=\"update\" />\n| 2023\n| {{nts|18}}\n| {{convert|11|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n| Under construction\n|}\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n===Gatineau===\n{{main|Gatineau LRT}}\n[[Gatineau]], [[Quebec]] is proposing a {{convert|26|km|adj=on}} LRT system that would connect with Ottawa's O-Train system.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gatineau reveals $2.1B LRT plan, eyes 2028 launch |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/gatineau-aylmer-ottawa-light-rail-1.4713843 |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |work=CBC News |date=June 20, 2018}}</ref>\n===Montreal===\n{{main|R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain}}\nThe [[R\u00e9seau express m\u00e9tropolitain]] is a light metro line under construction in Montreal. It is set to open in phases beginning in 2021. When completed, it will comprise of a central section connecting to the Green, Orange, and Blue metro lines, with four branches with service to the [[North Shore (Montreal)|North Shore]], [[West Island]], [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Trudeau International Airport|airport]], and [[South Shore (Montreal)|South Shore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.citymetric.com/transport/r-seau-express-m-tropolitain-multi-billion-dollar-light-rail-project-montreal-never-asked|title=The R\u00e9seau Express M\u00e9tropolitain: the multi-billion dollar light rail project Montreal never asked for|last=Noakes|first=Taylor|date=November 13, 2019|website=CityMetric|url-status=live|access-date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n===Peel Region===\n{{main|Hurontario LRT}}\nThe Hurontario LRT is a proposed {{convert|17.6|km|adj=on}} light rail line largely financed by the province of [[Ontario]] to run on the surface along [[Hurontario Street]] from [[Port Credit GO Station]] in [[Mississauga]] to Steeles Avenue in [[Brampton]]. On October 28, 2015, Brampton City Council cancelled the proposed {{convert|5.6|km|adj=on}} section of the line along [[Main Street (Brampton)|Main Street]] in [[Brampton]] to [[Brampton GO Station]].<ref name=\"Metro-2015-10-28\">{{cite news |url=http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2015/10/28/brampton-council-rejects-lrt.html |title=Brampton council votes to reject provincially approved LRT |newspaper=Metro News |date=October 28, 2015 |accessdate=October 28, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208153340/http://www.metronews.ca/news/toronto/2015/10/28/brampton-council-rejects-lrt.html |archive-date=December 8, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On March 21, 2019, Metrolinx announced that the most of the downtown loop would be deferred to a later date due to financial restrictions, although a short spur and stop on Rathburn would remain.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/03/21/metrolinx-scraps-portion-of-hurontario-lrt-in-effort-to-cut-costs.html |title=Metrolinx scraps portion of Hurontario LRT in effort to cut costs {{!}} The Star|website=Toronto Star |access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n===Quebec City===\n{{main|Quebec City Tramway}}\nThe Quebec City Tramway is a planned light rail transit line in Quebec City set to open in 2026. It will link [[Charlesbourg, Quebec City|Charlesbourg]] to [[Cap-Rouge, Quebec City|Cap Rouge]], passing through [[Parliament Hill (Quebec City)|Quebec Parliament Hill]]. The {{convert|23|km|adj=on}} line will include a {{convert|3.5|km|adj=on}} underground segment, with the rest of the line being on the surface.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/mayor-premier-unveil-plans-for-3-billion-tramway-for-quebec-city|title=Mayor, premier unveil plans for $3-billion tramway for Quebec City|date=March 16, 2018|work=Montreal Gazette|access-date=July 8, 2019|agency=Presse Canadienne}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[List of bus rapid transit systems in the Americas#Canada]]\n[[Public transport in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian passenger rail systems}}\n\n[[Category:Transport in Canada]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in North America]]\n", "name_user": "Mattximus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urban_rail_transit_in_Canada"}
{"title_page": "Hitotsume-koz\u014d", "text_new": "[[File:Obake Karuta 4-06.jpg|thumb|right|160px|The card \"{{nihongo|Boy with His Toungue Out Licking T\u014dfu|\u3057\u305f\u51fa\u3057\u5c0f\u50e7\u306e\u3068\u3046\u3075\u306a\u3081}}\" from [[Obake karuta|y\u014dkai karuta]]<ref name=\"\u5996\u602a\u304b\u308b\u305f\">{{Cite book|author=\u591a\u7530\u514b\u5df1\u7de8|title=\u6c5f\u6238\u5996\u602a\u304b\u308b\u305f|year=1998|publisher=\u56fd\u66f8\u520a\u884c\u4f1a|isbn=978-4-3360-4112-8|pages=49\u9801}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Masayoshi Hitotsume-kozo.jpg|thumb|right|160px|A hitotsume-koz\u014d from a [[kiby\u014dshi]]. \"Bakemono Chakut\u014dch\u014d\" by Masayoshi Kitao.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u30a2\u30c0\u30e0\u30fb\u30ab\u30d0\u30c3\u30c8\u6821\u6ce8\u30fb\u7de8 |title=\u6c5f\u6238\u5316\u7269\u8349\u7d19|year=1999|publisher=\u5c0f\u5b66\u9928|isbn=978-4-0936-2111-3|pages=43\u9801}}</ref>]]\n'''Hitotsume-koz\u014d''' (\u4e00\u3064\u76ee\u5c0f\u50e7) are a ''[[Y\u014dkai]]'' (supernatural apparition) of [[Japan]] that take on the appearance of a bald-headed child with one eye in the center of its forehead similar to a [[cyclops]].\n\n==Summary==\nThey generally do not cause any injury, are said to suddenly appear and surprise people, and are a comparatively harmless type of y\u014dkai. By that, it can be said that their behavior could also be understood in terms of the [[karakasa-obake]]. Perhaps because they don't perform bad deeds, when they are depicted in pictures, they are often depicted cutely, or in a humorous design.\n\nIn [[obake karuta|y\u014dkai karuta]], hitotsume-koz\u014d are depicted carrying t\u014dfu, but according to the y\u014dkai researcher [[Katsumi Tada]], since \"{{nihongo|mametsubu|\u8c46\u7c92|bean pieces}}\" leads to \"{{nihongo|mametsu|\u9b54\u6ec5|sound health}}\", hitotsume-koz\u014d are supposed to dislike beans, but somehow before anyone knew it the hitotsume-koz\u014d switched to having [[t\u014dfu]] (made from soybeans) as its favorite food. Additionally, this said to be related to the [[t\u014dfu-koz\u014d]].<ref name=\"\u5996\u602a\u304b\u308b\u305f\" />\n\nThey take on the appearance of a koz\u014d (a monk in training), but there is also the theory that they come from the y\u014dkai from [[Mount Hiei]], the '''{{nihongo|ichigan hitoashi h\u014dshi|\u4e00\u773c\u4e00\u8db3\u6cd5\u5e2b|one-eyed one-footed Buddhist priest}}''' said to be what the 18th Tendaizasu, [[Ry\u014dgen]] turned into. See also [[Hitotsume-ny\u016bd\u014d]].<ref name=\"youkaizukan\">{{Cite book|author=\u4eac\u6975\u590f\u5f66\u30fb\u591a\u7530\u514b\u5df1\u7de8\u8457|title=\u5996\u602a\u56f3\u5dfb|year=2000|publisher=\u56fd\u66f8\u520a\u884c\u4f1a|isbn=978-4-336-04187-6|pages=164\u2013165\u9801}}</ref>\n\n==Hitotsume-koz\u014d in classics==\nThey can frequently be seen in [[kaidan (parapsychology)|kaidan]], essays, and modern folkloristics material, but the story from \"{{nihongo|Kaidanoi no Tsue|\u602a\u8ac7\u8001\u306e\u6756}}\" by T\u014dsaku Ik\u014d is especially well-known. In [[Yotsuya, Tokyo|Yotsuya]], [[Edo]], there lived a man named Ojima Yakiemon (\u5c0f\u5d8b\u5f25\u559c\u53f3\u885b\u9580), and headed towards the estate of the samurai family Asanuno for business, and when he waited in the room, a koz\u014d about ten years of age appeared, and rolled up and rolled down the hanging scroll in the [[tokonoma]] over and over. When Yakiemon warned him about playing a prank, the koz\u014d said \"shut up\" while turning around, and there was only one eye on his face. Yakiemon raised a shriek and fell down, and was sent back to his home by the people of the estate who were surprised by his voice. Afterward, according to the people of the estate, this kind of strange occurrence happens about four or five times each year, but it doesn't particularly do anything bad. Even though Yakiemon slept for about 20 days, he returned to being as robust as he was before.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u5e73\u79fc\u6771\u4f5c|editor=\u67f4\u7530\u5bb5\u66f2\u7de8|year=2008|title=\u5947\u8ac7\u7570\u805e\u8f9e\u5178|publisher=\u7b51\u6469\u66f8\u623f|series=\u3061\u304f\u307e\u5b66\u82b8\u6587\u5eab|isbn=978-4-480-09162-8|pages=551\u2013552\u9801|chapter=\u602a\u8ac7\u8001\u306e\u6756}}</ref>\n\nIt is said that hitotsume-koz\u014d appear more frequently outside than inside. According to the \"{{nihongo|Aizu Kaidan Sh\u016b|\u4f1a\u6d25\u602a\u8ac7\u96c6}}\", near the {{nihongo|Honshi no Ch\u014d|\u672c\u56db\u30ce\u4e01}} in [[Aizuwakamatsu, Fukushima|Aizuwakamatsu]], a girl met a child who was eight or nine years of age who asked \"onee-san, do you money?\" and upon answering \"I want,\" the child face had only one eye, and the girl was glared at by that one eye fainted right there.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u5ddd\u53e3\u82b3\u662d\u7de8|title=\u4f1a\u6d25\u3075\u308b\u3055\u3068\u591c\u8a71|year=1978|publisher=\u6b74\u53f2\u6625\u79cb\u793e|volume=2|pages=28\u9801}}</ref> Also, in the \"Okayama no Kaidan,\" at Kamimomiimaidani, [[Kumenan, Okayama|Kumenan]], [[Kume District, Okayama|Kume District]], [[Okayama Prefecture]], there was a hill road called {{nihongo|Hitokuchizaka|\u4e00\u53e3\u5742|\"one mouth hill\"}}, and in the past, when one walks that path at night, a bright blue light together with a hitotsume-koz\u014d would appear, and those who are unable to stand due to surprise/fear would be licked by one mouthful of a long tongue, and this would be where the name Hitokuchizaka came from.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u4f50\u85e4\u7c73\u53f8|title=\u5ca1\u5c71\u306e\u602a\u8ac7|year=1979|publisher=\u65e5\u672c\u6587\u6559\u51fa\u7248|series=\u5ca1\u5c71\u6587\u5eab|pages=42\u9801}}</ref>\n\nIn y\u014dkai depictions from the Edo period such as the [[Hyakkai Zukan]], the \"Bakemono Zukushi,\" and the \"Bakemono Emaki,\" it was depicted under the name {{nihongo|Mehitotsu-b\u014d|\u76ee\u4e00\u3064\u574a}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u65e5\u672c\u5996\u602a\u5927\u4e8b\u5178|pages=5\u9801}}</ref> Also, in Oshu, they are called \"hitotsu managu.\"<ref>\u67f3\u7530\u570b\u7537 \u300e\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u4f1d\u8aac\u300f \u89d2\u5ddd\u6587\u5eab \u521d\u72481953\u5e74\uff0815\u72481977\u5e74\uff09 65\u9801\u3002</ref>\n\nAlso in [[rakugo]], people with one eye (including children) would appear, and in the program \"{{nihongo|Ichigankoku|\u4e00\u773c\u56fd|\"One Eyed Country\"}},\" it told of how a charlatan heard about a one-eyed person witnessed about 120 or 130 ri north of Edo on an empty field. He went out to capture one to show as an exhibit for the sake of profit. He found a one-eyed child, and when he attempted to take him away, there was a big uproar and he was surrounded by a great number of people who captured him. All of the people were one-eyed, and it ended with \"how strange he is, he has two eyes,\" and \"quickly, let's put him on exhibit\" (furthermore, geographically, 120 ri north of Edo would be about 470 kilometers, which would be the Iwate or Akita Prefecture).\n\n==Hitotsume-koz\u014d in folk religion==\nIn the [[Kant\u014d region]], there is the legend that on the night of {{nihongo|Kotoy\u014dka|\u4e8b\u516b\u65e5}}, the eighth day on the second month and the eighth day of the 12th month in the lunisolar calendar, they would come from mountain villages together with a [[mikaribaba]], and perform the custom of putting a bamboo basket in front of their house in order to drive it away. Also, depending on the region, [[Osmanthus heterophyllus|hiiragi]] are used to pierce baskets, but this is what \"to stab one eye\" means in those places.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u6751\u4e0a\u5065\u53f8\u7de8\u8457|title=\u65e5\u672c\u5996\u602a\u5927\u4e8b\u5178|year=2005|publisher=\u89d2\u5ddd\u66f8\u5e97|series=Kwai books|isbn=978-4-04-883926-6|pages=274\u2013276\u9801}}</ref> On Kotoy\u014dka, in the past there were many regions that people would not do their work and stay confined in their homes, but sometimes, this ritual of seclusion in the house was interpreted as staying in the home since monsters would appear; there is also a theory that these monsters are the hitotsume-koz\u014d and the mikaribaba.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u65e5\u672c\u5996\u602a\u5927\u4e8b\u5178|pages=310\u9801}}</ref>\n\nAlso in the legends of the Kant\u014d region, hitotsume-koz\u014d would go around houses carrying a notebook on Kotoy\u014dka and would investigate houses that had bad door fastenings or bad manners, and determine their fortune,<ref name=\"\u65c5\u3068\u4f1d\u8aac\">{{Cite journal|author=\u67f3\u7530\u570b\u7537|date=September 1933|title=\u5e74\u4e2d\u884c\u4e8b\u8abf\u67fb\u6a19\u76ee|journal=\u65c5\u3068\u4f1d\u8aac|volume=6\u5dfb|issue=9\u53f7\uff08\u901a\u5dfb69\u53f7\uff09|pages=86\u9801}}</ref> or report it to the [[yakuby\u014dgami]] and bring about misfortune.<ref name=\"\u5e7b\u60f3\u4e16\u754c\">{{Cite book|author=\u591a\u7530\u514b\u5df1|title=\u5e7b\u60f3\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u4f4f\u4eba\u305f\u3061|year=1990|publisher=\u65b0\u7d00\u5143\u793e|series=Truth in fantasy|volume=IV|isbn=978-4-915146-44-2|pages=281\u9801}}</ref> On this occasion, on the eighth day of the 12th month, the hitotsume-koz\u014d would record in a notebook the errors of each house and temporarily hand it to the [[d\u014dsojin]], and since they would be retrieving it on the eighth day of the second month, and as a practice to burn away the notebook, in [[Seya-ku, Yokohama|Seya-ku]], [[Yokohama]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], they would make a temporary shrine to the d\u014dsojin and on the 14th day of the first month, burn it in [[sagich\u014d|dondoyaki]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.city.yokohama.lg.jp/seya/shoukai/minwa/minwa15.html|title=\u702c\u8c37\u533a\u306e\u6c11\u8a71\u3068\u6614\u8a71 \u7b2c\u5341\u4e94\u8a71\uff1a\u4e00\u3064\u76ee\u5c0f\u50e7|website=\u6a2a\u6d5c\u5e02\u702c\u8c37\u533a \u533a\u653f\u63a8\u9032\u8ab2|accessdate=2008-12-25}}</ref>. In [[Izu Peninsula|Izu region]] in [[Shizuoka Prefecture]], on the 15th day of the first month, there is the custom of burning a statue of a d\u014dsojin in a fire in the d\u014dsojin festival.<ref name=\"\u65c5\u3068\u4f1d\u8aac\" /> With this, the hitotsume-koz\u014d who was supposed to retrieve the notebook from the d\u014dsojin on the eighth day of the second month would no longer be there, thus evading misfortune.<ref name=\"\u65c5\u3068\u4f1d\u8aac\" /><ref name=\"\u5e7b\u60f3\u4e16\u754c\" />\n\n===Atypical gods (kami)===\n[[Kunio Yanagita]], a great authority on [[folkloristics]], based on the thought that \"y\u014dkai are gods (kami) that have come to ruin,\" it has been explained that hitotsume-koz\u014d are fallen [[Yama-no-Kami|mountain gods]]. There are several regions that have the legend that \"mountain gods are cross-eyed ([[trabismus]]),\" and since \"has one eye\" was a common way to say \"cross-eyed,\" this is also originated from the divine spirits of the mountain. Also, there are hints that there existed people who lost a leg and an eye as a [[sacrifice]] in old rituals, and according to [[hunter]]s and [[lumberjack]]s, in a legend related to nature gods deified in the mountains, one can catch a glimpse of atypical gods that took on an appearance with one eye and one foot. Other than this, since, among those who were employed in smelting iron in a [[Tatara (furnace)|tatara]] there were many people who lost one eye, there is the theory that it is related to one-eyed god, [[Ame no Mahitotsu no Kami]] that people employed at iron smelting have put their faith into.\n\n==Cyclopia==\n{{main|Cyclopia}}\nThere is an inherited deformity called [[cyclopia]]. When the mother is deficient in [[Vitamin A]] or other nutrients, the [[cerebrum]] is unable to divide to the left and right, and accompanying this there is also only one eyeball. More than just abnormalities with the brain, nerves, or respiratory system, it is a condition that results in death in the womb before even birth. Vitamin A is, other than green vegetables, also contained in many animal foods, and in Japan, which did not have much of a culture in eating meat, it might not have been strange to be deficient in Vitamin A. With this background, since hitotsume-koz\u014d have the appearance of a child and the clothing of a young priest, it is thought that babies born with one eye were called this, which is where it started.<ref>{{Cite web|author=\u5c71\u7530\u654f\u4e4b|date=2007-06-29|url=http://www.sony-ef.or.jp/library/rakugo/2_ex.html|title=\u7b2c2\u56de \u300e\u4e00\u773c\u56fd\u300f\u3068\u8907\u773c\u601d\u8003 \u89e3\u8aac\u7de8|website=\u843d\u8a9e\u306b\u5b66\u3076 ([[Rakugo]] ni Manabu)|publisher=\u30bd\u30cb\u30fc\u6559\u80b2\u8ca1\u56e3|accessdate=2009-12-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110200707/http://www.sony-ef.or.jp/library/rakugo/2_ex.html|archivedate=2007-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"\u307e\u3081\u3053\u305e\u3046\">{{Cite web|author=|date=2007-01-08|url=http://www.0462.net/blog/mamekozo/index.html?page=2133|title=\u307e\u3081\u3053\u305e\u3046\u306e\u65c5 \u5ea7\u9593\u306e\u6b74\u53f2\u63a2\u691c \u7b2c34\u8a71 \u4e00\u3064\u76ee\u5c0f\u50e7\u5730\u8535|website=\u3042\u306a\u305f\u306e\u77e5\u3089\u306a\u3044\u5ea7\u9593\u304c\u3042\u308b 0462.net|publisher=\u5ea7\u9593\u5e02\u5546\u5e97\u4f1a\u9023\u5408\u4f1a|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Zama, Kanagawa|Zama]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], in 1932 (Showa 7), a skull with only one eye socket was dug up from the cemetery inside the city, and it was presumed to have been the result of someone who was attacked by wild dogs after collapsing, and a \"Hitotsume-koz\u014d Jiz\u014d\" was constructed as a memorial for this, and afterwards people connected it with the legend of hitotsume-koz\u014d and conveyed between people.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u5ea7\u9593\u5e02\u6587\u5316\u8ca1\u8abf\u67fb\u59d4\u54e1\u4f1a\u57f7\u7b46\u7de8\u96c6|title=\u5ea7\u9593\u5e02\u6587\u5316\u8ca1\u8abf\u67fb\u5831\u544a\u66f8|year=1984|publisher=\u5ea7\u9593\u5e02\u6559\u80b2\u59d4\u54e1\u4f1a|volume=\u7b2c9\u96c6|pages=96\u201397\u9801}}</ref> There is also the viewpoint that the owner of the skull had cyclopia.<ref name=\"\u307e\u3081\u3053\u305e\u3046\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cyclopes]]\n*[[List of legendary creatures from Japan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://hyakumonogatari.com/2012/03/12/tofu-kozo-the-tofu-boy/ T\u014dfu-koz\u014d \u2013 The Tofu Boy | \u767e\u7269\u8a9e\u602a\u8ac7\u4f1a Hyakumonogatari Kaidankai], by Mizuki Shigeru at hyakumonogatari.com\n*[http://en.gigazine.net/news/20081230_youkai_bronze/ 133 Yokai Statues on Mizuki Shigeru Road]; scroll down to see 84. Hitotsume Kozou (One-eyed boy)\n{{Japanese folklore long}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hitotsume-kozo}}\n[[Category:Mythic humanoids]]\n[[Category:Y\u014dkai]]\n[[Category:Mythological monsters]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Obake Karuta 4-06.jpg|thumb|right|160px|The card \"{{nihongo|Boy with His Toungue Out Licking T\u014dfu|\u3057\u305f\u51fa\u3057\u5c0f\u50e7\u306e\u3068\u3046\u3075\u306a\u3081}}\" from [[Obake karuta|y\u014dkai karuta]]<ref name=\"\u5996\u602a\u304b\u308b\u305f\">{{Cite book|author=\u591a\u7530\u514b\u5df1\u7de8|title=\u6c5f\u6238\u5996\u602a\u304b\u308b\u305f|year=1998|publisher=\u56fd\u66f8\u520a\u884c\u4f1a|isbn=978-4-3360-4112-8|pages=49\u9801}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Masayoshi Hitotsume-kozo.jpg|thumb|right|160px|A hitotsume-koz\u014d from a [[kiby\u014dshi]]. \"Bakemono Chakut\u014dch\u014d\" by Masayoshi Kitao.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u30a2\u30c0\u30e0\u30fb\u30ab\u30d0\u30c3\u30c8\u6821\u6ce8\u30fb\u7de8 |title=\u6c5f\u6238\u5316\u7269\u8349\u7d19|year=1999|publisher=\u5c0f\u5b66\u9928|isbn=978-4-0936-2111-3|pages=43\u9801}}</ref>]]\n'''Hitotsume-koz\u014d''' (\u4e00\u3064\u76ee\u5c0f\u50e7) are a ''[[Y\u014dkai]]'' (supernatural apparition) of [[Japan]] that take on the appearance of a bald-headed child with one eye in the center of its forehead similar to a [[cyclops]].\n\n==Summary==\nThey generally do not cause any injury, are said to suddenly appear and surprise people, and are a comparatively harmless type of y\u014dkai. By that, it can be said that their behavior could also be understood in terms of the [[karakasa-obake]]. Perhaps because they don't perform bad deeds, when they are depicted in pictures, they are often depicted cutely, or in a humorous design.\n\nIn [[obake karuta|y\u014dkai karuta]], hitotsume-koz\u014d are depicted carrying t\u014dfu, but according to the y\u014dkai researcher [[Katsumi Tada]], since \"{{nihongo|mametsubu|\u8c46\u7c92|bean pieces}}\" leads to \"{{nihongo|mametsu|\u9b54\u6ec5|sound health}}\", hitotsume-koz\u014d are supposed to dislike beans, but somehow before anyone knew it the hitotsume-koz\u014d switched to having [[t\u014dfu]] (made from soybeans) as its favorite food. Additionally, this said to be related to the [[t\u014dfu-koz\u014d]].<ref name=\"\u5996\u602a\u304b\u308b\u305f\" />\n\nThey take on the appearance of a koz\u014d (a monk in training), but there is also the theory that they come from the y\u014dkai from [[Mount Hiei]], the '''{{nihongo|ichigan hitoashi h\u014dshi|\u4e00\u773c\u4e00\u8db3\u6cd5\u5e2b|one-eyed one-footed Buddhist priest}}''' said to be what the 18th Tendaizasu, [[Ry\u014dgen]] turned into. See also [[Hitotsume-ny\u016bd\u014d]].<ref name=\"youkaizukan\">{{Cite book|author=\u4eac\u6975\u590f\u5f66\u30fb\u591a\u7530\u514b\u5df1\u7de8\u8457|title=\u5996\u602a\u56f3\u5dfb|year=2000|publisher=\u56fd\u66f8\u520a\u884c\u4f1a|isbn=978-4-336-04187-6|pages=164\u2013165\u9801}}</ref>\n\n==Hitotsume-koz\u014d in classics==\nThey can frequently be seen in [[kaidan]], essays, and modern folkloristics material, but the story from \"{{nihongo|Kaidanoi no Tsue|\u602a\u8ac7\u8001\u306e\u6756}}\" by T\u014dsaku Ik\u014d is especially well-known. In [[Yotsuya, Tokyo|Yotsuya]], [[Edo]], there lived a man named Ojima Yakiemon (\u5c0f\u5d8b\u5f25\u559c\u53f3\u885b\u9580), and headed towards the estate of the samurai family Asanuno for business, and when he waited in the room, a koz\u014d about ten years of age appeared, and rolled up and rolled down the hanging scroll in the [[tokonoma]] over and over. When Yakiemon warned him about playing a prank, the koz\u014d said \"shut up\" while turning around, and there was only one eye on his face. Yakiemon raised a shriek and fell down, and was sent back to his home by the people of the estate who were surprised by his voice. Afterward, according to the people of the estate, this kind of strange occurrence happens about four or five times each year, but it doesn't particularly do anything bad. Even though Yakiemon slept for about 20 days, he returned to being as robust as he was before.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u5e73\u79fc\u6771\u4f5c|editor=\u67f4\u7530\u5bb5\u66f2\u7de8|year=2008|title=\u5947\u8ac7\u7570\u805e\u8f9e\u5178|publisher=\u7b51\u6469\u66f8\u623f|series=\u3061\u304f\u307e\u5b66\u82b8\u6587\u5eab|isbn=978-4-480-09162-8|pages=551\u2013552\u9801|chapter=\u602a\u8ac7\u8001\u306e\u6756}}</ref>\n\nIt is said that hitotsume-koz\u014d appear more frequently outside than inside. According to the \"{{nihongo|Aizu Kaidan Sh\u016b|\u4f1a\u6d25\u602a\u8ac7\u96c6}}\", near the {{nihongo|Honshi no Ch\u014d|\u672c\u56db\u30ce\u4e01}} in [[Aizuwakamatsu, Fukushima|Aizuwakamatsu]], a girl met a child who was eight or nine years of age who asked \"onee-san, do you money?\" and upon answering \"I want,\" the child face had only one eye, and the girl was glared at by that one eye fainted right there.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u5ddd\u53e3\u82b3\u662d\u7de8|title=\u4f1a\u6d25\u3075\u308b\u3055\u3068\u591c\u8a71|year=1978|publisher=\u6b74\u53f2\u6625\u79cb\u793e|volume=2|pages=28\u9801}}</ref> Also, in the \"Okayama no Kaidan,\" at Kamimomiimaidani, [[Kumenan, Okayama|Kumenan]], [[Kume District, Okayama|Kume District]], [[Okayama Prefecture]], there was a hill road called {{nihongo|Hitokuchizaka|\u4e00\u53e3\u5742|\"one mouth hill\"}}, and in the past, when one walks that path at night, a bright blue light together with a hitotsume-koz\u014d would appear, and those who are unable to stand due to surprise/fear would be licked by one mouthful of a long tongue, and this would be where the name Hitokuchizaka came from.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u4f50\u85e4\u7c73\u53f8|title=\u5ca1\u5c71\u306e\u602a\u8ac7|year=1979|publisher=\u65e5\u672c\u6587\u6559\u51fa\u7248|series=\u5ca1\u5c71\u6587\u5eab|pages=42\u9801}}</ref>\n\nIn y\u014dkai depictions from the Edo period such as the [[Hyakkai Zukan]], the \"Bakemono Zukushi,\" and the \"Bakemono Emaki,\" it was depicted under the name {{nihongo|Mehitotsu-b\u014d|\u76ee\u4e00\u3064\u574a}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u65e5\u672c\u5996\u602a\u5927\u4e8b\u5178|pages=5\u9801}}</ref> Also, in Oshu, they are called \"hitotsu managu.\"<ref>\u67f3\u7530\u570b\u7537 \u300e\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u4f1d\u8aac\u300f \u89d2\u5ddd\u6587\u5eab \u521d\u72481953\u5e74\uff0815\u72481977\u5e74\uff09 65\u9801\u3002</ref>\n\nAlso in [[rakugo]], people with one eye (including children) would appear, and in the program \"{{nihongo|Ichigankoku|\u4e00\u773c\u56fd|\"One Eyed Country\"}},\" it told of how a charlatan heard about a one-eyed person witnessed about 120 or 130 ri north of Edo on an empty field. He went out to capture one to show as an exhibit for the sake of profit. He found a one-eyed child, and when he attempted to take him away, there was a big uproar and he was surrounded by a great number of people who captured him. All of the people were one-eyed, and it ended with \"how strange he is, he has two eyes,\" and \"quickly, let's put him on exhibit\" (furthermore, geographically, 120 ri north of Edo would be about 470 kilometers, which would be the Iwate or Akita Prefecture).\n\n==Hitotsume-koz\u014d in folk religion==\nIn the [[Kant\u014d region]], there is the legend that on the night of {{nihongo|Kotoy\u014dka|\u4e8b\u516b\u65e5}}, the eighth day on the second month and the eighth day of the 12th month in the lunisolar calendar, they would come from mountain villages together with a [[mikaribaba]], and perform the custom of putting a bamboo basket in front of their house in order to drive it away. Also, depending on the region, [[Osmanthus heterophyllus|hiiragi]] are used to pierce baskets, but this is what \"to stab one eye\" means in those places.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u6751\u4e0a\u5065\u53f8\u7de8\u8457|title=\u65e5\u672c\u5996\u602a\u5927\u4e8b\u5178|year=2005|publisher=\u89d2\u5ddd\u66f8\u5e97|series=Kwai books|isbn=978-4-04-883926-6|pages=274\u2013276\u9801}}</ref> On Kotoy\u014dka, in the past there were many regions that people would not do their work and stay confined in their homes, but sometimes, this ritual of seclusion in the house was interpreted as staying in the home since monsters would appear; there is also a theory that these monsters are the hitotsume-koz\u014d and the mikaribaba.<ref>{{Cite book|title=\u65e5\u672c\u5996\u602a\u5927\u4e8b\u5178|pages=310\u9801}}</ref>\n\nAlso in the legends of the Kant\u014d region, hitotsume-koz\u014d would go around houses carrying a notebook on Kotoy\u014dka and would investigate houses that had bad door fastenings or bad manners, and determine their fortune,<ref name=\"\u65c5\u3068\u4f1d\u8aac\">{{Cite journal|author=\u67f3\u7530\u570b\u7537|date=September 1933|title=\u5e74\u4e2d\u884c\u4e8b\u8abf\u67fb\u6a19\u76ee|journal=\u65c5\u3068\u4f1d\u8aac|volume=6\u5dfb|issue=9\u53f7\uff08\u901a\u5dfb69\u53f7\uff09|pages=86\u9801}}</ref> or report it to the [[yakuby\u014dgami]] and bring about misfortune.<ref name=\"\u5e7b\u60f3\u4e16\u754c\">{{Cite book|author=\u591a\u7530\u514b\u5df1|title=\u5e7b\u60f3\u4e16\u754c\u306e\u4f4f\u4eba\u305f\u3061|year=1990|publisher=\u65b0\u7d00\u5143\u793e|series=Truth in fantasy|volume=IV|isbn=978-4-915146-44-2|pages=281\u9801}}</ref> On this occasion, on the eighth day of the 12th month, the hitotsume-koz\u014d would record in a notebook the errors of each house and temporarily hand it to the [[d\u014dsojin]], and since they would be retrieving it on the eighth day of the second month, and as a practice to burn away the notebook, in [[Seya-ku, Yokohama|Seya-ku]], [[Yokohama]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], they would make a temporary shrine to the d\u014dsojin and on the 14th day of the first month, burn it in [[sagich\u014d|dondoyaki]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.city.yokohama.lg.jp/seya/shoukai/minwa/minwa15.html|title=\u702c\u8c37\u533a\u306e\u6c11\u8a71\u3068\u6614\u8a71 \u7b2c\u5341\u4e94\u8a71\uff1a\u4e00\u3064\u76ee\u5c0f\u50e7|website=\u6a2a\u6d5c\u5e02\u702c\u8c37\u533a \u533a\u653f\u63a8\u9032\u8ab2|accessdate=2008-12-25}}</ref>. In [[Izu Peninsula|Izu region]] in [[Shizuoka Prefecture]], on the 15th day of the first month, there is the custom of burning a statue of a d\u014dsojin in a fire in the d\u014dsojin festival.<ref name=\"\u65c5\u3068\u4f1d\u8aac\" /> With this, the hitotsume-koz\u014d who was supposed to retrieve the notebook from the d\u014dsojin on the eighth day of the second month would no longer be there, thus evading misfortune.<ref name=\"\u65c5\u3068\u4f1d\u8aac\" /><ref name=\"\u5e7b\u60f3\u4e16\u754c\" />\n\n===Atypical gods (kami)===\n[[Kunio Yanagita]], a great authority on [[folkloristics]], based on the thought that \"y\u014dkai are gods (kami) that have come to ruin,\" it has been explained that hitotsume-koz\u014d are fallen [[Yama-no-Kami|mountain gods]]. There are several regions that have the legend that \"mountain gods are cross-eyed ([[trabismus]]),\" and since \"has one eye\" was a common way to say \"cross-eyed,\" this is also originated from the divine spirits of the mountain. Also, there are hints that there existed people who lost a leg and an eye as a [[sacrifice]] in old rituals, and according to [[hunter]]s and [[lumberjack]]s, in a legend related to nature gods deified in the mountains, one can catch a glimpse of atypical gods that took on an appearance with one eye and one foot. Other than this, since, among those who were employed in smelting iron in a [[Tatara (furnace)|tatara]] there were many people who lost one eye, there is the theory that it is related to one-eyed god, [[Ame no Mahitotsu no Kami]] that people employed at iron smelting have put their faith into.\n\n==Cyclopia==\n{{main|Cyclopia}}\nThere is an inherited deformity called [[cyclopia]]. When the mother is deficient in [[Vitamin A]] or other nutrients, the [[cerebrum]] is unable to divide to the left and right, and accompanying this there is also only one eyeball. More than just abnormalities with the brain, nerves, or respiratory system, it is a condition that results in death in the womb before even birth. Vitamin A is, other than green vegetables, also contained in many animal foods, and in Japan, which did not have much of a culture in eating meat, it might not have been strange to be deficient in Vitamin A. With this background, since hitotsume-koz\u014d have the appearance of a child and the clothing of a young priest, it is thought that babies born with one eye were called this, which is where it started.<ref>{{Cite web|author=\u5c71\u7530\u654f\u4e4b|date=2007-06-29|url=http://www.sony-ef.or.jp/library/rakugo/2_ex.html|title=\u7b2c2\u56de \u300e\u4e00\u773c\u56fd\u300f\u3068\u8907\u773c\u601d\u8003 \u89e3\u8aac\u7de8|website=\u843d\u8a9e\u306b\u5b66\u3076 ([[Rakugo]] ni Manabu)|publisher=\u30bd\u30cb\u30fc\u6559\u80b2\u8ca1\u56e3|accessdate=2009-12-05|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110200707/http://www.sony-ef.or.jp/library/rakugo/2_ex.html|archivedate=2007-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\"\u307e\u3081\u3053\u305e\u3046\">{{Cite web|author=|date=2007-01-08|url=http://www.0462.net/blog/mamekozo/index.html?page=2133|title=\u307e\u3081\u3053\u305e\u3046\u306e\u65c5 \u5ea7\u9593\u306e\u6b74\u53f2\u63a2\u691c \u7b2c34\u8a71 \u4e00\u3064\u76ee\u5c0f\u50e7\u5730\u8535|website=\u3042\u306a\u305f\u306e\u77e5\u3089\u306a\u3044\u5ea7\u9593\u304c\u3042\u308b 0462.net|publisher=\u5ea7\u9593\u5e02\u5546\u5e97\u4f1a\u9023\u5408\u4f1a|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Zama, Kanagawa|Zama]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], in 1932 (Showa 7), a skull with only one eye socket was dug up from the cemetery inside the city, and it was presumed to have been the result of someone who was attacked by wild dogs after collapsing, and a \"Hitotsume-koz\u014d Jiz\u014d\" was constructed as a memorial for this, and afterwards people connected it with the legend of hitotsume-koz\u014d and conveyed between people.<ref>{{Cite book|author=\u5ea7\u9593\u5e02\u6587\u5316\u8ca1\u8abf\u67fb\u59d4\u54e1\u4f1a\u57f7\u7b46\u7de8\u96c6|title=\u5ea7\u9593\u5e02\u6587\u5316\u8ca1\u8abf\u67fb\u5831\u544a\u66f8|year=1984|publisher=\u5ea7\u9593\u5e02\u6559\u80b2\u59d4\u54e1\u4f1a|volume=\u7b2c9\u96c6|pages=96\u201397\u9801}}</ref> There is also the viewpoint that the owner of the skull had cyclopia.<ref name=\"\u307e\u3081\u3053\u305e\u3046\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Cyclopes]]\n*[[List of legendary creatures from Japan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://hyakumonogatari.com/2012/03/12/tofu-kozo-the-tofu-boy/ T\u014dfu-koz\u014d \u2013 The Tofu Boy | \u767e\u7269\u8a9e\u602a\u8ac7\u4f1a Hyakumonogatari Kaidankai], by Mizuki Shigeru at hyakumonogatari.com\n*[http://en.gigazine.net/news/20081230_youkai_bronze/ 133 Yokai Statues on Mizuki Shigeru Road]; scroll down to see 84. Hitotsume Kozou (One-eyed boy)\n{{Japanese folklore long}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hitotsume-kozo}}\n[[Category:Mythic humanoids]]\n[[Category:Y\u014dkai]]\n[[Category:Mythological monsters]]\n", "name_user": "Star Mississippi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:kaidan\u2192kaidan (parapsychology)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hitotsume-koz%C5%8D"}
{"title_page": "Trams in Z\u00fcrich", "text_new": "{{Infobox tram network\n| name                          = Trams in Z\u00fcrich\n| image                         = Bahnhofstrasse - Uraniastrasse - Beatengasse 2010-08-27 19-07-46 ShiftN.jpg\n| image_width                   = 250px\n| caption                       = Bahnhofstrasse, Z\u00fcrich's premier shopping street\n<!-- Operation -->\n| locale                        = [[Z\u00fcrich]]\n| open                          = 1882\n| status                        = Operational\n| routes                        = 15<ref name=gpw/>\n| owner                         = City of Z\u00fcrich\n| operator                      = [[Verkehrsbetriebe Z\u00fcrich]]\n<!-- Infrastructure -->\n| gauge                         = {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}}\n| propulsion_system             = Electric\n| el                            = 600 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[overhead line|overhead]]\n| stock                         = 258\n| total_track_length            = {{convert|171.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"figures\" />\n| double_track_length           = {{convert|72.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"figures\"/>\n| route_length                  = {{convert|118.7|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"figures\"/>\n| pass_year                     = 2012\n| passengers                    = 205.0 million<ref name=\"passengers\">{{cite web |url=https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/portraet/zahlen_fakten/fahrgastzahlen.html |title=Startseite VBZ - Die VBZ - Portr\u00e4t - Zahlen & Fakten - Fahrgastzahlen |publisher=Stadt Z\u00fcrich [City of Z\u00fcrich] |language=German |trans-title=Home VBZ - VBZ - Portrait - Facts & Figures - Ridership |date= |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref>\n| map                           = [[Image:Tramnetz Z\u00fcrich.png|350px]]\n| website                       = http://www.vbz.ch/ www.vbz.ch\n}}\nTrams make an important contribution to public transport in the city of [[Z\u00fcrich]] in [[Switzerland]]. The [[tram]] network serves most city neighbourhoods, and is the backbone of public transport within the city, albeit supplemented by the inner sections of the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn]], along with urban [[trolleybus]] and [[bus]] routes as well as two [[funicular]] railways and one [[rack railway]]. The trams and other city transport modes operate within a fare regime provided by the cantonal public transport authority [[Z\u00fcrcher Verkehrsverbund]] (ZVV), which also covers regional rail and bus services.<ref name=tutttctlr>{{cite news | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | title = Z\u00fcrich: Top city \u2014 thanks to light rail | work = [[Tramways & Urban Transit]] | publisher = Ian Allan Ltd / Light Rail Transit Association | pages = 130\u2013134 | date = April 2005}}</ref><ref name=tuttcraag>{{cite news | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | title =  Z\u00fcrich: The Cobra rules, all above ground | work = [[Tramways & Urban Transit]] | publisher = Ian Allan Ltd / Light Rail Transit Association | pages = 180\u2013184 | date = May 2005}}</ref><ref name=zacait>{{cite web |  first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/zurich05_0.html | title = Z\u00fcrich: A city and its trams | date = December 2005 | accessdate = 2011-08-10}}</ref>\n\nThe city's trams are operated by the [[Verkehrsbetriebe Z\u00fcrich]] (VBZ), which also manages the tramway infrastructure within the city, but the city's tram tracks are also used by two other operations. The [[Stadtbahn Glattal|Glattalbahn]] tram services to the [[Glattal]] area to the north of the city interwork with the city tram services and are also operated by the VBZ, although in this case it does so as a sub-contractor to the [[Verkehrsbetriebe Glattal]] (VBG). Trains of the independent [[Forchbahn]] (FB) light railway also use the city's tram lines to reach their city centre terminus.<ref name=saw>{{cite book | title = Eisenbahnatlas Schweiz | year = 2012 | publisher = Verlag Schweers + Wall GmbH | isbn=978-3-89494-130-7 | pages = 64\u201365}}</ref>\n\nTrams have been a consistent part of Z\u00fcrich's streetscape since the 1880s, when the first horse tram ran. Electrified from the 1890s, they have seen off challenges including proposals to replace them by [[trolleybuses]] and by a [[metro (rapid transit)|metro]] or [[U-Bahn]]. With a relatively static city network from the 1930s to the late 1970s, the city's trams have been expanding again since then. Recent expansions have taken the network into the suburbs beyond the city boundary, covering areas it retreated from in the first part of the 20th century. Further extensions have been approved, both to the city tram network itself, and by the introduction of a [[Limmattal light rail line|new light rail system]] in the [[Limmat Valley]] that will interwork with the city trams.\n\n==History==\n\n===Beginnings===\n[[File:R\u00f6sslitram.jpg|thumb|left|One of Z\u00fcrich's horse trams  in 1900]]\nVarious projects to introduce trams to Z\u00fcrich were proposed from the 1860s onwards. It was not until 1882, however, that the first tram operated in the city. These initial trams were operated by the {{ill|Z\u00fcrcher Strassenbahn Gesellschaft|de}} (ZStG), a private company, and were of [[standard gauge]] ({{RailGauge|sg|disp=or}} gauge) and horse-drawn.<ref name=vbzfafch>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/corporate_history.html | title = Facts & figures - Corporate history | publisher = VBZ | accessdate = 2012-05-26 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121007013822/http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/corporate_history.html | archivedate = 2012-10-07 }}</ref>\n\nBy 1888 the first electric tramway in Switzerland (the [[Vevey\u2013Montreux\u2013Chillon tramway]]) had opened, and, in 1894, another private company, the {{ill|Elektrische Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich|de}} (EStZ), started operating [[metre gauge]] ({{RailGauge|1000mm|first=imp|disp=1}} gauge) electric trams in Z\u00fcrich. The EStZ only survived for two years before it was taken over by the City of Z\u00fcrich, who renamed it the [[St\u00e4dtische Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich]] (StStZ). The following year, the horse trams of the ZStG were acquired.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nFurther tramway companies were founded, some operating entirely within the city, some connecting the city with its nearer suburbs, and some running in rural areas entirely beyond the city, but still linked by connections with other lines to the city. Like the EStZ, all these lines were electrified and were built to the metre gauge. The StStZ gradually took over those companies that had significant city operations, usually closing any cross-boundary lines, whilst leaving those lines entirely beyond the city to their own devices.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Many companies===\n[[File:Zuercher Strassenbahnlinien um 1899.jpg|thumb|The mix of routes in 1899, distinguishing city owned (''Stadt'') and private (''Privat''), and horse (''Pferdebahn'') and electric (''elektrisch'')]]\nThe many companies that operated trams in and around Z\u00fcrich are summarised in the table below. Names of companies whose lines were entirely outside the current city boundaries are shown in ''italic'' type, and those which still operate tram or other light rail services are shown in '''bold''' type.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; font-size:95%; margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;\"\n!Company\n!Abbreviation\n!From\n!Until\n!Absorbed by\n!Notes\n|-\n|{{ill|Z\u00fcrcher Strassenbahn Gesellschaft|de}}\n|ZStG\n|1882\n|1897\n|StStZ\n|The private company that opened Z\u00fcrich's first tramway, using horse-drawn [[standard gauge]] ({{RailGauge|sg|disp=or}} gauge) trams.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n|-\n|{{ill|Elektrische Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich|de}}\n|EStZ\n|1894\n|1896\n|StStZ\n|The first electric tram operator, and the first to use [[metre gauge]] ({{RailGauge|1000mm|first=imp|disp=1}} gauge). Bought by the City of Z\u00fcrich, and renamed the StStZ.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n|-\n|{{ill|Zentrale Z\u00fcrichbergbahn|de}}\n|ZZB\n|1895\n|1905\n|StStZ\n|Constructed two electric tramways from near the current [[Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich|Kunsthaus]] to the [[Kirche Fluntern]] and to the lower terminus of the [[Rigiblick funicular]]. Their trams operated through to [[Paradeplatz]] over StStZ tracks, and were eventually acquired by that company.<ref name=tmbzzb>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zzb-D.htm | title = Die Zentrale Z\u00fcrichbergbahn (ZZB), 1894\u20131905 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-12 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901042053/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zzb-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St\u00e4dtische Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich]]\n|StStZ\n|1896\n|1950\n|VBZ\n|Formed by the City of Z\u00fcrich to buy the EStZ. The city owned company continued to acquire other tram operators, until by 1931 it owned all the remaining tramways within the city. In 1950, renamed as the VBZ.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n|-\n|{{ill|Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich-Oerlikon-Seebach|de}}\n|ZOS\n|1897\n|1931\n|StStZ\n|Constructed a tram route from [[Leonhardsplatz]] (now known as Central) to [[Oerlikon (Z\u00fcrich)|Oerlikon]] and [[Seebach (Z\u00fcrich)|Seebach]] via Stampfenbachstrasse and Schaffhauserstrasse. Later additions included an extension from Seebach to [[Glattbrugg]], and a route from Oerlikon to [[Schwamendingen]]. An early connection to the StStZ network was soon removed, and the ZOS operated independently of the city trams until the company was taken over by them in 1931. At the same time, the Oerlikon to Schwamendingen and Seebach to Glattbrugg lines were closed.<ref name=tmbzos>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zos-D.htm | title = Die Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich \u2013 Oerlikon \u2013 Seebach (ZOS), 1897\u20131931 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-12 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901041732/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zos-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{ill|Industriequartier-Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich|de}}\n|IStB\n|1898\n|1903\n|StStZ\n|Constructed a tram route from [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Bahnhofquai]] to [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]]. At Escher-Wyss-Platz, connection was made with the StZH route to [[H\u00f6ngg]], and initially cars ran through from Bahnhofquai to Hongg. However this ceased after 1901, and passengers needed to change trams and rebook at Escher-Wyss-Platz. The company was taken over by the StStZ in 1903, after which through running to Hongg resumed.<ref name=tmbisz>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/istb-D.htm | title = Die Industriequartier Strassenbahn (IStB), 1898 - 1902 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-10 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901042359/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/istb-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{ill|Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich\u2013H\u00f6ngg|de}}\n|StZH\n|1898\n|1923\n|StStZ\n|Constructed a tram route from [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]], with connection to the IStB line to Bahnhofquai, via [[Wipkingen]] to [[Hongg]]. The line was acquired by the StStZ in three phases; firstly in 1907 when the bridge over the [[Limmat river]] to Wipkingen was replaced, then in 1913 when the line as far as Grenzstein Honng was acquired, and finally in 1923 when the rest of the line as far as the terminus at the Wartau depot was acquired.<ref name=tmbstzh>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zh-D.htm | title = Die Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich - H\u00f6ngg (Z-H), 1898 - 1924 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-11 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901042448/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zh-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Dolderbahn]]'''\n|Db\n|1895\n|\n|\n|From 1899, the Dolderbahn company operated an electric tram between the upper station of the Dolderbahn (then a funicular) and the [[Dolder Grand Hotel]]. This line never had any track connection with any other tram line, and was replaced by a bus in 1930. In 1973 the Dolderbahn was converted to a rack railway and extended to the Dolder Grand, thus replacing the bus.\n|-\n|[[Limmattal Strassenbahn]]\n|LSB\n|1900\n|1931\n|StStZ\n|Constructed an interurban line from the former Z\u00fcrich city boundary at Letzigraben, via [[Altstetten (Z\u00fcrich)|Altstetten]] (Farbhof) and [[Schlieren, Switzerland|Schlieren]] to [[Dietikon]], together with a branch from Schlieren to [[Weiningen]]. A connection with the StStZ was made at Letzigraben. The line between Schlieren and Dietikon closed in 1928, whilst that Schlieren and Weiningen closed in 1931, at the same time as the rest of the line from Letzigraben to Schlieren were acquired by the StStZ.<ref name=tmblsb>{{cite web | url =http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/lsb-D.htm | title = Die Limmattal - Strassenbahn (LSB), 1900 - 1931 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-10 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901042018/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/lsb-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Bremgarten-Dietikon-Bahn]]''\n|BD\n|1902\n|2000\n|BDWM\n|Originally constructed as a rural tramway between [[Bremgarten, Switzerland|Bremgarten]] and [[Dietikon]] to the west of Z\u00fcrich. Althyough well outside the city of Z\u00fcrich, it was at one time indirectly connected to the city's tramways by the LSB, which also served Dietikon. The section between Bremgarten and [[Wohlen]] was originally a [[standard gauge]] steam operated railway, which was [[Gauge conversion|converted]] to [[Dual gauge|mixed gauge]] and taken over by BD in 1912.\n|-\n|{{ill|Albisg\u00fctlibahn|de}}\n|AGB\n|1907\n|1925\n|StStZ\n|The last privately owned tramway to be built within the city was built to connect the city tramway at Giessh\u00fcbelstrasse to the site of the federal shooting festival, held at {{ill|Albisg\u00fcetli|de}} in July 1907. Lack of traffic to this, then very rural, location after the festival finished caused the line financial troubles, and in 1913 the line sold three of its five trams to the StStZ. By 1915 the line was operating only on Sundays, and in 1925 the StStZ took over.<ref name=bdagb>{{cite web | url = http://www.bahndaten.ch/content/bahnen-detail/2003/albisgueetli-bahn | title = Albisg\u00fcetli-Bahn | work = Bahndaten | publisher = ViaStoria - University of Bern | accessdate = 16 April 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Wetzikon-Meilen-Bahn]]''\n|WMB\n|1909\n|1950\n|(closed)\n|A rural tramway linking [[Kempten, Switzerland|Kempten]], [[Wetzikon]] and {{ill|Bahnhof Langholz|de|lt=Langholz}} to the east of Z\u00fcrich with [[Meilen]] on the shores of [[Lake Z\u00fcrich]]. Well outside the city of Z\u00fcrich, it was at one time indirectly connected to the city's tramways by the UOeb, with which it connected at Langholz, and hence the FB.<ref name=ebwmb>{{cite web | url = http://www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch/58895/59042.html | title = Wetzikon-Meilen Bahn | publisher = www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch | accessdate = 2013-10-09 | archivedate = 2013-10-17 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017231434/http://www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch/58895/59042.html | url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Uster-Oetwil-Bahn]]''\n|UOeB\n|1909\n|1949\n|(closed)\n|A rural tramway linking [[Uster]], [[Esslingen, Switzerland|Esslingen]], [[Oetwil am See]] and {{ill|Bahnhof Langholz|de|lt=Langholz}} to the east of Z\u00fcrich. Well outside the city of Z\u00fcrich, it was at one time indirectly connected to the city's tramways by the FB, with which it connected at Esslingen.<ref name=ebuoeb>{{cite web | url = http://www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch/58895/1825855.html | title = Uster-Oetwil Bahn | publisher = www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch | accessdate = 2013-10-11 | archivedate = 2013-10-14 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131014234112/http://www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch/58895/1825855.html | url-status = live}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''''[[Forchbahn]]'''''\n|FB\n|1912\n|\n|\n|A line linking line Z\u00fcrich with the towns of [[Esslingen, Switzerland|Esslingen]] and [[Forch]]. The line opened in 1912 as a rural tramway connecting at Rehalp with the city trams, with inter-running as far as the city centre. The line has since been rebuilt with more railway characteristics, and quite substantial trains, but these continue to operate across the city tram network between [[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Stadelhofen]] in the city centre and Rehalp.\n|-\n|'''[[Verkehrsbetriebe Z\u00fcrich]]'''\n|VBZ\n|1950\n|\n|\n|Owned by city of Z\u00fcrich.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n|-\n|'''''[[BDWM Transport AG]]'''''\n|BDWM\n|2000\n|\n|\n|Created by amalgamation of the BD with the bus operator WM. Still operates a light rail service between Dietikon and Wohlen, but is no longer connected to the Z\u00fcrich tram system.\n|-\n|}\n\n===Heyday of the StStZ===\n[[File:Zurich Tram Museum 2011 526a.jpg|thumb|A Swiss Standard Tram, at the city's tramway museum]]\nBy the mid-1930s, the StStZ had acquired all the companies that had operated tramways within the city boundaries, with the single exception of the [[Dolderbahn]], which had closed its short tramway in 1930. The standard gauge horse tram lines had all been converted to metre gauge and electrified. The StStZ had also built many tram extensions, resulting in a dense network of tramlines serving most city neighbourhoods.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nHowever, in 1927, the StStZ had introduced its first [[motor bus]] route, and this was to be followed in 1939 by the first of the [[Trolleybuses in Z\u00fcrich|city's trolleybus routes]]. Initially these modes complemented the trams, but at various times they have threatened to replace parts of the tram system, and sometimes succeeded in doing so.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nIn 1940, the StStZ started a modernisation of its trams, introducing the first prototypes of the {{ill|Swiss Standard Tram|de|Schweizer Standardwagen|fr|Tramway standard suisse}}. Despite Switzerland's neutrality, the economic effects of the [[second world war]] slowed down the program, but by 1953 the VBZ, as the StStZ had become in 1950, had taken delivery of 177 such trams.<ref name=zacait/><ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\n===Lines closed===\n[[File:Wetzikon Meilen Bahn Gr\u00fcningen.JPG|thumb|left|The WMB in Gr\u00fcningen, prior to 1950]]\nWhile the tram network within the city of Z\u00fcrich has seen relatively few line closures, the same cannot be said for the lines beyond the city. The StStZ routinely closed any out-of-city lines belonging to the companies it took over.<ref name=zacait/> In other cases, private sector operated lines succumbed without StStZ involvement. Out of town closures included:\n\n* The Schlieren to Dietikon and Schlieren to Weinigen lines of the LSB company, closed in 1928 and 1931 respectively.<ref name=tmblsb/> \n* The Oerlikon to Schwamendingen and Seebach to Glattbrugg lines of the ZOS company, closed in 1931.<ref name=tmbzos/> \n* The Uster to Langholz line of the UOeB company, closed in 1949.<ref name=ebuoeb/>\n* The Wetzikon to Meilen line of the WMB company, closed in 1950.<ref name=ebwmb/>\n\nIn the city, the initial threat to the tram came from its perceived inflexibility and susceptibility to the growing traffic congestion in the city streets. One proposed solution was the conversion of the less busy lines to trolleybus routes, and the first step in this direction was the conversion of tram route 1, from Burgwies to Hardplatz (1954-1956). This was followed by the Farbhof to Schlieren section of route 2 (1956-8) which became a westward extension of the same trolleybus route. In practice, the trolleybus service struggled to cope with peak loadings and punctuality did not improve. No further conversions of tram routes to trollrybuses have taken place.<ref name=zacait/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Underground proposals===\n[[File:No. 7 Tram, Parade Platz.jpg|thumb|right|A pair of ''Mirage'' trams at Paradeplatz, operating on the surface where they were originally intended to be underground]]\nIn the 1950s, as well as proposing the conversion of less busy lines to trolleybus, plans were also made to place the busier lines in tunnel, in a form called the ''Tiefbahn''. The recently delivered Swiss Standard trams were not seen as suitable for this, because they had doors on their tapered car ends that would not have aligned with the proposed underground station platforms. In order to overcome this limitation, several new designs of tram were introduced. The first design, known as the P16 or ''Karpfen'', could not run on some existing routes, and only one batch of 15 motor tram and trailer pairs was built. A later design, which used articulation to avoid the problems of the P16, was eventually more successful and 126 vehicles were delivered by 1969. This car became popularly known as the ''Mirage''.<ref name=zacait/>\n\nDespite the planning and new rolling stock, a [[referendum]] in 1962 rejected the ''Tiefbahn''. However the proponents of going underground instead proposed a full scale [[metro (rapid transit)|metro]], the [[Z\u00fcrich U-Bahn]] system. This would have been standard gauge and electrified using a third rail, and hence incompatible with the tram system. The lines would have extended further into the suburbs and provided faster transit times than the tramways, which would have been curtailed so as not to compete with the U-Bahn. However this would have been at the expense of a coarser grained network, with much longer distances between U-Bahn stations than between the tram stops they replaced.<ref name=zacait/><ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nIn 1973, the U-Bahn proposal too was rejected in a referendum, but not before several stretches of U-Bahn tunnel had been built. One section of the putative U-Bahn has since been adapted, as described below, for use by trams, whilst another now forms the terminus of the [[Uetliberg railway line|Uetliberg]] and [[Sihltal railway line|Sihltal]] railway lines under the [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Hauptbahnhof]].<ref name=zacait/><ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\n===Extensions and a new model===\n[[File:Zurich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2075 Waldgarten.jpg|thumb|left|Tram 2000 tram at Waldgarten stop in the tunnel section built for the U-Bahn]]\nIn 1976, the first tram extension since 1954 took place, with the extension of route 4 from Hardturm to [[Werdh\u00f6lzli]]. Unlike the older lines, this extension was built mostly on reserved track, a precedent to be followed by most subsequent extensions.<ref name=zacait/>\n\nThe Werdh\u00f6lzli extension was followed in 1986 by the extension of routes 7 and 9 into new residential areas to the north-east of Z\u00fcrich. This used one of the stretches of tunnel that had been built for the rejected U-Bahn, between Milchbuck and Schwamendingen. The tram route was extended through the tunnel before splitting at Schwamendingen to serve the area beyond, using new surface track. Because the tunnels and stations had been built with [[island platform]]s, whilst Z\u00fcrich trams only have doors on their [[Right- and left-hand traffic#Terminology|nearside]], the section through the tunnel uses left-hand running.<ref name=zacait/>\n\nFrom 1976 onwards, the VBZ tram fleet was further updated, with the introduction of Z\u00fcrich's variant of the [[Tram 2000|Tram 2000 design]] used by several Swiss tram systems. Several sub-classes of the Tram 2000 were purchased, including articulated and non-articulated variants, and some without drivers cabs that could only operate in multiple with other cars. Eventually 171 of these vehicles were delivered, with the last of the class delivered in 1992.<ref name=zacait/><ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nFrom the 1980s onwards, the system was increasingly acclaimed for its success in maintaining a high share of the [[modal split]], and the [[Z\u00fcrich model]] of transport provision was named after it. Beyond the tramway, the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn|Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn rail network]] was introduced to serve the region beyond the city boundaries, taking on some of the role that was originally planned for the U-Bahn. In 1990, the city's urban and regional transport were integrated by the introduction of the [[Z\u00fcrcher Verkehrsverbund|ZVV]] and its zone-based common fare structure.<ref name=zacait/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n=== Low floors and the Glattalbahn ===\n[[File:Zurich Be 5-6 Cobra 3002 Letzistrasse.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Cobra (tram)|Bombardier Cobra]] low-floor tram on typical VBZ street track]]\nIn 2001, the VBZ took delivery of the first prototypes of a brand-new low-floor design of tram, known as the [[Cobra (tram)|Cobra]].<ref name=vbzfafch/> Despite many teething problems with the prototypes, which were eventually extensively rebuilt, there are now 88 of these trams in service, with the last delivered in 2010. In order to increase the number of low-floor trams in service, 23 trams from the otherwise high-floor Tram 2000 fleet were rebuilt between 2001 and 2005 with the addition of a low-floor centre section.\n\n[[File:Glatttalbahn - \u00d6rlikerhaus 2011-08-22 19-33-44.JPG|thumb|left|The Glattalbahn]]\nFrom the 1950s onwards, the [[Glattal]] region to the north of Z\u00fcrich experienced a rapid boom as population and industry spilled over from nearby Z\u00fcrich, partly driven by the presence of [[Z\u00fcrich Airport]]. Whilst the airport is served by the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn|city's S-Bahn rail network]], the economic growth and resulting congestion led to a need for a finer-grained form of public transport. The responsible transport authority (the [[Verkehrsbetriebe Glattal]] or VBG) responded by constructing a new light rail system, the [[Stadtbahn Glattal|Glattalbahn]]. This was built to be compatible with Z\u00fcrich's tram network, with which it connects at several points on the city boundary. The system opened in stages between 2006 and 2010. The VBG contracted the VBZ to operate the network, and several tram routes now operate across both networks.<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/><ref name=tuthhqlr>{{cite news | first = C.J. | last = Wansbeek | title = Glattal: High quality light rail to Z\u00fcrich airport | work = [[Tramways & Urban Transit]] | publisher = Ian Allan Ltd / Light Rail Transit Association | pages = 374\u2013376 | date = October 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe arrival of new trams between 2001 and 2010 led to the departure of older vehicles. The ''Karpfen'' last ran in regular service in 2006, and the ''Mirage'' in 2010. Many members of both classes have been transferred to [[Vinnytsia]] in [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web |  first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2006&item=131106b | title = Karpfen farewell tour | date = November 2006 | accessdate = 2012-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |  first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2010&item=300610 | title = Last Mirage day | date = June 2010 | accessdate = 2012-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |  first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2010&item=250810 | title = Karpfen and Mirage in Vinnitsa | date = August 2010 | accessdate = 2012-05-26}}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n=== More extensions ===\n\"Tram Z\u00fcrich West\", an extension from Escher-Wyss-Platz to Bahnhof Altstetten Nord, in the city of Z\u00fcrich, opened in December 2011. The resulting reorganisation of routes included a new route 17 from Hauptbahnhof to Werdh\u00f6lzli via Escher-Wyss-Platz, and the diversion of route 4, which had previously served Werdh\u00f6lzli, to Altstetten.<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2011&item=101211 | title = Opening of Tram Z\u00fcrich West | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = December 2011 | accessdate = 2012-05-27}}</ref> In 2017, route 8 was extended from Hardplatz to Hardturm, via new track over Hardbr\u00fccke, the first tram line to cross the main railway line through Z\u00fcrich.<ref name=amv2030>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2013&item=260713b | title = Vision 2030, looking at VBZ's plans for the future | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = July 2013 | accessdate = 2014-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2017&item=071217 | title = Tram Hardbr\u00fccke opening this weekend, and network changes | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = December 2017 | accessdate = 2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, city route 2 was extended from Farbhof to Geissweid, a distance of {{convert|2.9|km}} with seven stops. The new route operates over the first section of the [[Limmatalbahn]] to open, and replaces [[Trolleybuses in Z\u00fcrich|trolleybus route 31]] over that section. The new tram line operates over the first section of the [[Limmattalbahn]] to open. Once that the Limmatalbahn is completed, it will also carry a separate regional service from Bahnhof Altstetten to [[Killwangen-Spreitenbach]], although that service will not form part of the city tram network and will be operated by the [[BDWM]].<ref name=rgifpl>{{cite news |url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/projects-and-planning/first-phase-of-limmattalbahn-opens-in-zurich/54477.article| title=First phase of Limmattalbahn opens in Z\u00fcrich |work=Railway Gazette International |date=2019-09-03 |accessdate=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n===History preserved===\nThe [[Z\u00fcrich Tram Museum]], located at the former tram depot at Burgwies (on tram route 11), preserves many examples of Z\u00fcrich's former tramcar fleet, along with other related exhibits.\n\n==Operation==\n\n===Route network===\n[[File:Tramnetz-zuerich2.png|thumb|Tram network in Z\u00fcrich (from ? until the change of timetable in the year 2017 when the Hardbr\u00fccke tram was opened)]]\n[[File:Z\u00fcrich Paradeplatz.jpg|thumb|Paradeplatz is one of the key nodes of the route network, served by 7 routes]]\nThe following tram routes make up the urban and Glattalbahn route network:<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/><ref name=zurmap>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/dam/stzh/vbz/Deutsch/Ueber%20das%20Departement/Publikationen%20und%20Broschueren/Fahrplan/liniennetzplaene/Stadt%20Zuerich.pdf | title = Stadt Z\u00fcrich - Z\u00fcrich City - Transport Map | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2016-10-11}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; font-size:95%; margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;\"\n!Route\n!Description (''Portion of route in italics is on Glattalbahn track'')\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#D8232A | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''2'''</big></span>\n| [[Z\u00fcrich Tiefenbrunnen railway station|Bhf. Tiefenbrunnen]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Stauffacher]] - Albisriederplatz - Farbhof - [[Schlieren]] Geissweid\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#009F4A | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''3'''</big></span>\n| Klusplatz - R\u00f6merhof - [[Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich|Kunsthaus]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Stauffacher]] - Albisriederplatz - [[Albisrieden]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#3E4085 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''4'''</big></span>\n| [[Z\u00fcrich Tiefenbrunnen railway station|Bhf. Tiefenbrunnen]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]] - [[Altstetten railway station|Bhf. Altstetten]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#855B37 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''5'''</big></span>\n| (Laubegg -) [[Z\u00fcrich Enge railway station|Bhf. Enge]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich|Kunsthaus]] - Kirche Fluntern (- [[Zoo Z\u00fcrich|Zoo]])\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#DA9F4F | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''6'''</big></span>\n| [[Werdh\u00f6lzli]] - [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[ETH Z\u00fcrich|ETH]]/[[University Hospital of Z\u00fcrich|Universit\u00e4tsspital]] - [[Kirche Fluntern]] - [[Zoo Z\u00fcrich|Zoo]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#191919 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''7'''</big></span>\n| [[Stettbach railway station|Bhf. Stettbach]] - [[Schwamendingerplatz]] - Milchbuck - Schaffhauserplatz - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Enge railway station|Bhf. Enge]] - [[Wollishofen]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#86CD16 | <big>'''8'''</big>\n| [[Hardturm]] - [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hardbr\u00fccke railway station|Bhf. Hardbr\u00fccke]] - Hardplatz - [[Stauffacher]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Selnau railway station|Bhf. Selnau]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Bhf.Stadelhofen]] - Kreuzplatz - R\u00f6merhof - Klusplatz) \n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#3E4085 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''9'''</big></span>\n| [[Hirzenbach]] - Schwamendingerplatz - Milchbuck - [[Seilbahn Rigiblick]] - [[ETH Z\u00fcrich|ETH]]/[[University Hospital of Z\u00fcrich|Universit\u00e4tsspital]] - [[Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich|Kunsthaus]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Stauffacher]] - Heuried (- Triemli)\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#DA3987 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''10'''</big></span>\n| (Albisg\u00fctli - Laubegg - [[Z\u00fcrich Enge railway station|Bhf. Enge]] - [[Paradeplatz]] -) [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[ETH Z\u00fcrich|ETH]]/[[University Hospital of Z\u00fcrich|Universit\u00e4tsspital]] - Seilbahn Rigiblick - Milchbuck - Sternen Oerlikon - [[Z\u00fcrich Oerlikon railway station|Bhf. Oerlikon Ost]] - ''[[Glattpark]]'' - ''[[Glattbrugg railway station|Bhf. Glattbrugg]]'' - ''[[Z\u00fcrich Flughafen, Bahnhof]]''\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#009F4A | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''11'''</big></span>\n| [[Z\u00fcrich Rehalp railway station|Rehalp]] - Kreuzplatz - [[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Bhf. Stadelhofen]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]]  - Schaffhauserplatz - Bucheggplatz - [[Z\u00fcrich Oerlikon railway station|Bhf. Oerlikon]] - Sternen Oerlikon - Messe/[[Hallenstadion]] - ''[[Glattpark]]'' - ''Auzelg'' \n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#7ACAD4 | <big>'''12'''</big>\n| ''[[Z\u00fcrich Flughafen, Bahnhof]]'' - ''[[Glattbrugg railway station|Bhf.Glattbrugg]]'' - ''[[Glattpark]]'' - ''Auzelg'' - ''[[Wallisellen railway station|Bhf. Wallisellen]]'' - ''[[Glattzentrum]]'' - [[Stettbach railway station|Bhf. Stettbach]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#FBD01F | <big>'''13'''</big>\n| Albisg\u00fctli - Laubegg - [[Z\u00fcrich Enge railway station|Bhf. Enge]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]] - Meierhofplatz - Frankental\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#00A4DB | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''14'''</big></span>\n| [[Seebach (Z\u00fcrich)|Seebach]] - Sternen Oerlikon - Milchbuck - Schaffhauserplatz - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Stauffacher]] - Heuried - [[Stadtspital Triemli|Triemli]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#D8232A | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''15'''</big></span>\n|[[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Bhf. Stadelhofen]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - Schaffhauserplatz - Bucheggplatz\n|-\n|}\n[[File:Forchbahn Be 4-6 Kreuzplatz.jpg|thumb|left|A Forchbahn train on Z\u00fcrich tram tracks]]\n<br/>\nAll journeys on routes 6, 10 and 12 are operated by low-floor trams, whilst at least every other journey on lines 2, 3, 4, 7, 9, 11, 13 and 14 are provided by such vehicles. Most, but not all, tram stops are configured to allow passengers in [[wheelchair]]s to board low-floor trams.<ref name=gpw/>\n\nOf the three routes that operate in part over Glattalbahn tracks, routes 10 and 12 are operated by the VBZ on behalf of the [[Verkehrsbetriebe Glattal]] (VBG), normally using tramcars in the VBG's own predominantly white colour scheme, whilst route 11 is operated by the VBZ on its own behalf, normally using vehicles in its own livery.<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/><ref name=tuthhqlr/>\n\nThe independent [[Forchbahn]] (FB) railway uses VBZ trackwork to reach their city centre terminus, at [[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Bahnhof Stadelhofen]], from the eastern edge of the city, at Rehalp. The FB trains operate largely in the street for this section of their route, sharing track with VBZ tram routes, but are categorised as route [[S18 (ZVV)|S18]] of the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn|city's S-Bahn railway network]] rather than as part of the tram network. Beyond Rehalp the trains use the FB's own segregated tracks to reach their outer terminus at [[Esslingen, Switzerland|Esslingen]].<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/>\n\nOn the last weekend of each month, the [[Z\u00fcrich Tram Museum]] operates tram route 21 from the city centre to the museum at Burgwies (up to Rehalp at Saturdays), using their own heritage rolling stock.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum.ch/content.php?id=5&lang=en | title = The Museum Line 21 | publisher = Z\u00fcrich Tram Museum | accessdate=2012-05-09}}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Infrastructure===\n[[File:Z\u00fcrich - Stadelhoferplatz IMG 4441.JPG|thumb|Raised platforms for use with low-floor trams, being used by a high-floor tram]]\nZ\u00fcrich's tram network is built to [[metre gauge]] ({{RailGauge|1000mm|first=imp|disp=1}} gauge). There are {{convert|171.9|km|mi}} of track, equating to a network length of {{convert|72.9|km|mi}} and a total route length of {{convert|118.7|km|mi}}. The tracks are electrified using [[overhead line]] at 600 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]], utilising a supply system shared with the [[Trolleybuses in Z\u00fcrich|city's trolleybus network]].<ref name=\"figures\">{{cite web |url=https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/portraet/zahlen_fakten/linien.html |title=Startseite VBZ - Die VBZ - Portr\u00e4t - Zahlen & Fakten - Linien |publisher=Stadt Z\u00fcrich [City of Z\u00fcrich] |language=German |trans-title=Home VBZ - VBZ - Portrait - Facts & Figures - Lines |date= |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref><ref name=saw/>\n\nThe VBZ infrastructure within Z\u00fcrich is largely street based, with varying degrees of segregation from other street traffic and significant sections where trams run in unrestricted traffic lanes. In the city centre the tram tracks run through largely pedestrianised streets, and in one place in the suburbs the trams use a tunnel originally constructed for the never completed [[Z\u00fcrich U-Bahn]] system. By contrast, on VBG infrastructure in the Stadtbahn Glattal, VBZ trams operate on long stretches of dedicated track.<ref name=gpw>{{cite web | title = Gleisplan - Stra\u00dfenbahn Z\u00fcrich mit Glattal |  url = http://www.gleisplanweb.eu/Maps/Zuerich.pdf | language = German | trans-title = Trackplan - Z\u00fcrich with Glattal | date = 2014-01-23 | accessdate = 2014-06-21}}</ref><ref name=saw/>\n\nMany of Z\u00fcrich's tram stops have been equipped with boarding platforms raised to match the floor height of the low floor trams, although there are still examples of stops where passengers must board from street level. Z\u00fcrich's trams are single-ended, with doors on only one side, although Forchbahn trains are double-ended and double-sided. In consequence all terminal locations are equipped with [[turning loop]]s, and all tram stops are to the [[Right- and left-hand traffic#Terminology|nearside]] of the tram.<ref name=gpw/>\n\n===Depots and workshops===\n[[File:Tramdepot Zuerich 1911 Friedrich Fissler.jpg|thumb|left|The tram depot at Hard was built in 1911]]\nZ\u00fcrich's tram fleet is kept in the five operational depots of Hard, Irchel, Kalkbreite, Oerlikon and  Wollishofen, together with a permanent way yard at Hardturm. Whilst these depots have the capability to undertake minor maintenance, heavier maintenance is the responsibility of the VBZ's central workshop at Altstetten. This is connected to the tram network, and also has a rail connection to the [[Swiss Federal Railway]] system, allowing the delivery of infrastructure items and vehicles by rail.<ref name=gpw/><ref name=zws>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/produkte_dienstleistungen/werkstatt.html | title = Werkstatt | language = German | trans-title = Workshop | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-02-17}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the above depots and workshops, two other former tram depots, at Burgweis and Wartau, are also still connected to the tram network. Burgweis depot now houses the [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] main collection, whilst Wartau is used as a workshop by that organisation. The rail connections permit the occasional operation of preserved trams on the VBZ network.<ref name=gpw/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Tram fleet===\nAs of 2012, the VBZ owns 313 tram vehicles, which between them cover over 16 million vehicle-kilometres per year. All regular public services are covered by 289 vehicles of two basic classes, with the remainder of the fleet made up of a number of assorted works vehicles, including some used for the cargo tram service, and heritage vehicles. The heritage fleet sees occasional use on special services.<ref name=vbzfafveh>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/vehicles.html | title = VBZ - Portrait - Facts & figures - Vehicles | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-04 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121007014744/http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/vehicles.html | archivedate = 2012-10-07 }}</ref><ref name=vbzfafser>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/service.html | title = VBZ - Portrait - Facts & figures - Service | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-04}}</ref>\n\nThe tram fleet comprises the following vehicles:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; font-size:95%; margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;\"\n!Image\n!Numbers\n!Type\n![[Swiss locomotive and railcar classification|Notation]]\n!Capacity<br>Sit/Stand\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[File:Zurich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2034 Bellevue.jpg|200px|Z\u00fcrich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2034 Bellevue]]\n|2001-2098\n|Tram&nbsp;2000\n|Be 4/6\n|50/54\n|The two section articulated variant of the [[Tram 2000|Tram 2000 design]] for Z\u00fcrich, of which 98 vehicles were delivered in two stages from 1976 to 1978, and from 1985 to 1987. Each vehicle is {{convert|21.4|m}} in length and {{convert|2.2|m}} in width. In most cases these cars operate in multiple.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzveht20>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/fahrzeuge/unsere_fahrzeuge/trams/tram2000.html | title = VBZ - Fahrzeuge - Unsere Fahrzeuge - Trams - Tram 2000 | language = German | trans-title = VBZ - Vehicles - Our vehicles - Trams - Tram 2000 | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Zurich Be 4-8 Saenfte 2110 Milchbuck.jpg|200px|A Tram 2000 tram with low-floor centre section]]\n|2099-2121\n|Tram 2000\n|Be 4/8\n|68/75\n|Originally two section units similar to 2001-2098, these cars were built from 1992 to 1993. Between 1999 and 2005 they were rebuilt with a third central low-floor section. Each vehicle is {{convert|28|m}} in length and {{convert|2.2|m}} in width. They are also known as ''S\u00e4nfte''.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzveht20/><ref name=vbzveht2s>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/fahrzeuge/unsere_fahrzeuge/trams/tram2000_saenfte.html | title = VBZ - Fahrzeuge - Unsere Fahrzeuge - Trams - Tram 2000 S\u00e4nfte | language = German | trans-title = VBZ - Vehicles - Our vehicles - Trams - Tram 2000 S\u00e4nfte | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-29}}</ref> \n|-\n|[[File:Zurich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2303 Seebach.jpg|200px|Z\u00fcrich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2303 Seebach]]\n|2301-2315\n|Tram 2000\n|Be 4/6\n|50/57\n|Two section articulated unit similar to 2001-2098 but without a drivers cab. These cars were built in 1978, and must run as the second unit in multiple with another Tram 2000 unit. Each vehicle is {{convert|21.4|m}} in length and {{convert|2.2|m}} in width.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzveht20/>\n|-\n|[[File:Zurich Be 2-4 Pony 2415 Klusplatz.jpg|200px|A single-section Tram 2000 ''Pony'' car]]\n|2401-2435\n|Tram 2000\n|Be 2/4\n|35/41\n|Single section non-articulated unit without a drivers cab. These cars were built in two stages from 1985 to 1987, and 1992 to 1993. Like 2301-2315, they must run as the second unit in multiple with another Tram 2000 unit. Each vehicle is {{convert|15.4|m}} in length and {{convert|2.2|m}} in width. They are also known as ''Pony''.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzveht20/>\n|-\n|[[File:Zurichcobratram.jpg|200px|A [[Cobra (tram)|Bombardier Cobra]] low-floor tram on typical VBZ street track]]\n|3001-3088\n|Cobra\n|Be 5/6\n|90/113\n|The more recent of the two classes of trams in regular service are the 88 modern low-floor [[Cobra (tram)|Bombardier Cobra]] trams delivered between 2001 and 2010. 18 of them (3062-3079) were in VBG livery. These are all five section articulated vehicles running on six pairs of wheels, of which five are powered. Each vehicle is {{convert|36|m}} in length and {{convert|2.4|m}} in width. Because of their length, Cobras only run as single units in normal service.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzvehcob>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/fahrzeuge/unsere_fahrzeuge/trams/cobra.html | title = VBZ - Fahrzeuge - Unsere Fahrzeuge - Trams - Cobra | language = German | trans-title = VBZ - Vehicles - Our vehicles - Trams - Cobra   | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-29}}</ref> \n|-\n|}\n\n===Fares and tickets===\n[[File:Ticket machine at Zurich Airport tram stop 03.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Ticket machine]]\nLike the rest of the VBZ network, Z\u00fcrich's tram network operates on a [[proof-of-payment]] system. All tram stops are equipped with ticket machines, and passengers are required to purchase a ticket before boarding the vehicle. Passengers may board through any door and are not required to show tickets on boarding. Instead, tickets are randomly checked by roving teams of fare inspectors, and fines are imposed on passengers found without one.<ref name=vbzatm>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/tickets/fare_zone_system.html | title = VBZ - Automatic ticket machine | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-21}}</ref>\n\nTram services are operated within the fare and ticketing system provided by the cantonal public transport authority, the [[Z\u00fcrcher Verkehrsverbund]] (ZVV). This system covers the whole of the [[canton of Z\u00fcrich]] and thus covers travel on other modes and services, provided by many other operators, and includes the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn]] suburban rail network. Free transfer is permitted between different vehicles, routes, modes and operators, provided a ticket valid for the whole journey is held.<ref name=vbzfzs>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/tickets/fare_zone_system.html | title = VBZ - Fare zone system | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-21}}</ref>\n\nThe ZVV system is zone-based, with fares for individual journeys set by the zones the journey passes through. The Z\u00fcrich tram network extends over just two of these zones, with zone 110 covering the city routes, and zone 121 covering the Stadtbahn Glattal routes. Both single journey and day tickets are available, as are a number of passes with longer validities.<ref name=vbzfzs/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.zvv.ch/export/sites/default/common-images/content-image-gallery/linien-zonen-pdfs/Tarifzonen_Kanton_Zuerich_2011.pdf | title = Tarifzonen - Fare zones | publisher = ZVV | accessdate = 2012-06-18}}</ref>\n\n===Cargo tram===\n[[File:Cargo Tram outside Zurich Hauptbahnhof.JPG|thumb|left|The cargo tram]]\nBesides its passenger transport activities, VBZ, jointly with the city refuse and recycling department ERZ, operates the cargo tram to collect bulky waste. The cargo tram serves 10 different collection points around Z\u00fcrich, calling at each on different days of the month. The collected refuse is taken to a specially constructed siding at the ERZ yard adjacent to the Werdh\u00f6lzli tram terminus.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/produkte_dienstleistungen/cargo_tram_und_etram.html | title = Cargo- und E-Tram | language = German | trans-title = Cargo- and E-Tram | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-09 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120829085657/http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/produkte_dienstleistungen/cargo_tram_und_etram.html | archivedate = 2012-08-29 }}</ref><ref name=amcargo>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/cargotram.html | title = Cargotram -  Z\u00fcrich's domestic refuse takes to the rails | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | date = August 2003 | accessdate = 2013-07-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2014&item=140114 | title = Cargotram serves additional destination | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | date = 2014-01-14 | accessdate = 2014-02-06}}</ref>\n\nThe service was introduced in 2003, as an attempt to reduce the amount of bulky waste items dumped illegally every year. As Z\u00fcrich has an extensive tram network serving most neighbourhoods, and many suitable sidings not used by regular services, it was decided to use the tram network. In its first year of operation it was responsible for the collection of {{convert|380|tonnes}} of waste.<ref name=amcargo/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2004&item=160404 | title = Cargo tram is a success! | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | date = April 2004 | accessdate = 2013-07-14}}</ref>\n\nThe collected waste is carried in two standard refuse containers, which are mounted on four-wheeled flat wagons. These are hauled by car 1922, a former Swiss Standard Tram, originally delivered to Z\u00fcrich in 1940, and converted into a works car in 1980.<ref name=amcargo/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Future developments==\n\n===New vehicles===\n[[File:Tango als Tram in Z\u00fcrich beim Paradeplatz.jpg|thumb|A Stadler Tango on trial in Paradeplatz]]\nThe VBZ has long intended to order a new generation of tram cars, to replace the high-floor Tram 2000 trams currently in service. By 2010, it had conducted trials of three existing tram types on its network. These were the [[Stadler Tango]], the [[Siemens Combino]] and the [[Bombardier Flexity]]. It then requested tenders for the supply of 30 new trams, together with an option for the supply of a further 70 vehicles. The first trams were to be delivered in December 2016, and were to be 100% low floor with capacity for at least 225 passengers. In response, by April 2013 five suppliers had submitted bids. As of February 2015, no decision had been made as to which supplier to select, with reports of conflict between city and canton authorities.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?item=210610a | title = Tango, Combino or Flexity? | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = June 2010 | accessdate = 2013-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?item=201112 | title = New tram order: The ball is rolling | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = November 2012 | accessdate = 2013-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2013&item=080413 | title = Five suppliers vie for tram contract | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = April 2013 | accessdate = 2013-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2015&item=260215 | title = More gloom over tram order | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = February 2015 | accessdate = 2015-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, it was announced that VBZ had awarded a contract worth 358 million [[Swiss Franc]]s to [[Bombardier Transportation]] for the supply of 70<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/tram-zuerich-flexity-kommt-erst-im-sommer-2020-zum-einsatz-ld.1524125 | title = Das erste Flexity-Tram kurvt durch Z\u00fcrich \u2013 aber Passagiere d\u00fcrfen noch lange nicht mitfahren | language = German |  work =  Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung | date = 25 November 2019 | accessdate = 25 November 2019}}</ref> 7-section [[Flexity 2]] trams, with an option for a further 70, to be delivered between 2018 and 2023. The new trams will be {{convert|43|m}} long and {{convert|2.4|m}} wide, and be capable of carrying 90 seated and 186 standing passengers. Both [[Stadler Rail]] and [[Siemens]] filed complaints with the [[Administrative Court of the Canton of Z\u00fcrich]], causing the finalisation of the contract to be suspended, but the court ruled in February 2017 that VBZ could conclude the contract with Bombardier. After both Stadler and Siemens decided not to appeal this decision to the [[Federal Supreme Court of Switzerland]], the contract was finally signed on 2 March 2017.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://mobile2.tagesanzeiger.ch/articles/573af28cab5c371886000001 | title = So sieht das neue Z\u00fcri-Tram aus | language = German | trans-title = Looks like the new Z\u00fcrich tram | work = Tages Anzeiger | date = 17 May 2016 | accessdate = 17 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Z\u00fcrich orders 70 Flexity 2 trams | url = http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/news/europe/single-view/view/zuerich-orders-70-flexity-2-trams.html | work = Railway Gazette | date = 18 May 2016 | publisher = DVV Media UK Ltd | accessdate = 18 May 2016 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160518151231/http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/news/europe/single-view/view/zuerich-orders-70-flexity-2-trams.html | archivedate = 18 May 2016 | url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/medien/medienmitteilungen/trambeschaffung0.html |title=Trambeschaffung: Keine aufschiebende Wirkung der Beschwerden |language=German |trans-title=Tram procurement: No suspensory effect of the complaints |publisher=City of Z\u00fcrich |date=21 February 2017 |accessdate=27 February 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227110556/https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/medien/medienmitteilungen/trambeschaffung0.html |archivedate=27 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/aktuelles/Trambeschaffung1.html |title=Vertrag unterschrieben |language=German |trans-title=Contract signed |publisher=City of Z\u00fcrich |date=2 March 2017 |accessdate=3 March 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303112240/https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/aktuelles/Trambeschaffung1.html |archivedate=3 March 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=tr256>{{cite news | first = Christian | last = Ammann | title = Z\u00fcrich's Bombardier order confirmed | work = Today's Railways | publisher = Platform 5 Publishing Ltd | pages = 16 | date = April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===System expansion===\nIn the Limmat Valley, between [[Altstetten railway station|Bahnhof Altstetten]] and [[Killwangen-Spreitenbach railway station|Bahnhof Killwangen-Spreitenbach]], the [[Limmattal light rail line]] is under construction and should be partially opened by 2020. A referendum, held in November 2015, approved the construction of the line, and it was announced in May 2016 that it would be operated by [[BDWM Transport|BDWM]]. The line will connect to the VBZ tram system at Farbhof, the current terminus of route 2, and that route will be extended over the light rail line as far as [[Schlieren, Switzerland|Schlieren]], as a partial replacement for [[Z\u00fcrich trolleybus route 31|trolleybus route 31]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2010&item=030310a |title=Limmattalbahn |first=Andrew |last=Moglestue |date=March 2010 |accessdate=31 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531124735/http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2010&item=030310a |archivedate=31 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/aktuell/zuerich-sagt-ja-zur-limmattalbahn-ld.3186 |first1=Stefan |last1=Hotz |first2=Andr\u00e9 |last2=M\u00fcller |title=Nur das Limmattal selbst stimmt gegen \u00absein\u00bb neues Tram |language=German |trans-title=Only the Limmattal itself voted against \"its\" new tram |work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung |date=22 November 2015 |accessdate=27 February 2017 |archivedate=28 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228082218/https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/aktuell/zuerich-sagt-ja-zur-limmattalbahn-ld.3186}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/aktuell/bdwm-transport-ag-aargauer-betreiben-zuercher-limmattalbahn-ld.82405 |first=Corsin |last=Zander |title=Aargauer betreiben Z\u00fcrcher Limmattalbahn |language=German |trans-title=Aargau company to operate Z\u00fcrcher Limmattalbahn |work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung |date=13 May 2016 |accessdate=27 February 2017 |archivedate=28 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228075100/https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/aktuell/bdwm-transport-ag-aargauer-betreiben-zuercher-limmattalbahn-ld.82405}}</ref>\n\nThere are also plans for a number of other extensions to be built up to 2025.<ref name=amv2030/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Trains|Switzerland}}\n*[[List of railway companies in Switzerland]]\n*[[List of town tramway systems in Switzerland]]\n*[[Trolleybuses in Z\u00fcrich]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Bernet-Trams-Schweiz}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bodmer |first=Hans |title=Das Tram in Z\u00fcrich 1928 bis 1962 |trans-title=The Tram in Z\u00fcrich 1928 to 1962 |year=2011 |publisher=Sutton Verlag GmbH |location=Erfurt |isbn=9783866809291 |language=de}}\n*{{cite book |last=Galliker |first=Hans-Rudolf |title=Tramstadt: Verkehrsplanung, \u00f6ffentlicher Nahverkehr und Stadtentwicklung am Beispiel der Stadt Z\u00fcrich |trans-title=Tram City: Transport Planning, Local Public Transport and Urban Development with the City of Z\u00fcrich as an Example |year=1997 |publisher=Chronos-Verlag |location=Z\u00fcrich |isbn=3905312026 |language=de}}\n*{{Schwandl-TAtlas-Schweiz}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tram transport in Z\u00fcrich}}\n*[http://www.vbz.ch VBZ official website]\n*[http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich Trams of Z\u00fcrich unofficial website]\n*[https://www.gleisplanweb.eu/Map-e.php?Map=Zuerich Track plan of the Z\u00fcrich tram system]\n*[http://www.tram-museum.ch Tram Museum Z\u00fcrich website]\n*{{Urban Electric Transit | id = 222 | title = Zurich | tram = yes}}\n\n{{Public transport in Z\u00fcrich}}\n{{Urban public transport in Switzerland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trams in Zurich}}\n[[Category:Public transport in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Tram transport in Switzerland|Zurich]]\n[[Category:Transport in Z\u00fcrich]]\n[[Category:1882 establishments in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Metre gauge railways in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:600 V DC railway electrification]]\n[[Category:Town tramway systems by city|Zurich]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox tram network\n| name                          = Trams in Z\u00fcrich\n| image                         = Bahnhofstrasse - Uraniastrasse - Beatengasse 2010-08-27 19-07-46 ShiftN.jpg\n| image_width                   = 250px\n| caption                       = Bahnhofstrasse, Z\u00fcrich's premier shopping street\n<!-- Operation -->\n| locale                        = [[Z\u00fcrich]]\n| open                          = 1882\n| status                        = Operational\n| routes                        = 15<ref name=gpw/>\n| owner                         = City of Z\u00fcrich\n| operator                      = [[Verkehrsbetriebe Z\u00fcrich]]\n<!-- Infrastructure -->\n| gauge                         = {{RailGauge|1000mm|allk=on}}\n| propulsion_system             = Electric\n| el                            = 600 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]] [[overhead line|overhead]]\n| stock                         = 258\n| total_track_length            = {{convert|171.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"figures\" />\n| double_track_length           = {{convert|72.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"figures\"/>\n| route_length                  = {{convert|118.7|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"figures\"/>\n| pass_year                     = 2012\n| passengers                    = 205.0 million<ref name=\"passengers\">{{cite web |url=https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/portraet/zahlen_fakten/fahrgastzahlen.html |title=Startseite VBZ - Die VBZ - Portr\u00e4t - Zahlen & Fakten - Fahrgastzahlen |publisher=Stadt Z\u00fcrich [City of Z\u00fcrich] |language=German |trans-title=Home VBZ - VBZ - Portrait - Facts & Figures - Ridership |date= |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref>\n| map                           = [[Image:Tramnetz Z\u00fcrich.png|350px]]\n| website                       = http://www.vbz.ch/ www.vbz.ch\n}}\nTrams make an important contribution to public transport in the city of [[Z\u00fcrich]] in [[Switzerland]]. The [[tram]] network serves most city neighbourhoods, and is the backbone of public transport within the city, albeit supplemented by the inner sections of the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn]], along with urban [[trolleybus]] and [[bus]] routes as well as two [[funicular]] railways and one [[rack railway]]. The trams and other city transport modes operate within a fare regime provided by the cantonal public transport authority [[Z\u00fcrcher Verkehrsverbund]] (ZVV), which also covers regional rail and bus services.<ref name=tutttctlr>{{cite news | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | title = Z\u00fcrich: Top city \u2014 thanks to light rail | work = [[Tramways & Urban Transit]] | publisher = Ian Allan Ltd / Light Rail Transit Association | pages = 130\u2013134 | date = April 2005}}</ref><ref name=tuttcraag>{{cite news | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | title =  Z\u00fcrich: The Cobra rules, all above ground | work = [[Tramways & Urban Transit]] | publisher = Ian Allan Ltd / Light Rail Transit Association | pages = 180\u2013184 | date = May 2005}}</ref><ref name=zacait>{{cite web |  first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/zurich05_0.html | title = Z\u00fcrich: A city and its trams | date = December 2005 | accessdate = 2011-08-10}}</ref>\n\nThe city's trams are operated by the [[Verkehrsbetriebe Z\u00fcrich]] (VBZ), which also manages the tramway infrastructure within the city, but the city's tram tracks are also used by two other operations. The [[Stadtbahn Glattal|Glattalbahn]] tram services to the [[Glattal]] area to the north of the city interwork with the city tram services and are also operated by the VBZ, although in this case it does so as a sub-contractor to the [[Verkehrsbetriebe Glattal]] (VBG). Trains of the independent [[Forchbahn]] (FB) light railway also use the city's tram lines to reach their city centre terminus.<ref name=saw>{{cite book | title = Eisenbahnatlas Schweiz | year = 2012 | publisher = Verlag Schweers + Wall GmbH | isbn=978-3-89494-130-7 | pages = 64\u201365}}</ref>\n\nTrams have been a consistent part of Z\u00fcrich's streetscape since the 1880s, when the first horse tram ran. Electrified from the 1890s, they have seen off challenges including proposals to replace them by [[trolleybuses]] and by a [[metro (rapid transit)|metro]] or [[U-Bahn]]. With a relatively static city network from the 1930s to the late 1970s, the city's trams have been expanding again since then. Recent expansions have taken the network into the suburbs beyond the city boundary, covering areas it retreated from in the first part of the 20th century. Further extensions have been approved, both to the city tram network itself, and by the introduction of a [[Limmattal light rail line|new light rail system]] in the [[Limmat Valley]] that will interwork with the city trams.\n\n==History==\n\n===Beginnings===\n[[File:R\u00f6sslitram.jpg|thumb|left|One of Z\u00fcrich's horse trams  in 1900]]\nVarious projects to introduce trams to Z\u00fcrich were proposed from the 1860s onwards. It was not until 1882, however, that the first tram operated in the city. These initial trams were operated by the {{ill|Z\u00fcrcher Strassenbahn Gesellschaft|de}} (ZStG), a private company, and were of [[standard gauge]] ({{RailGauge|sg|disp=or}} gauge) and horse-drawn.<ref name=vbzfafch>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/corporate_history.html | title = Facts & figures - Corporate history | publisher = VBZ | accessdate = 2012-05-26 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121007013822/http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/corporate_history.html | archivedate = 2012-10-07 }}</ref>\n\nBy 1888 the first electric tramway in Switzerland (the [[Vevey\u2013Montreux\u2013Chillon tramway]]) had opened, and, in 1894, another private company, the {{ill|Elektrische Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich|de}} (EStZ), started operating [[metre gauge]] ({{RailGauge|1000mm|first=imp|disp=1}} gauge) electric trams in Z\u00fcrich. The EStZ only survived for two years before it was taken over by the City of Z\u00fcrich, who renamed it the [[St\u00e4dtische Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich]] (StStZ). The following year, the horse trams of the ZStG were acquired.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nFurther tramway companies were founded, some operating entirely within the city, some connecting the city with its nearer suburbs, and some running in rural areas entirely beyond the city, but still linked by connections with other lines to the city. Like the EStZ, all these lines were electrified and were built to the metre gauge. The StStZ gradually took over those companies that had significant city operations, usually closing any cross-boundary lines, whilst leaving those lines entirely beyond the city to their own devices.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Many companies===\n[[File:Zuercher Strassenbahnlinien um 1899.jpg|thumb|The mix of routes in 1899, distinguishing city owned (''Stadt'') and private (''Privat''), and horse (''Pferdebahn'') and electric (''elektrisch'')]]\nThe many companies that operated trams in and around Z\u00fcrich are summarised in the table below. Names of companies whose lines were entirely outside the current city boundaries are shown in ''italic'' type, and those which still operate tram or other light rail services are shown in '''bold''' type.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; font-size:95%; margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;\"\n!Company\n!Abbreviation\n!From\n!Until\n!Absorbed by\n!Notes\n|-\n|{{ill|Z\u00fcrcher Strassenbahn Gesellschaft|de}}\n|ZStG\n|1882\n|1897\n|StStZ\n|The private company that opened Z\u00fcrich's first tramway, using horse-drawn [[standard gauge]] ({{RailGauge|sg|disp=or}} gauge) trams.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n|-\n|{{ill|Elektrische Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich|de}}\n|EStZ\n|1894\n|1896\n|StStZ\n|The first electric tram operator, and the first to use [[metre gauge]] ({{RailGauge|1000mm|first=imp|disp=1}} gauge). Bought by the City of Z\u00fcrich, and renamed the StStZ.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n|-\n|{{ill|Zentrale Z\u00fcrichbergbahn|de}}\n|ZZB\n|1895\n|1905\n|StStZ\n|Constructed two electric tramways from near the current [[Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich|Kunsthaus]] to the [[Kirche Fluntern]] and to the lower terminus of the [[Rigiblick funicular]]. Their trams operated through to [[Paradeplatz]] over StStZ tracks, and were eventually acquired by that company.<ref name=tmbzzb>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zzb-D.htm | title = Die Zentrale Z\u00fcrichbergbahn (ZZB), 1894\u20131905 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-12 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901042053/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zzb-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-21}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[St\u00e4dtische Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich]]\n|StStZ\n|1896\n|1950\n|VBZ\n|Formed by the City of Z\u00fcrich to buy the EStZ. The city owned company continued to acquire other tram operators, until by 1931 it owned all the remaining tramways within the city. In 1950, renamed as the VBZ.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n|-\n|{{ill|Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich-Oerlikon-Seebach|de}}\n|ZOS\n|1897\n|1931\n|StStZ\n|Constructed a tram route from [[Leonhardsplatz]] (now known as Central) to [[Oerlikon (Z\u00fcrich)|Oerlikon]] and [[Seebach (Z\u00fcrich)|Seebach]] via Stampfenbachstrasse and Schaffhauserstrasse. Later additions included an extension from Seebach to [[Glattbrugg]], and a route from Oerlikon to [[Schwamendingen]]. An early connection to the StStZ network was soon removed, and the ZOS operated independently of the city trams until the company was taken over by them in 1931. At the same time, the Oerlikon to Schwamendingen and Seebach to Glattbrugg lines were closed.<ref name=tmbzos>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zos-D.htm | title = Die Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich \u2013 Oerlikon \u2013 Seebach (ZOS), 1897\u20131931 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-12 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901041732/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zos-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{ill|Industriequartier-Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich|de}}\n|IStB\n|1898\n|1903\n|StStZ\n|Constructed a tram route from [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Bahnhofquai]] to [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]]. At Escher-Wyss-Platz, connection was made with the StZH route to [[H\u00f6ngg]], and initially cars ran through from Bahnhofquai to Hongg. However this ceased after 1901, and passengers needed to change trams and rebook at Escher-Wyss-Platz. The company was taken over by the StStZ in 1903, after which through running to Hongg resumed.<ref name=tmbisz>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/istb-D.htm | title = Die Industriequartier Strassenbahn (IStB), 1898 - 1902 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-10 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901042359/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/istb-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{ill|Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich\u2013H\u00f6ngg|de}}\n|StZH\n|1898\n|1923\n|StStZ\n|Constructed a tram route from [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]], with connection to the IStB line to Bahnhofquai, via [[Wipkingen]] to [[Hongg]]. The line was acquired by the StStZ in three phases; firstly in 1907 when the bridge over the [[Limmat river]] to Wipkingen was replaced, then in 1913 when the line as far as Grenzstein Honng was acquired, and finally in 1923 when the rest of the line as far as the terminus at the Wartau depot was acquired.<ref name=tmbstzh>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zh-D.htm | title = Die Strassenbahn Z\u00fcrich - H\u00f6ngg (Z-H), 1898 - 1924 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-11 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901042448/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/zh-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[Dolderbahn]]'''\n|Db\n|1895\n|\n|\n|From 1899, the Dolderbahn company operated an electric tram between the upper station of the Dolderbahn (then a funicular) and the [[Dolder Grand Hotel]]. This line never had any track connection with any other tram line, and was replaced by a bus in 1930. In 1973 the Dolderbahn was converted to a rack railway and extended to the Dolder Grand, thus replacing the bus.\n|-\n|[[Limmattal Strassenbahn]]\n|LSB\n|1900\n|1931\n|StStZ\n|Constructed an interurban line from the former Z\u00fcrich city boundary at Letzigraben, via [[Altstetten (Z\u00fcrich)|Altstetten]] (Farbhof) and [[Schlieren, Switzerland|Schlieren]] to [[Dietikon]], together with a branch from Schlieren to [[Weiningen]]. A connection with the StStZ was made at Letzigraben. The line between Schlieren and Dietikon closed in 1928, whilst that Schlieren and Weiningen closed in 1931, at the same time as the rest of the line from Letzigraben to Schlieren were acquired by the StStZ.<ref name=tmblsb>{{cite web | url =http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/lsb-D.htm | title = Die Limmattal - Strassenbahn (LSB), 1900 - 1931 | language = German | publisher = [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] | date = 2003-10-10 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110901042018/http://www.tram-museum-archiv.ch/Seiten_Zeitreise/in_Zuerich/lsb-D.htm | archivedate = 2011-09-01 | url-status = dead | accessdate = 2015-07-23}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Bremgarten-Dietikon-Bahn]]''\n|BD\n|1902\n|2000\n|BDWM\n|Originally constructed as a rural tramway between [[Bremgarten, Switzerland|Bremgarten]] and [[Dietikon]] to the west of Z\u00fcrich. Althyough well outside the city of Z\u00fcrich, it was at one time indirectly connected to the city's tramways by the LSB, which also served Dietikon. The section between Bremgarten and [[Wohlen]] was originally a [[standard gauge]] steam operated railway, which was [[Gauge conversion|converted]] to [[Dual gauge|mixed gauge]] and taken over by BD in 1912.\n|-\n|{{ill|Albisg\u00fctlibahn|de}}\n|AGB\n|1907\n|1925\n|StStZ\n|The last privately owned tramway to be built within the city was built to connect the city tramway at Giessh\u00fcbelstrasse to the site of the federal shooting festival, held at {{ill|Albisg\u00fcetli|de}} in July 1907. Lack of traffic to this, then very rural, location after the festival finished caused the line financial troubles, and in 1913 the line sold three of its five trams to the StStZ. By 1915 the line was operating only on Sundays, and in 1925 the StStZ took over.<ref name=bdagb>{{cite web | url = http://www.bahndaten.ch/content/bahnen-detail/2003/albisgueetli-bahn | title = Albisg\u00fcetli-Bahn | work = Bahndaten | publisher = ViaStoria - University of Bern | accessdate = 16 April 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Wetzikon-Meilen-Bahn]]''\n|WMB\n|1909\n|1950\n|(closed)\n|A rural tramway linking [[Kempten, Switzerland|Kempten]], [[Wetzikon]] and {{ill|Bahnhof Langholz|de|lt=Langholz}} to the east of Z\u00fcrich with [[Meilen]] on the shores of [[Lake Z\u00fcrich]]. Well outside the city of Z\u00fcrich, it was at one time indirectly connected to the city's tramways by the UOeb, with which it connected at Langholz, and hence the FB.<ref name=ebwmb>{{cite web | url = http://www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch/58895/59042.html | title = Wetzikon-Meilen Bahn | publisher = www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch | accessdate = 2013-10-09 | archivedate = 2013-10-17 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131017231434/http://www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch/58895/59042.html | url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Uster-Oetwil-Bahn]]''\n|UOeB\n|1909\n|1949\n|(closed)\n|A rural tramway linking [[Uster]], [[Esslingen, Switzerland|Esslingen]], [[Oetwil am See]] and {{ill|Bahnhof Langholz|de|lt=Langholz}} to the east of Z\u00fcrich. Well outside the city of Z\u00fcrich, it was at one time indirectly connected to the city's tramways by the FB, with which it connected at Esslingen.<ref name=ebuoeb>{{cite web | url = http://www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch/58895/1825855.html | title = Uster-Oetwil Bahn | publisher = www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch | accessdate = 2013-10-11 | archivedate = 2013-10-14 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131014234112/http://www.eingestellte-bahnen.ch/58895/1825855.html | url-status = live}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''''[[Forchbahn]]'''''\n|FB\n|1912\n|\n|\n|A line linking line Z\u00fcrich with the towns of [[Esslingen, Switzerland|Esslingen]] and [[Forch]]. The line opened in 1912 as a rural tramway connecting at Rehalp with the city trams, with inter-running as far as the city centre. The line has since been rebuilt with more railway characteristics, and quite substantial trains, but these continue to operate across the city tram network between [[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Stadelhofen]] in the city centre and Rehalp.\n|-\n|'''[[Verkehrsbetriebe Z\u00fcrich]]'''\n|VBZ\n|1950\n|\n|\n|Owned by city of Z\u00fcrich.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n|-\n|'''''[[BDWM Transport AG]]'''''\n|BDWM\n|2000\n|\n|\n|Created by amalgamation of the BD with the bus operator WM. Still operates a light rail service between Dietikon and Wohlen, but is no longer connected to the Z\u00fcrich tram system.\n|-\n|}\n\n===Heyday of the StStZ===\n[[File:Zurich Tram Museum 2011 526a.jpg|thumb|A Swiss Standard Tram, at the city's tramway museum]]\nBy the mid-1930s, the StStZ had acquired all the companies that had operated tramways within the city boundaries, with the single exception of the [[Dolderbahn]], which had closed its short tramway in 1930. The standard gauge horse tram lines had all been converted to metre gauge and electrified. The StStZ had also built many tram extensions, resulting in a dense network of tramlines serving most city neighbourhoods.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nHowever, in 1927, the StStZ had introduced its first [[motor bus]] route, and this was to be followed in 1939 by the first of the [[Trolleybuses in Z\u00fcrich|city's trolleybus routes]]. Initially these modes complemented the trams, but at various times they have threatened to replace parts of the tram system, and sometimes succeeded in doing so.<ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nIn 1940, the StStZ started a modernisation of its trams, introducing the first prototypes of the {{ill|Swiss Standard Tram|de|Schweizer Standardwagen|fr|Tramway standard suisse}}. Despite Switzerland's neutrality, the economic effects of the [[second world war]] slowed down the program, but by 1953 the VBZ, as the StStZ had become in 1950, had taken delivery of 177 such trams.<ref name=zacait/><ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\n===Lines closed===\n[[File:Wetzikon Meilen Bahn Gr\u00fcningen.JPG|thumb|left|The WMB in Gr\u00fcningen, prior to 1950]]\nWhile the tram network within the city of Z\u00fcrich has seen relatively few line closures, the same cannot be said for the lines beyond the city. The StStZ routinely closed any out-of-city lines belonging to the companies it took over.<ref name=zacait/> In other cases, private sector operated lines succumbed without StStZ involvement. Out of town closures included:\n\n* The Schlieren to Dietikon and Schlieren to Weinigen lines of the LSB company, closed in 1928 and 1931 respectively.<ref name=tmblsb/> \n* The Oerlikon to Schwamendingen and Seebach to Glattbrugg lines of the ZOS company, closed in 1931.<ref name=tmbzos/> \n* The Uster to Langholz line of the UOeB company, closed in 1949.<ref name=ebuoeb/>\n* The Wetzikon to Meilen line of the WMB company, closed in 1950.<ref name=ebwmb/>\n\nIn the city, the initial threat to the tram came from its perceived inflexibility and susceptibility to the growing traffic congestion in the city streets. One proposed solution was the conversion of the less busy lines to trolleybus routes, and the first step in this direction was the conversion of tram route 1, from Burgwies to Hardplatz (1954-1956). This was followed by the Farbhof to Schlieren section of route 2 (1956-8) which became a westward extension of the same trolleybus route. In practice, the trolleybus service struggled to cope with peak loadings and punctuality did not improve. No further conversions of tram routes to trollrybuses have taken place.<ref name=zacait/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Underground proposals===\n[[File:No. 7 Tram, Parade Platz.jpg|thumb|right|A pair of ''Mirage'' trams at Paradeplatz, operating on the surface where they were originally intended to be underground]]\nIn the 1950s, as well as proposing the conversion of less busy lines to trolleybus, plans were also made to place the busier lines in tunnel, in a form called the ''Tiefbahn''. The recently delivered Swiss Standard trams were not seen as suitable for this, because they had doors on their tapered car ends that would not have aligned with the proposed underground station platforms. In order to overcome this limitation, several new designs of tram were introduced. The first design, known as the P16 or ''Karpfen'', could not run on some existing routes, and only one batch of 15 motor tram and trailer pairs was built. A later design, which used articulation to avoid the problems of the P16, was eventually more successful and 126 vehicles were delivered by 1969. This car became popularly known as the ''Mirage''.<ref name=zacait/>\n\nDespite the planning and new rolling stock, a [[referendum]] in 1962 rejected the ''Tiefbahn''. However the proponents of going underground instead proposed a full scale [[metro (rapid transit)|metro]], the [[Z\u00fcrich U-Bahn]] system. This would have been standard gauge and electrified using a third rail, and hence incompatible with the tram system. The lines would have extended further into the suburbs and provided faster transit times than the tramways, which would have been curtailed so as not to compete with the U-Bahn. However this would have been at the expense of a coarser grained network, with much longer distances between U-Bahn stations than between the tram stops they replaced.<ref name=zacait/><ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nIn 1973, the U-Bahn proposal too was rejected in a referendum, but not before several stretches of U-Bahn tunnel had been built. One section of the putative U-Bahn has since been adapted, as described below, for use by trams, whilst another now forms the terminus of the [[Uetliberg railway line|Uetliberg]] and [[Sihltal railway line|Sihltal]] railway lines under the [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Hauptbahnhof]].<ref name=zacait/><ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\n===Extensions and a new model===\n[[File:Zurich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2075 Waldgarten.jpg|thumb|left|Tram 2000 tram at Waldgarten stop in the tunnel section built for the U-Bahn]]\nIn 1976, the first tram extension since 1954 took place, with the extension of route 4 from Hardturm to [[Werdh\u00f6lzli]]. Unlike the older lines, this extension was built mostly on reserved track, a precedent to be followed by most subsequent extensions.<ref name=zacait/>\n\nThe Werdh\u00f6lzli extension was followed in 1986 by the extension of routes 7 and 9 into new residential areas to the north-east of Z\u00fcrich. This used one of the stretches of tunnel that had been built for the rejected U-Bahn, between Milchbuck and Schwamendingen. The tram route was extended through the tunnel before splitting at Schwamendingen to serve the area beyond, using new surface track. Because the tunnels and stations had been built with [[island platform]]s, whilst Z\u00fcrich trams only have doors on their [[Right- and left-hand traffic#Terminology|nearside]], the section through the tunnel uses left-hand running.<ref name=zacait/>\n\nFrom 1976 onwards, the VBZ tram fleet was further updated, with the introduction of Z\u00fcrich's variant of the [[Tram 2000|Tram 2000 design]] used by several Swiss tram systems. Several sub-classes of the Tram 2000 were purchased, including articulated and non-articulated variants, and some without drivers cabs that could only operate in multiple with other cars. Eventually 171 of these vehicles were delivered, with the last of the class delivered in 1992.<ref name=zacait/><ref name=vbzfafch/>\n\nFrom the 1980s onwards, the system was increasingly acclaimed for its success in maintaining a high share of the [[modal split]], and the [[Z\u00fcrich model]] of transport provision was named after it. Beyond the tramway, the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn|Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn rail network]] was introduced to serve the region beyond the city boundaries, taking on some of the role that was originally planned for the U-Bahn. In 1990, the city's urban and regional transport were integrated by the introduction of the [[Z\u00fcrcher Verkehrsverbund|ZVV]] and its zone-based common fare structure.<ref name=zacait/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n=== Low floors and the Glattalbahn ===\n[[File:Zurich Be 5-6 Cobra 3002 Letzistrasse.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Cobra (tram)|Bombardier Cobra]] low-floor tram on typical VBZ street track]]\nIn 2001, the VBZ took delivery of the first prototypes of a brand-new low-floor design of tram, known as the [[Cobra (tram)|Cobra]].<ref name=vbzfafch/> Despite many teething problems with the prototypes, which were eventually extensively rebuilt, there are now 88 of these trams in service, with the last delivered in 2010. In order to increase the number of low-floor trams in service, 23 trams from the otherwise high-floor Tram 2000 fleet were rebuilt between 2001 and 2005 with the addition of a low-floor centre section.\n\n[[File:Glatttalbahn - \u00d6rlikerhaus 2011-08-22 19-33-44.JPG|thumb|left|The Glattalbahn]]\nFrom the 1950s onwards, the [[Glattal]] region to the north of Z\u00fcrich experienced a rapid boom as population and industry spilled over from nearby Z\u00fcrich, partly driven by the presence of [[Z\u00fcrich Airport]]. Whilst the airport is served by the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn|city's S-Bahn rail network]], the economic growth and resulting congestion led to a need for a finer-grained form of public transport. The responsible transport authority (the [[Verkehrsbetriebe Glattal]] or VBG) responded by constructing a new light rail system, the [[Stadtbahn Glattal|Glattalbahn]]. This was built to be compatible with Z\u00fcrich's tram network, with which it connects at several points on the city boundary. The system opened in stages between 2006 and 2010. The VBG contracted the VBZ to operate the network, and several tram routes now operate across both networks.<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/><ref name=tuthhqlr>{{cite news | first = C.J. | last = Wansbeek | title = Glattal: High quality light rail to Z\u00fcrich airport | work = [[Tramways & Urban Transit]] | publisher = Ian Allan Ltd / Light Rail Transit Association | pages = 374\u2013376 | date = October 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe arrival of new trams between 2001 and 2010 led to the departure of older vehicles. The ''Karpfen'' last ran in regular service in 2006, and the ''Mirage'' in 2010. Many members of both classes have been transferred to [[Vinnytsia]] in [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite web |  first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2006&item=131106b | title = Karpfen farewell tour | date = November 2006 | accessdate = 2012-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |  first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2010&item=300610 | title = Last Mirage day | date = June 2010 | accessdate = 2012-05-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |  first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2010&item=250810 | title = Karpfen and Mirage in Vinnitsa | date = August 2010 | accessdate = 2012-05-26}}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n=== More extensions ===\n\"Tram Z\u00fcrich West\", an extension from Escher-Wyss-Platz to Bahnhof Altstetten Nord, in the city of Z\u00fcrich, opened in December 2011. The resulting reorganisation of routes included a new route 17 from Hauptbahnhof to Werdh\u00f6lzli via Escher-Wyss-Platz, and the diversion of route 4, which had previously served Werdh\u00f6lzli, to Altstetten.<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2011&item=101211 | title = Opening of Tram Z\u00fcrich West | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = December 2011 | accessdate = 2012-05-27}}</ref> In 2017, route 8 was extended from Hardplatz to Hardturm, via new track over Hardbr\u00fccke, the first tram line to cross the main railway line through Z\u00fcrich.<ref name=amv2030>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2013&item=260713b | title = Vision 2030, looking at VBZ's plans for the future | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = July 2013 | accessdate = 2014-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2017&item=071217 | title = Tram Hardbr\u00fccke opening this weekend, and network changes | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = December 2017 | accessdate = 2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, city route 2 was extended from Farbhof to Geissweid, a distance of {{convert|2\u00b79|km}} with seven stops. The new route operates over the first section of the [[Limmatalbahn]] to open, and replaces [[Trolleybuses in Z\u00fcrich|trolleybus route 31]] over that section. The new tram line operates over the first section of the [[Limmattalbahn]] to open. Once that the Limmatalbahn is completed, it will also carry a separate regional service from Bahnhof Altstetten to [[Killwangen-Spreitenbach]], although that service will not form part of the city tram network and will be operated by the [[BDWM]].<ref name=rgifpl>{{cite news |url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/projects-and-planning/first-phase-of-limmattalbahn-opens-in-zurich/54477.article| title=First phase of Limmattalbahn opens in Z\u00fcrich |work=Railway Gazette International |date=2019-09-03 |accessdate=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n===History preserved===\nThe [[Z\u00fcrich Tram Museum]], located at the former tram depot at Burgwies (on tram route 11), preserves many examples of Z\u00fcrich's former tramcar fleet, along with other related exhibits.\n\n==Operation==\n\n===Route network===\n[[File:Tramnetz-zuerich2.png|thumb|Tram network in Z\u00fcrich (from ? until the change of timetable in the year 2017 when the Hardbr\u00fccke tram was opened)]]\n[[File:Z\u00fcrich Paradeplatz.jpg|thumb|Paradeplatz is one of the key nodes of the route network, served by 7 routes]]\nThe following tram routes make up the urban and Glattalbahn route network:<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/><ref name=zurmap>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/dam/stzh/vbz/Deutsch/Ueber%20das%20Departement/Publikationen%20und%20Broschueren/Fahrplan/liniennetzplaene/Stadt%20Zuerich.pdf | title = Stadt Z\u00fcrich - Z\u00fcrich City - Transport Map | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2016-10-11}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; font-size:95%; margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;\"\n!Route\n!Description (''Portion of route in italics is on Glattalbahn track'')\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#D8232A | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''2'''</big></span>\n| [[Z\u00fcrich Tiefenbrunnen railway station|Bhf. Tiefenbrunnen]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Stauffacher]] - Albisriederplatz - Farbhof - [[Schlieren]] Geissweid\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#009F4A | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''3'''</big></span>\n| Klusplatz - R\u00f6merhof - [[Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich|Kunsthaus]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Stauffacher]] - Albisriederplatz - [[Albisrieden]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#3E4085 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''4'''</big></span>\n| [[Z\u00fcrich Tiefenbrunnen railway station|Bhf. Tiefenbrunnen]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]] - [[Altstetten railway station|Bhf. Altstetten]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#855B37 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''5'''</big></span>\n| (Laubegg -) [[Z\u00fcrich Enge railway station|Bhf. Enge]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich|Kunsthaus]] - Kirche Fluntern (- [[Zoo Z\u00fcrich|Zoo]])\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#DA9F4F | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''6'''</big></span>\n| [[Werdh\u00f6lzli]] - [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[ETH Z\u00fcrich|ETH]]/[[University Hospital of Z\u00fcrich|Universit\u00e4tsspital]] - [[Kirche Fluntern]] - [[Zoo Z\u00fcrich|Zoo]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#191919 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''7'''</big></span>\n| [[Stettbach railway station|Bhf. Stettbach]] - [[Schwamendingerplatz]] - Milchbuck - Schaffhauserplatz - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Enge railway station|Bhf. Enge]] - [[Wollishofen]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#86CD16 | <big>'''8'''</big>\n| [[Hardturm]] - [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hardbr\u00fccke railway station|Bhf. Hardbr\u00fccke]] - Hardplatz - [[Stauffacher]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Selnau railway station|Bhf. Selnau]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Bhf.Stadelhofen]] - Kreuzplatz - R\u00f6merhof - Klusplatz) \n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#3E4085 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''9'''</big></span>\n| [[Hirzenbach]] - Schwamendingerplatz - Milchbuck - [[Seilbahn Rigiblick]] - [[ETH Z\u00fcrich|ETH]]/[[University Hospital of Z\u00fcrich|Universit\u00e4tsspital]] - [[Kunsthaus Z\u00fcrich|Kunsthaus]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Stauffacher]] - Heuried (- Triemli)\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#DA3987 | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''10'''</big></span>\n| (Albisg\u00fctli - Laubegg - [[Z\u00fcrich Enge railway station|Bhf. Enge]] - [[Paradeplatz]] -) [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - [[ETH Z\u00fcrich|ETH]]/[[University Hospital of Z\u00fcrich|Universit\u00e4tsspital]] - Seilbahn Rigiblick - Milchbuck - Sternen Oerlikon - [[Z\u00fcrich Oerlikon railway station|Bhf. Oerlikon Ost]] - ''[[Glattpark]]'' - ''[[Glattbrugg railway station|Bhf. Glattbrugg]]'' - ''[[Z\u00fcrich Flughafen, Bahnhof]]''\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#009F4A | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''11'''</big></span>\n| [[Z\u00fcrich Rehalp railway station|Rehalp]] - Kreuzplatz - [[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Bhf. Stadelhofen]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[B\u00fcrkliplatz]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]]  - Schaffhauserplatz - Bucheggplatz - [[Z\u00fcrich Oerlikon railway station|Bhf. Oerlikon]] - Sternen Oerlikon - Messe/[[Hallenstadion]] - ''[[Glattpark]]'' - ''Auzelg'' \n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#7ACAD4 | <big>'''12'''</big>\n| ''[[Z\u00fcrich Flughafen, Bahnhof]]'' - ''[[Glattbrugg railway station|Bhf.Glattbrugg]]'' - ''[[Glattpark]]'' - ''Auzelg'' - ''[[Wallisellen railway station|Bhf. Wallisellen]]'' - ''[[Glattzentrum]]'' - [[Stettbach railway station|Bhf. Stettbach]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#FBD01F | <big>'''13'''</big>\n| Albisg\u00fctli - Laubegg - [[Z\u00fcrich Enge railway station|Bhf. Enge]] - [[Paradeplatz]] - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Escher-Wyss-Platz]] - Meierhofplatz - Frankental\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#00A4DB | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''14'''</big></span>\n| [[Seebach (Z\u00fcrich)|Seebach]] - Sternen Oerlikon - Milchbuck - Schaffhauserplatz - [[Z\u00fcrich Hauptbahnhof|Z\u00fcrich HB]] - [[Stauffacher]] - Heuried - [[Stadtspital Triemli|Triemli]]\n|- align=center\n| bgcolor=#D8232A | <span style=\"color:white\"><big>'''15'''</big></span>\n|[[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Bhf. Stadelhofen]] - [[Bellevueplatz|Bellevue]] - [[Central, Z\u00fcrich|Central]] - Schaffhauserplatz - Bucheggplatz\n|-\n|}\n[[File:Forchbahn Be 4-6 Kreuzplatz.jpg|thumb|left|A Forchbahn train on Z\u00fcrich tram tracks]]\n<br/>\nAll journeys on routes 6, 10 and 12 are operated by low-floor trams, whilst at least every other journey on lines 2, 3, 4, 7, 9, 11, 13 and 14 are provided by such vehicles. Most, but not all, tram stops are configured to allow passengers in [[wheelchair]]s to board low-floor trams.<ref name=gpw/>\n\nOf the three routes that operate in part over Glattalbahn tracks, routes 10 and 12 are operated by the VBZ on behalf of the [[Verkehrsbetriebe Glattal]] (VBG), normally using tramcars in the VBG's own predominantly white colour scheme, whilst route 11 is operated by the VBZ on its own behalf, normally using vehicles in its own livery.<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/><ref name=tuthhqlr/>\n\nThe independent [[Forchbahn]] (FB) railway uses VBZ trackwork to reach their city centre terminus, at [[Z\u00fcrich Stadelhofen railway station|Bahnhof Stadelhofen]], from the eastern edge of the city, at Rehalp. The FB trains operate largely in the street for this section of their route, sharing track with VBZ tram routes, but are categorised as route [[S18 (ZVV)|S18]] of the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn|city's S-Bahn railway network]] rather than as part of the tram network. Beyond Rehalp the trains use the FB's own segregated tracks to reach their outer terminus at [[Esslingen, Switzerland|Esslingen]].<ref name=gpw/><ref name=saw/>\n\nOn the last weekend of each month, the [[Z\u00fcrich Tram Museum]] operates tram route 21 from the city centre to the museum at Burgwies (up to Rehalp at Saturdays), using their own heritage rolling stock.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tram-museum.ch/content.php?id=5&lang=en | title = The Museum Line 21 | publisher = Z\u00fcrich Tram Museum | accessdate=2012-05-09}}</ref>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Infrastructure===\n[[File:Z\u00fcrich - Stadelhoferplatz IMG 4441.JPG|thumb|Raised platforms for use with low-floor trams, being used by a high-floor tram]]\nZ\u00fcrich's tram network is built to [[metre gauge]] ({{RailGauge|1000mm|first=imp|disp=1}} gauge). There are {{convert|171.9|km|mi}} of track, equating to a network length of {{convert|72.9|km|mi}} and a total route length of {{convert|118.7|km|mi}}. The tracks are electrified using [[overhead line]] at 600 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]], utilising a supply system shared with the [[Trolleybuses in Z\u00fcrich|city's trolleybus network]].<ref name=\"figures\">{{cite web |url=https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/portraet/zahlen_fakten/linien.html |title=Startseite VBZ - Die VBZ - Portr\u00e4t - Zahlen & Fakten - Linien |publisher=Stadt Z\u00fcrich [City of Z\u00fcrich] |language=German |trans-title=Home VBZ - VBZ - Portrait - Facts & Figures - Lines |date= |accessdate=2014-05-25}}</ref><ref name=saw/>\n\nThe VBZ infrastructure within Z\u00fcrich is largely street based, with varying degrees of segregation from other street traffic and significant sections where trams run in unrestricted traffic lanes. In the city centre the tram tracks run through largely pedestrianised streets, and in one place in the suburbs the trams use a tunnel originally constructed for the never completed [[Z\u00fcrich U-Bahn]] system. By contrast, on VBG infrastructure in the Stadtbahn Glattal, VBZ trams operate on long stretches of dedicated track.<ref name=gpw>{{cite web | title = Gleisplan - Stra\u00dfenbahn Z\u00fcrich mit Glattal |  url = http://www.gleisplanweb.eu/Maps/Zuerich.pdf | language = German | trans-title = Trackplan - Z\u00fcrich with Glattal | date = 2014-01-23 | accessdate = 2014-06-21}}</ref><ref name=saw/>\n\nMany of Z\u00fcrich's tram stops have been equipped with boarding platforms raised to match the floor height of the low floor trams, although there are still examples of stops where passengers must board from street level. Z\u00fcrich's trams are single-ended, with doors on only one side, although Forchbahn trains are double-ended and double-sided. In consequence all terminal locations are equipped with [[turning loop]]s, and all tram stops are to the [[Right- and left-hand traffic#Terminology|nearside]] of the tram.<ref name=gpw/>\n\n===Depots and workshops===\n[[File:Tramdepot Zuerich 1911 Friedrich Fissler.jpg|thumb|left|The tram depot at Hard was built in 1911]]\nZ\u00fcrich's tram fleet is kept in the five operational depots of Hard, Irchel, Kalkbreite, Oerlikon and  Wollishofen, together with a permanent way yard at Hardturm. Whilst these depots have the capability to undertake minor maintenance, heavier maintenance is the responsibility of the VBZ's central workshop at Altstetten. This is connected to the tram network, and also has a rail connection to the [[Swiss Federal Railway]] system, allowing the delivery of infrastructure items and vehicles by rail.<ref name=gpw/><ref name=zws>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/produkte_dienstleistungen/werkstatt.html | title = Werkstatt | language = German | trans-title = Workshop | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-02-17}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the above depots and workshops, two other former tram depots, at Burgweis and Wartau, are also still connected to the tram network. Burgweis depot now houses the [[Tram-Museum Z\u00fcrich]] main collection, whilst Wartau is used as a workshop by that organisation. The rail connections permit the occasional operation of preserved trams on the VBZ network.<ref name=gpw/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Tram fleet===\nAs of 2012, the VBZ owns 313 tram vehicles, which between them cover over 16 million vehicle-kilometres per year. All regular public services are covered by 289 vehicles of two basic classes, with the remainder of the fleet made up of a number of assorted works vehicles, including some used for the cargo tram service, and heritage vehicles. The heritage fleet sees occasional use on special services.<ref name=vbzfafveh>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/vehicles.html | title = VBZ - Portrait - Facts & figures - Vehicles | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-04 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121007014744/http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/vehicles.html | archivedate = 2012-10-07 }}</ref><ref name=vbzfafser>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/vbz/portrait/facts_figures/service.html | title = VBZ - Portrait - Facts & figures - Service | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-04}}</ref>\n\nThe tram fleet comprises the following vehicles:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; font-size:95%; margin-right:10px; margin-bottom:5px;\"\n!Image\n!Numbers\n!Type\n![[Swiss locomotive and railcar classification|Notation]]\n!Capacity<br>Sit/Stand\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[File:Zurich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2034 Bellevue.jpg|200px|Z\u00fcrich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2034 Bellevue]]\n|2001-2098\n|Tram&nbsp;2000\n|Be 4/6\n|50/54\n|The two section articulated variant of the [[Tram 2000|Tram 2000 design]] for Z\u00fcrich, of which 98 vehicles were delivered in two stages from 1976 to 1978, and from 1985 to 1987. Each vehicle is {{convert|21.4|m}} in length and {{convert|2.2|m}} in width. In most cases these cars operate in multiple.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzveht20>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/fahrzeuge/unsere_fahrzeuge/trams/tram2000.html | title = VBZ - Fahrzeuge - Unsere Fahrzeuge - Trams - Tram 2000 | language = German | trans-title = VBZ - Vehicles - Our vehicles - Trams - Tram 2000 | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-29}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[File:Zurich Be 4-8 Saenfte 2110 Milchbuck.jpg|200px|A Tram 2000 tram with low-floor centre section]]\n|2099-2121\n|Tram 2000\n|Be 4/8\n|68/75\n|Originally two section units similar to 2001-2098, these cars were built from 1992 to 1993. Between 1999 and 2005 they were rebuilt with a third central low-floor section. Each vehicle is {{convert|28|m}} in length and {{convert|2.2|m}} in width. They are also known as ''S\u00e4nfte''.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzveht20/><ref name=vbzveht2s>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/fahrzeuge/unsere_fahrzeuge/trams/tram2000_saenfte.html | title = VBZ - Fahrzeuge - Unsere Fahrzeuge - Trams - Tram 2000 S\u00e4nfte | language = German | trans-title = VBZ - Vehicles - Our vehicles - Trams - Tram 2000 S\u00e4nfte | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-29}}</ref> \n|-\n|[[File:Zurich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2303 Seebach.jpg|200px|Z\u00fcrich Be 4-6 Tram 2000 2303 Seebach]]\n|2301-2315\n|Tram 2000\n|Be 4/6\n|50/57\n|Two section articulated unit similar to 2001-2098 but without a drivers cab. These cars were built in 1978, and must run as the second unit in multiple with another Tram 2000 unit. Each vehicle is {{convert|21.4|m}} in length and {{convert|2.2|m}} in width.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzveht20/>\n|-\n|[[File:Zurich Be 2-4 Pony 2415 Klusplatz.jpg|200px|A single-section Tram 2000 ''Pony'' car]]\n|2401-2435\n|Tram 2000\n|Be 2/4\n|35/41\n|Single section non-articulated unit without a drivers cab. These cars were built in two stages from 1985 to 1987, and 1992 to 1993. Like 2301-2315, they must run as the second unit in multiple with another Tram 2000 unit. Each vehicle is {{convert|15.4|m}} in length and {{convert|2.2|m}} in width. They are also known as ''Pony''.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzveht20/>\n|-\n|[[File:Zurichcobratram.jpg|200px|A [[Cobra (tram)|Bombardier Cobra]] low-floor tram on typical VBZ street track]]\n|3001-3088\n|Cobra\n|Be 5/6\n|90/113\n|The more recent of the two classes of trams in regular service are the 88 modern low-floor [[Cobra (tram)|Bombardier Cobra]] trams delivered between 2001 and 2010. 18 of them (3062-3079) were in VBG livery. These are all five section articulated vehicles running on six pairs of wheels, of which five are powered. Each vehicle is {{convert|36|m}} in length and {{convert|2.4|m}} in width. Because of their length, Cobras only run as single units in normal service.<ref name=vbzfafveh/><ref name=vbzvehcob>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/fahrzeuge/unsere_fahrzeuge/trams/cobra.html | title = VBZ - Fahrzeuge - Unsere Fahrzeuge - Trams - Cobra | language = German | trans-title = VBZ - Vehicles - Our vehicles - Trams - Cobra   | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-29}}</ref> \n|-\n|}\n\n===Fares and tickets===\n[[File:Ticket machine at Zurich Airport tram stop 03.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Ticket machine]]\nLike the rest of the VBZ network, Z\u00fcrich's tram network operates on a [[proof-of-payment]] system. All tram stops are equipped with ticket machines, and passengers are required to purchase a ticket before boarding the vehicle. Passengers may board through any door and are not required to show tickets on boarding. Instead, tickets are randomly checked by roving teams of fare inspectors, and fines are imposed on passengers found without one.<ref name=vbzatm>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/tickets/fare_zone_system.html | title = VBZ - Automatic ticket machine | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-21}}</ref>\n\nTram services are operated within the fare and ticketing system provided by the cantonal public transport authority, the [[Z\u00fcrcher Verkehrsverbund]] (ZVV). This system covers the whole of the [[canton of Z\u00fcrich]] and thus covers travel on other modes and services, provided by many other operators, and includes the [[Z\u00fcrich S-Bahn]] suburban rail network. Free transfer is permitted between different vehicles, routes, modes and operators, provided a ticket valid for the whole journey is held.<ref name=vbzfzs>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/en/index/tickets/fare_zone_system.html | title = VBZ - Fare zone system | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-21}}</ref>\n\nThe ZVV system is zone-based, with fares for individual journeys set by the zones the journey passes through. The Z\u00fcrich tram network extends over just two of these zones, with zone 110 covering the city routes, and zone 121 covering the Stadtbahn Glattal routes. Both single journey and day tickets are available, as are a number of passes with longer validities.<ref name=vbzfzs/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.zvv.ch/export/sites/default/common-images/content-image-gallery/linien-zonen-pdfs/Tarifzonen_Kanton_Zuerich_2011.pdf | title = Tarifzonen - Fare zones | publisher = ZVV | accessdate = 2012-06-18}}</ref>\n\n===Cargo tram===\n[[File:Cargo Tram outside Zurich Hauptbahnhof.JPG|thumb|left|The cargo tram]]\nBesides its passenger transport activities, VBZ, jointly with the city refuse and recycling department ERZ, operates the cargo tram to collect bulky waste. The cargo tram serves 10 different collection points around Z\u00fcrich, calling at each on different days of the month. The collected refuse is taken to a specially constructed siding at the ERZ yard adjacent to the Werdh\u00f6lzli tram terminus.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/produkte_dienstleistungen/cargo_tram_und_etram.html | title = Cargo- und E-Tram | language = German | trans-title = Cargo- and E-Tram | publisher = City of Z\u00fcrich | accessdate = 2012-05-09 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120829085657/http://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/content/vbz/de/index/produkte_dienstleistungen/cargo_tram_und_etram.html | archivedate = 2012-08-29 }}</ref><ref name=amcargo>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/cargotram.html | title = Cargotram -  Z\u00fcrich's domestic refuse takes to the rails | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | date = August 2003 | accessdate = 2013-07-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2014&item=140114 | title = Cargotram serves additional destination | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | date = 2014-01-14 | accessdate = 2014-02-06}}</ref>\n\nThe service was introduced in 2003, as an attempt to reduce the amount of bulky waste items dumped illegally every year. As Z\u00fcrich has an extensive tram network serving most neighbourhoods, and many suitable sidings not used by regular services, it was decided to use the tram network. In its first year of operation it was responsible for the collection of {{convert|380|tonnes}} of waste.<ref name=amcargo/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2004&item=160404 | title = Cargo tram is a success! | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue | date = April 2004 | accessdate = 2013-07-14}}</ref>\n\nThe collected waste is carried in two standard refuse containers, which are mounted on four-wheeled flat wagons. These are hauled by car 1922, a former Swiss Standard Tram, originally delivered to Z\u00fcrich in 1940, and converted into a works car in 1980.<ref name=amcargo/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==Future developments==\n\n===New vehicles===\n[[File:Tango als Tram in Z\u00fcrich beim Paradeplatz.jpg|thumb|A Stadler Tango on trial in Paradeplatz]]\nThe VBZ has long intended to order a new generation of tram cars, to replace the high-floor Tram 2000 trams currently in service. By 2010, it had conducted trials of three existing tram types on its network. These were the [[Stadler Tango]], the [[Siemens Combino]] and the [[Bombardier Flexity]]. It then requested tenders for the supply of 30 new trams, together with an option for the supply of a further 70 vehicles. The first trams were to be delivered in December 2016, and were to be 100% low floor with capacity for at least 225 passengers. In response, by April 2013 five suppliers had submitted bids. As of February 2015, no decision had been made as to which supplier to select, with reports of conflict between city and canton authorities.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?item=210610a | title = Tango, Combino or Flexity? | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = June 2010 | accessdate = 2013-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?item=201112 | title = New tram order: The ball is rolling | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = November 2012 | accessdate = 2013-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2013&item=080413 | title = Five suppliers vie for tram contract | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = April 2013 | accessdate = 2013-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2015&item=260215 | title = More gloom over tram order | first = Andrew | last = Moglestue |  date = February 2015 | accessdate = 2015-03-02}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, it was announced that VBZ had awarded a contract worth 358 million [[Swiss Franc]]s to [[Bombardier Transportation]] for the supply of 70<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/tram-zuerich-flexity-kommt-erst-im-sommer-2020-zum-einsatz-ld.1524125 | title = Das erste Flexity-Tram kurvt durch Z\u00fcrich \u2013 aber Passagiere d\u00fcrfen noch lange nicht mitfahren | language = German |  work =  Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung | date = 25 November 2019 | accessdate = 25 November 2019}}</ref> 7-section [[Flexity 2]] trams, with an option for a further 70, to be delivered between 2018 and 2023. The new trams will be {{convert|43|m}} long and {{convert|2.4|m}} wide, and be capable of carrying 90 seated and 186 standing passengers. Both [[Stadler Rail]] and [[Siemens]] filed complaints with the [[Administrative Court of the Canton of Z\u00fcrich]], causing the finalisation of the contract to be suspended, but the court ruled in February 2017 that VBZ could conclude the contract with Bombardier. After both Stadler and Siemens decided not to appeal this decision to the [[Federal Supreme Court of Switzerland]], the contract was finally signed on 2 March 2017.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://mobile2.tagesanzeiger.ch/articles/573af28cab5c371886000001 | title = So sieht das neue Z\u00fcri-Tram aus | language = German | trans-title = Looks like the new Z\u00fcrich tram | work = Tages Anzeiger | date = 17 May 2016 | accessdate = 17 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Z\u00fcrich orders 70 Flexity 2 trams | url = http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/news/europe/single-view/view/zuerich-orders-70-flexity-2-trams.html | work = Railway Gazette | date = 18 May 2016 | publisher = DVV Media UK Ltd | accessdate = 18 May 2016 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160518151231/http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/news/europe/single-view/view/zuerich-orders-70-flexity-2-trams.html | archivedate = 18 May 2016 | url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/medien/medienmitteilungen/trambeschaffung0.html |title=Trambeschaffung: Keine aufschiebende Wirkung der Beschwerden |language=German |trans-title=Tram procurement: No suspensory effect of the complaints |publisher=City of Z\u00fcrich |date=21 February 2017 |accessdate=27 February 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227110556/https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/die_vbz/medien/medienmitteilungen/trambeschaffung0.html |archivedate=27 February 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/aktuelles/Trambeschaffung1.html |title=Vertrag unterschrieben |language=German |trans-title=Contract signed |publisher=City of Z\u00fcrich |date=2 March 2017 |accessdate=3 March 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170303112240/https://www.stadt-zuerich.ch/vbz/de/index/aktuelles/Trambeschaffung1.html |archivedate=3 March 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=tr256>{{cite news | first = Christian | last = Ammann | title = Z\u00fcrich's Bombardier order confirmed | work = Today's Railways | publisher = Platform 5 Publishing Ltd | pages = 16 | date = April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===System expansion===\nIn the Limmat Valley, between [[Altstetten railway station|Bahnhof Altstetten]] and [[Killwangen-Spreitenbach railway station|Bahnhof Killwangen-Spreitenbach]], the [[Limmattal light rail line]] is under construction and should be partially opened by 2020. A referendum, held in November 2015, approved the construction of the line, and it was announced in May 2016 that it would be operated by [[BDWM Transport|BDWM]]. The line will connect to the VBZ tram system at Farbhof, the current terminus of route 2, and that route will be extended over the light rail line as far as [[Schlieren, Switzerland|Schlieren]], as a partial replacement for [[Z\u00fcrich trolleybus route 31|trolleybus route 31]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2010&item=030310a |title=Limmattalbahn |first=Andrew |last=Moglestue |date=March 2010 |accessdate=31 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180531124735/http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich/newslog/newsitem.php?year=2010&item=030310a |archivedate=31 May 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/aktuell/zuerich-sagt-ja-zur-limmattalbahn-ld.3186 |first1=Stefan |last1=Hotz |first2=Andr\u00e9 |last2=M\u00fcller |title=Nur das Limmattal selbst stimmt gegen \u00absein\u00bb neues Tram |language=German |trans-title=Only the Limmattal itself voted against \"its\" new tram |work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung |date=22 November 2015 |accessdate=27 February 2017 |archivedate=28 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228082218/https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/aktuell/zuerich-sagt-ja-zur-limmattalbahn-ld.3186}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/aktuell/bdwm-transport-ag-aargauer-betreiben-zuercher-limmattalbahn-ld.82405 |first=Corsin |last=Zander |title=Aargauer betreiben Z\u00fcrcher Limmattalbahn |language=German |trans-title=Aargau company to operate Z\u00fcrcher Limmattalbahn |work=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung |date=13 May 2016 |accessdate=27 February 2017 |archivedate=28 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170228075100/https://www.nzz.ch/zuerich/aktuell/bdwm-transport-ag-aargauer-betreiben-zuercher-limmattalbahn-ld.82405}}</ref>\n\nThere are also plans for a number of other extensions to be built up to 2025.<ref name=amv2030/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Trains|Switzerland}}\n*[[List of railway companies in Switzerland]]\n*[[List of town tramway systems in Switzerland]]\n*[[Trolleybuses in Z\u00fcrich]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{Bernet-Trams-Schweiz}}\n*{{cite book |last=Bodmer |first=Hans |title=Das Tram in Z\u00fcrich 1928 bis 1962 |trans-title=The Tram in Z\u00fcrich 1928 to 1962 |year=2011 |publisher=Sutton Verlag GmbH |location=Erfurt |isbn=9783866809291 |language=de}}\n*{{cite book |last=Galliker |first=Hans-Rudolf |title=Tramstadt: Verkehrsplanung, \u00f6ffentlicher Nahverkehr und Stadtentwicklung am Beispiel der Stadt Z\u00fcrich |trans-title=Tram City: Transport Planning, Local Public Transport and Urban Development with the City of Z\u00fcrich as an Example |year=1997 |publisher=Chronos-Verlag |location=Z\u00fcrich |isbn=3905312026 |language=de}}\n*{{Schwandl-TAtlas-Schweiz}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tram transport in Z\u00fcrich}}\n*[http://www.vbz.ch VBZ official website]\n*[http://www.proaktiva.ch/tram/zurich Trams of Z\u00fcrich unofficial website]\n*[https://www.gleisplanweb.eu/Map-e.php?Map=Zuerich Track plan of the Z\u00fcrich tram system]\n*[http://www.tram-museum.ch Tram Museum Z\u00fcrich website]\n*{{Urban Electric Transit | id = 222 | title = Zurich | tram = yes}}\n\n{{Public transport in Z\u00fcrich}}\n{{Urban public transport in Switzerland}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trams in Zurich}}\n[[Category:Public transport in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Tram transport in Switzerland|Zurich]]\n[[Category:Transport in Z\u00fcrich]]\n[[Category:1882 establishments in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Metre gauge railways in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:600 V DC railway electrification]]\n[[Category:Town tramway systems by city|Zurich]]\n", "name_user": "Chris j 