ics Championships|2018 Glasgow]]|[[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metre backstroke|200 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold|2018 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre freestyle relay|4\u00d7100 m freestyle]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2018 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|2018 Glasgow|[[Swimming at the 2018 European Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Summer Youth Olympics]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics|2014 Nanjing]] | [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Boys' 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold | 2014 Nanjing | [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Boys' 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]]}}\n{{MedalGold | 2014 Nanjing | [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Boys' 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | 2014 Nanjing | [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Boys' 200 metre backstroke|200 m backstroke]]}}\n}}\n'''Evgeny Mikhailovich Rylov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0420\u044b\u043b\u043e\u0432}}; born 23 September 1996) is a Russian competitive [[Swimming (sport)|swimmer]] who specializes in [[backstroke]] events. He has won three gold medals at the [[2014 Summer Youth Olympics]] in [[Nanjing]], and a bronze on his major debut at the [[2015 World Aquatics Championships|2015 FINA World Championships]] in [[Kazan]].<ref name=rylov-bronze>{{cite news|title=\u0420\u044b\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u043f\u043e\u043c\u043d\u0438\u043b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043e \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044f\u0445|trans-title=Rylov reminded Russia about the medals|language=ru|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/sport/2015/08/07/a_7673489.shtml|publisher=[[Gazeta.ru]]|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> He also won a bronze at the [[Swimming at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Summer Olympics]] in Rio and a gold at [[Swimming at the 2017 World Aquatics Championships|2017 Fina World Championships]] in Budapest, both were from the 200 m backstroke event.\n\n==Career==\nRylov first established himself on the world scene at the [[2014 Summer Youth Olympics]] in [[Nanjing, China]], where he achieved a total of four medals, three golds and one silver, and broke two junior world swimming records. In the [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Boys' 100 metre backstroke|boys' 100 m backstroke]], Rylov shared the top prize with Italy's Simone Sabbioni in a matching time of 54.24 seconds.<ref>{{cite news|title=Youth Olympic Games: Liliana Szilagyi Vaults to 3rd in World in 200 Fly|url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/youth-olympic-games-day-two-finals-live-recap/|publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|date=18 August 2014|accessdate=23 September 2014}}</ref> On 20 August, he put up a sterling effort of 25.09 to crush the world junior record and pick up his second gold of the meet in the [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Boys' 50 metre backstroke|50 m backstroke]], touching out Greece's [[Apostolos Christou]] by 0.35 of a second.<ref name=rylov-wjr>{{cite news|title=Youth Olympic Games: World Junior Records Bonanza on Night Four|url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/youth-olympic-games-world-junior-records-bonanza-on-night-four/|publisher=[[Russian News Agency TASS]]|date=20 August 2014|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Russian swimmer Rylov wins gold at 2014 Youth Olympics in China|url=http://tass.ru/en/sports/745856|publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|date=20 August 2014|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> Less than an hour later, Rylov and his teammates [[Anton Chupkov]], Aleksandr Sadovnikov, and Filipp Shopin led throughout the race to capture the [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Boys' 4 \u00d7 100 metre medley relay|4\u00d7100 m medley relay]] title in a junior world-record breaking time of 3:38.02.<ref name=rylov-wjr/><ref>{{cite news|title=Nanjing provides perfect springboard for Rio|url=http://www.olympic.org/news/swimming-men-nanjing-provides-perfect-springboard-for-rio/237765|publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|date=3 October 2014|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> On the final night of the Games, Rylov added a silver to his medal tally in the [[Swimming at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Boys' 200 metre backstroke|200 m backstroke]] with a time of 1:57.08, losing the title and his chance of breaking another record to China's Li Guangyuan by 14-hundredths of a second.<ref>{{cite news|title=Youth Olympic Games: World Junior Record Bonanza on Final Night|url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/youth-olympic-games-world-junior-record-bonanza-on-final-night/|publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|date=22 August 2014|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhen his nation [[Russia]] hosted the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships|2015 FINA World Championships]] in [[Kazan]], Rylov charged his way to round out the podium with a third-place time of 1:54.60 in the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metre backstroke|200 m backstroke]].<ref name=rylov-bronze/><ref>{{cite news|title=Mitch Larkin Breaks American Streak in 200 Back at 2015 FINA World Championships|url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/mitch-larkin-breaks-american-streak-in-200-back-at-2015-fina-world-championships//|publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|date=7 August 2015|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref> Earlier in the meet, Rylov also posted a time of 53.23 to place seventh in the finals of the [[Swimming at the 2015 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 100 metre backstroke|100 m backstroke]], missing out the podium by more than half a second.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mitchell Larkin Clips Top Field For 100 Back Title at 2015 FINA World Championships|url=http://www.swimmingworldmagazine.com/news/mitchell-larkin-clips-top-field-for-100-back-title-at-2015-fina-world-championships/|publisher=[[Swimming World Magazine]]|date=4 August 2015|accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAt the Russian Championships in April 2016, Rylov broke the [[List of European records in swimming|European record]] in the 200 m backstroke with a time of 1:54.21.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evgeny Rylov Confines Kawecki\u2019s Euro 200 Back Standard To History in 1:54.2|url=http://www.swimvortex.com/evgeny-rylov-confines-kaweckis-euro-200-back-standard-to-history-in-154-2/|publisher=Swimvortex|date=21 April 2016|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the World Championships in July 2017, Rylov broke the [[List of European records in swimming|European record]] in the 200 m backstroke with a time of 1:53.61.<ref>{{cite web|title=MEN\u2019S 200 BACK FINAL IN BUDAPEST WITH RYLOV-MURPHY-PEBLEY|url=https://swimswam.com/race-video-mens-200-back-final-budapest-rylov-murphy-pebley/|publisher=SwimSwam|date=28 July 2017|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref> defeating the reigning Olympic Gold Medalist [[Ryan Murphy (swimmer)|Ryan Murphy]] in the process.  The swim places Rylov as the sixth fastest man to ever swim the 200 m backstroke while only [[Aaron Peirsol]], [[Ryosuke Irie]], [[Ryan Lochte]], [[Mitch Larkin]] and [[Tyler Clary]] have swum faster.\n\nHe defended the World Championships title in [[Swimming at the 2019 World Aquatics Championships \u2013 Men's 200 metre backstroke|200 m backstroke]].<ref>[https://rsport.ria.ru/20190726/1556910948.html \u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u044b\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0437\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0447\u0435\u043c\u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u043d\u0430 200-\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u0438\u043d\u0435]</ref>\n\n=== International Swimming League ===\nIn the Autumn of 2019 he was member of the inaugural [[International Swimming League]] swimming for the [[Energy Standard International Swim Club]], who won the team title in Las Vegas, Nevada, in December.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://isl.global/club-rosters/|title=Club Rosters \u2013 International Swimming League|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> He won the 100m and 200m Backstrokes at both the Naples and London matches after winning just the 100m Backstroke in Naples.<ref>{{Citation|title=2019 International Swimming League|date=2020-04-17|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2019_International_Swimming_League&oldid=951503304|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FINA}}\n*{{Sports-reference}}\n*[http://result.nanjing2014.org/IRS/ENG/ZB/ZBB101A_YO2014SW@@@@@@@ENG_number=22272.htm Nanjing 2014 Profile]\n*[http://www.eurosport.co.uk/swimming/evgeny-rylov_prs430287/person.shtml Eurosport Bio]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box|before=Evgeny Rylov|title=[[List of European records in swimming|Men's 200 metre backstroke<br />European record holder (long course)]]|years=8 August 2018 \u2013 present|after=''Incumbent''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer World LC Champions 200m Backstroke Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 50m Backstroke Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 200m Backstroke Men}}\n{{Footer World SC Champions 4x50m Medley Men}}\n{{Footer European Champions 200m Backstroke Men}}\n{{Footer European Champions 4x100m Freestyle Men}}\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Swimming 50m Backstroke Boys}} \n{{Footer Olympic Champions Swimming 100m Backstroke Boys}} \n{{Footer Olympic Champions Swimming 4 \u00d7 100m Medley Relay Boys}} \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rylov, Evgeny}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian male swimmers]]\n[[Category:Olympic swimmers of Russia]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Swimmers at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics]]\n[[Category:World Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Male backstroke swimmers]]\n[[Category:People from Novotroitsk]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists for Russia]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:European Aquatics Championships medalists in swimming]]\n[[Category:Youth Olympic gold medalists for Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Coach Rushton", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added club information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evgeny_Rylov"}
{"title_page": "Doxy (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|Jazz musical piece by Sonny Rollins}}\n\n\"'''Doxy'''\" is an early composition by jazz saxophonist [[Sonny Rollins]]. It was originally recorded by Rollins with [[Miles Davis]] in 1954, and appeared on the 10-inch LP ''[[Miles Davis with Sonny Rollins]]''. It was also included on the 1957 Davis album ''[[Bags' Groove]]''. The original recording features Davis on trumpet, Rollins on tenor saxophone, [[Horace Silver]] on piano, [[Percy Heath]] on bass, and [[Kenny Clarke]] on drums. When Rollins eventually established his own record label, he named it Doxy Records.  The chords are from [[Bob Carleton]]'s 16-bar song \"[[Ja-Da]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Charles|last2=McCarthy|first2=Albert|title=Jazz on record: a critical guide to the first 50 years, 1917\u20131967|year=1960|publisher=Hanover Books|page=62}}</ref>\n\n\"Doxy\" has become a [[jazz standard]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Martin|first1=Henry|last2=Waters|first2=Keith|title=Jazz: The First 100 Years|year=2010 |publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-4390-8333-8|page=248}}</ref> a frequently performed and recorded part of many musicians' repertoires. \"Doxy\" was written by Sonny Rollins during his stopover in England on a European tour. Its name is given after a [[Spread (food)|bread-spread]] that the band was eating in the hotel.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Charles|last2=McCarthy|first2=Albert|title=Jazz on record: a critical guide to the first 50 years, 1917\u20131967|year=1960|publisher=Hanover Books|page=15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1950s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Hard bop jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in B-flat major]]\n[[Category:Jazz songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Jazz musical piece by Sonny Rollins}}\n\"'''Doxy'''\" is an early composition by jazz saxophonist [[Sonny Rollins]]. It was originally recorded by Rollins with [[Miles Davis]] in 1954, and appeared on the 10-inch LP ''[[Miles Davis with Sonny Rollins]]''. It was also included on the 1957 Davis album ''[[Bags' Groove]]''. The original recording features Davis on trumpet, Rollins on tenor saxophone, [[Horace Silver]] on piano, [[Percy Heath]] on bass, and [[Kenny Clarke]] on drums. When Rollins eventually established his own record label, he named it Doxy Records.  The chords are from [[Bob Carleton]]'s 16-bar song, \"[[Ja-Da]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Charles|last2=McCarthy|first2=Albert|title=Jazz on record: a critical guide to the first 50 years, 1917-1967|year=1960|publisher=Hanover Books|page=62}}</ref>\n\n\"Doxy\" has become a [[jazz standard]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Martin|first1=Henry|last2=Waters|first2=Keith|title=Jazz: The First 100 Years|year=2010 |publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1-4390-8333-8|page=248}}</ref> a frequently performed and recorded part of many musicians' repertoires. \"Doxy\" was written by Sonny Rollins during his stopover in England on a European tour. Its name is given after a [[Spread (food)|bread-spread]] that the band was eating in the hotel.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fox|first1=Charles|last2=McCarthy|first2=Albert|title=Jazz on record: a critical guide to the first 50 years, 1917-1967|year=1960|publisher=Hanover Books|page=15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Jazz songs]]\n[[Category:1950s jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Hard bop jazz standards]]\n[[Category:Jazz compositions in B-flat major]]\n", "name_user": "DocWatson42", "label": "safe", "comment": "Performed minor cleanup.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doxy_(song)"}
{"title_page": "Second Silesian War", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Short description|18th-century war between Prussia and Austria}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Second Silesian War\n| partof      = the [[War of the Austrian Succession]] and the [[Silesian Wars]]\n| image       = Hohenfriedeberg - Attack of Prussian Infantry - 1745.jpg\n| alt         = Painting of Prussian infantry marching in formation across a field at the Battle of Hohenfriedberg\n| caption     = A Prussian infantry advance during the [[Battle of Hohenfriedberg]], as depicted by [[Carl R\u00f6chling]]\n| date        = 15 August 1744&nbsp;\u2013 25 December 1745\n| place       = [[Silesia]], [[Bohemia]], [[Upper Saxony]]\n| coordinates =\n| map_type    =\n| map_relief  =\n| latitude    =\n| longitude   =\n| map_size    =\n| map_marksize =\n| map_caption =\n| map_label   =\n| result      = Prussian victory\n| territory   =\n| combatant1  = {{flagcountry|Prussia|1750}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|Habsburg Monarchy|empire}}<br />{{flagcountry|Electorate of Saxony}}\n| commander1  = {{flagicon|Prussia|1750}} [[Frederick II of Prussia|King Frederick II]]\n* [[Kurt Christoph Graf von Schwerin|Count Kurt von Schwerin]]\n* [[Leopold I, Prince of Anhalt-Dessau|Prince Leopold I of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n* [[Leopold II, Prince of Anhalt-Dessau|Prince Leopold II of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|Habsburg Monarchy|empire}} [[Maria Theresa I of Austria|Archduchess Maria Theresa]]\n* [[Prince Charles Alexander of Lorraine|Prince Charles of Lorraine]]\n* [[Otto Ferdinand von Abensberg und Traun|Otto Ferdinand von Traun]]\n{{flagicon|Electorate of Saxony}} [[Augustus III of Poland|Prince-Elector Frederick Augustus II]]\n* [[Frederick Augustus Rutowsky|Count Frederick Augustus Rutowsky]]\n| strength1   =\n| strength2   =\n| casualties1 =\n| casualties2 =\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Silesian Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox War of the Austrian Succession}}\n}}\nThe '''Second Silesian War''' ({{lang-de|Zweiter Schlesischer Krieg|links=no}}) was a conflict between [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] and [[Archduchy of Austria|Austria]] that lasted from 1744 to 1745 and confirmed Prussia's control of the region of [[Silesia]] (now in south-western Poland). The war was fought mainly in Silesia, [[Bohemia]], and [[Upper Saxony]] and formed one [[theatre (warfare)|theatre]] of the wider [[War of the Austrian Succession]]. It was the second of three [[Silesian Wars]] fought between [[Frederick the Great]]'s Prussia and [[Maria Theresa]]'s Austria in the mid-18th century, all three of which ended in Prussian control of Silesia.\n\nThe conflict has been viewed as a continuation of the [[First Silesian War]], which had concluded only two years before. After the [[Treaty of Berlin (1742)|Treaty of Berlin]] ended hostilities between Austria and Prussia in 1742, the [[Habsburg Monarchy]]'s fortunes improved greatly in the continuing War of the Austrian Succession. As Austria expanded its alliances with the 1743 [[Treaty of Worms (1743)|Treaty of Worms]], Prussia entered a renewed alliance with Austria's enemies in the [[League of Frankfurt]] and rejoined the war, hoping to prevent a resurgent Austria from taking back Silesia.\n\nThe war began with a Prussian invasion of Habsburg Bohemia in mid-1744, and ended in a Prussian victory with the [[Treaty of Dresden]] in December 1745, which confirmed Prussian control of Silesia. Continuing conflict over Silesia would draw Austria and Prussia into a [[Third Silesian War]] a decade later. The Second Silesian War repeated the defeat of the Habsburg Monarchy by a lesser German power and contributed to the [[Austria\u2013Prussia rivalry]] that shaped German politics for more than a century.\n\n==Context and causes==\n===First Silesian War===\n{{Main|First Silesian War}}\n[[File:Maria Theresia of Austria Tuerkisch.jpg|thumb|alt=Portrait painting of a young Maria Theresa|[[Maria Theresa]] of Austria {{circa|1744}}, by [[Martin van Meytens]]]]\n[[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor Charles VI]] of [[House of Habsburg|Habsburg]] died in 1740 without a male heir; he was succeeded by his eldest daughter, who became ruler of the [[Archduchy of Austria]], as well as of the [[Lands of the Bohemian Crown|Bohemian]] and [[Kingdom of Hungary (1526\u20131867)|Hungarian]] lands within the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], as Archduchess [[Maria Theresa]].<ref>{{Harvp|Asprey|1986|p=24}}</ref> During Emperor Charles VI's lifetime, this female succession was generally acknowledged by the [[imperial state]]s, but when he died it was promptly contested by several parties.<ref>{{Harvp|Clifford|1914|p=3100}}</ref> The newly crowned King [[Frederick the Great|Frederick II]] of [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] took this Austrian succession crisis as an opportunity to press his dynasty's territorial claims in the Habsburg [[crown land]] of [[Silesia]], invading in December 1740 and beginning the [[First Silesian War]].<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|p=183}}</ref>\n\nAfter early Prussian successes, other powers were emboldened to attack the beleaguered Habsburg realm, widening the conflict into what became the [[War of the Austrian Succession]].<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|pp=193\u2013194}}</ref> Prussia, [[Kingdom of France|France]], [[Spanish Empire|Spain]], [[Electorate of Bavaria|Bavaria]] and others formed an alliance known as the [[League of Nymphenburg]] to support each other's efforts to seize Habsburg territory and Bavaria's bid for the [[imperial election of 1742|imperial election]]. The allies invaded on multiple fronts in mid-1741, soon occupying Austrian [[Tyrol]], [[Upper Austria]] and [[Bohemia]], and even threatening [[Vienna]].<ref>{{Harvp|Black|2002|pp=102\u2013103}}</ref> Faced with a potential war of [[Partition (politics)|partition]], Austria negotiated a secret [[armistice]] with Prussia in October and redeployed its forces to face its other enemies.<ref name=\"Holborn 213\">{{Harvp|Holborn|1982|p=213}}</ref>\n\nPrussian forces resumed offensive operations in December, invading [[Moravia]] and blocking an Austrian drive toward [[Prague]] in early 1742.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1862a|volume=Book XIII|title=Chapter XIII \u2013 Battle of Chotusitz|pages=574\u2013579|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-VTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA574}}</ref> Elector [[Charles VII, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles Albert of Bavaria]] won the [[1742 Imperial election]] and became [[Holy Roman Emperor]].<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=106}}</ref> In July 1742 Prussia and Austria made a [[separate peace]] in the [[Treaty of Berlin (1742)|Treaty of Berlin]], under which Austria [[Cession|ceded]] the majority of Silesia to Prussia in return for Prussia's neutrality in the continuing war.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1862a|volume=Book XIII|title=Chapter XIV \u2013 Peace of Breslau|pages=581\u2013586|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-VTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA581}}</ref> In late 1742, while Prussia enjoyed the restored peace and worked to assimilate Silesia into its administration and economy,<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=130\u2013131}}</ref> Austria fought on against Bavaria and France, reversing its losses from 1741.<ref name=\"Clifford 3103\">{{Harvp|Clifford|1914|p=3103}}</ref> By the middle of 1743 Austria had recovered control of Bohemia, driven the French back across the [[Rhine]] into [[Alsace]], and occupied Bavaria, exiling Emperor Charles Albert to [[Frankfurt]].<ref name=\"Clifford 3103\"/> Prussia's withdrawal from the War of the Austrian Succession under a separate peace embittered its erstwhile allies,<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=135\u2013136}}</ref> and the diplomatic position shifted in Austria's favour.<ref name=\"Fraser 143\">{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=143}}</ref>\n\n===Preparations for a second war===\n{{Further|War of the Austrian Succession}}\n[[File:CharlesVIIEmperor.JPG|thumb|alt=Portrait painting of Emperor Charles VII|[[Charles VII, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles Albert of Bavaria]] as Holy Roman Emperor, by [[Georg Desmar\u00e9es]]]]\nIn September 1743 Austria, [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Britain]]\u2013[[Electorate of Hanover|Hanover]], and [[Kingdom of Sardinia|Savoy\u2013Sardinia]] concluded a new alliance under the [[Treaty of Worms (1743)|Treaty of Worms]]; Britain had previously recognised Prussia's acquisition of Silesia as the mediator of the Treaty of Berlin, but this new alliance made no mention of that guarantee.<ref name=\"Fraser 143\"/> Meanwhile, the [[Russo-Swedish War (1741\u20131743)|Russo-Swedish War]] that had paralleled the First Silesian War ended in August 1743, freeing [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to potentially take Austria's side in the ongoing succession war. The following year, Empress [[Elizabeth of Russia]] appointed as her chancellor [[Alexey Bestuzhev-Ryumin|Alexey Bestuzhev]], a proponent of a pro-British and anti-French policy that entailed friendship to Austria and enmity to Prussia.<ref>{{Harvp|Bain|1911|pp=824\u2013826}}</ref> Prussia sought warmer relations with Russia and briefly won a minor defensive agreement, but Russia posed a growing threat to Prussia's eastern frontier.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=144}}</ref>\n\nFrederick was apprehensive that an irresistible anti-Prussian coalition might soon develop between Britain\u2013Hanover, [[Electorate of Saxony|Saxony]], Russia and Austria.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=148}}</ref> He viewed the Peace of Breslau as little more than another armistice with Austria, and he needed to prevent Maria Theresa from taking revenge at her convenience when the war elsewhere was concluded.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=163\u2013164}}</ref> Frederick decided that Prussia must restore its French alliance, build an anti-Austrian coalition with as many other German princes as possible, and then re-enter the war by striking first against Austria.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=152\u2013153}}</ref> So, in late 1743 and early 1744 Prussia conducted negotiations with France, Bavaria and other German princes to build a coalition to support the Emperor.<ref name=\"Carlyle XIV-VII\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1862b|volume=Book XIV|title=Chapter VII \u2013 Friedrich Makes Treaty With France; and Silently Gets Ready|pages=725\u2013729|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-VTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA725}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 1744 Prussia formed an alliance with Bavaria, Sweden, [[Hesse\u2013Kassel]] and the [[Electoral Palatinate]] known as the [[League of Frankfurt]], whose announced aim was to recover and defend the territories of Emperor Charles Albert, including Bohemia (where he had been proclaimed king in 1742).<ref name=\"Clifford 3104\">{{Harvp|Clifford|1914|p=3104}}</ref> A parallel treaty with France was concluded on 5 June, under which France committed to support the League and attack the [[Austrian Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Carlyle XIV-VII\"/><ref>{{Harvp|Hochedlinger|2003|p=257}}</ref> Prussia would champion the Emperor's cause by invading Bohemia from the north, a service for which the Emperor committed to cede the portions of Bohemia northeast of the [[Elbe]] to Prussia.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=153, 159}}</ref> Meanwhile, the main Austrian force under [[Prince Charles Alexander of Lorraine|Prince Charles of Lorraine]] would be occupied by the French in Alsace, where the French would counterattack on the opposite front as Prince Charles's army was pulled in two directions.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-I\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter I \u2013 Preliminary: How the Moment Arrived|pages=11\u201313|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA11}}</ref><ref name=\"Holborn 215\">{{Harvp|Holborn|1982|p=215}}</ref>\n\nMaria Theresa pursued the same goals she had from the beginning of the War of the Austrian Succession: first, she needed to compel a general recognition of the [[Pragmatic Sanction of 1713]] and her right to rule the Habsburg lands; second, she wanted to achieve the election of her husband, [[Francis I, Holy Roman Emperor|Francis Stephen of Lorraine]], as Holy Roman Emperor; third, she hoped to recover and preserve control of the contested Habsburg crown lands of Bohemia and Silesia.<ref name=\"Carlyle XIV-VII\"/> As soon as the Franco\u2013Bavarian threat from the west could be defeated, Austria intended to resume hostilities in Silesia and drive out the Prussians, restoring the borders of the territories Maria Theresa had inherited.<ref>{{Harvp|Asprey|1986|p=290}}</ref><ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=150}}</ref> On 7 August Prussia declared its intervention in the Austrian war on behalf of Emperor Charles Albert, beginning the Second Silesian War.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-I\"/>\n\n===Methods and technologies===\n{{Further|Early modern warfare}}\nEuropean warfare in the [[early modern period]] was characterised by the widespread adoption of [[firearm]]s in combination with more traditional [[bladed weapons]]. Eighteenth-century European armies were built around units of massed [[infantry]] armed with [[smoothbore]] [[flintlock musket]]s and [[bayonet]]s. [[Cavalry]] units of various weights armed with [[sabre]]s and [[pistol]]s were used for [[reconnaissance]] and [[shock tactics]]. Smoothbore [[artillery]] provided [[fire support]] and played the leading role in [[siege warfare]].<ref name=\"Black 38\">{{Harvp|Black|1994|pp=38\u201352}}</ref> Strategic warfare in this period centred around control of key [[fortification]]s positioned so as to command the surrounding regions and roads, with lengthy sieges a common feature of armed conflict. Decisive field battles were relatively rare, though they played a larger part in Frederick's theory of warfare than was typical among his contemporary rivals.<ref>{{Harvp|Black|1994|pp=67\u201380}}</ref>\n\nThe Silesian Wars and most European wars of the eighteenth century were fought as so-called [[cabinet wars]] in which disciplined [[regular armies]] were equipped and supplied by the state to conduct warfare on behalf of the sovereign's interests. Occupied enemy territories were regularly taxed and extorted for funds, but large-scale atrocities against civilian populations were rare compared with conflicts in the previous century.<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|209}}</ref> [[Military logistics]] was the decisive factor in many wars, as armies had grown too large to support themselves on prolonged campaigns by foraging and plunder alone. Military supplies were stored in centralised [[Supply depot|magazines]] and distributed by [[baggage train]]s that were highly vulnerable to enemy raids.<ref>{{Harvp|Creveld|1977|pp=26\u201328}}</ref> Armies were generally unable to sustain combat operations during winter and normally established [[Cantonment|winter quarters]] in the cold season, resuming their campaigns with the return of spring.<ref name=\"Black 38\"/>\n\n==Course==\n[[File:Map for the Silesian and Seven Years Wars.jpg|thumb|alt=Map of Central Europe with coloured territories|The Central European borders of [[Kingdom of Prussia|Brandenburg\u2013Prussia]] (blue-green) and the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] (red) after Prussia's seizure of Silesia in the [[First Silesian War]]|upright=1.2]]\n\n===Bohemian campaign of 1744===\nFrederick led Prussian soldiers across the frontier into Bohemia on 15 August 1744.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-II\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter II \u2013 Friedrich Marches upon Prag, Captures Prag|pages=16\u201327|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA16}}</ref> The invading army of around 70,000 men<ref name=\"Clifford 3104\"/> entered Bohemia in three columns: the eastern column, led by [[Kurt Christoph Graf von Schwerin|Count Kurt von Schwerin]], advanced from Silesia through [[Kladsko|Glatz]] and across the [[Giant Mountains]]; the central column, led by [[Leopold II, Prince of Anhalt-Dessau|Prince Leopold II of Anhalt-Dessau]], marched through Saxony (with an order from the Emperor guaranteeing [[safe conduct]]), passing through [[Lusatia]] and advancing to [[Leitmeritz]]; the western column, led by Frederick himself, advanced up the Elbe through [[Dresden]] and across the [[Ore Mountains]] to Leitmeritz.<ref name=\"Browning 181\">{{Harvp|Browning|1993|p=181}}</ref> After entering Bohemia, all three forces converged on Prague by the beginning of September, surrounding and besieging the Bohemian capital. The city underwent a week of heavy [[artillery]] bombardment, eventually surrendering to the Prussians on 16 September.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-II\"/>\n\nFrederick left a modest garrison in Prague and quickly marched on to the south, occupying [[T\u00e1bor|Tabor]], [[Budweis]] and [[Hlubok\u00e1 nad Vltavou|Frauenberg]].<ref>{{Harvp|Asprey|1986|pp=293\u2013294}}</ref> As expected, this new threat drew the Austrian army under Prince Charles back from Alsace through Bavaria; the French, however, failed to harass and disrupt the Austrian redeployment as they had promised,<ref name=\"Holborn 215\"/> owing in part to [[Louis XV of France|King Louis XV]]'s falling seriously ill while overseeing the defence at [[Metz]].<ref name=\"Clifford 3104\"/> Consequently, Prince Charles's army was able to return to Bohemia quickly, in good order and at full strength, though it was forced to abandon control of Alsace and Bavaria.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter III \u2013 Friedrich, Diligent in His Bohemian Conquests, Unexpectedly Comes upon Prince Karl, with No French Attending Him|pages=35\u201336|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA35}}</ref> Austrian diplomats also persuaded Saxony to re-enter the conflict on Austria's side, though in a strictly defensive role.<ref name=\"Browning 181\"/> By early October the Austrians were advancing through southwestern Bohemia toward Prague, while a Saxon army marched from the northwest to support them.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-IV\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter IV \u2013 Friedrich Reduced to Straits; Cannot Maintain His Moldau Conquests Against Prince Karl|pages=42\u201354|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA42}}</ref>\n\nLearning of the Austrians' rapid approach and unexpected strength, Frederick began pulling his forces back from south-eastern Bohemia to face the oncoming foes. Frederick tried repeatedly to force a decisive engagement, but Austrian commander [[Otto Ferdinand von Abensberg und Traun|Otto Ferdinand von Traun]] manoeuvred away from all Prussian advances while continually harassing the invaders' supply lines, and the Prussians' supplies ran low in the hostile province. By early November the Prussians were forced to retreat to Prague and the Elbe, and after some weeks of manoeuvre an Austrian\u2013Saxon force crossed the Elbe on 19 November.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-IV\"/> At this point the Prussians abandoned Prague and gave up Bohemia, retreating in poor morale into [[Upper Silesia]], which they defended through the winter against Austrian incursions.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-V\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter V \u2013 Friedrich, under Difficulties, Prepares for a New Campaign|pages=61\u201362,79\u201380|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA61}}</ref>\n\n===Early 1745: Bavarian defeat===\n[[File:Louis de Silvestre - Portrait of Augustus III of Poland - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|alt=Portrait painting of Frederick Augustus II|[[Augustus III of Poland|Frederick Augustus II]] of Saxony and Poland, by [[Louis de Silvestre]]]]\nOn 8 January 1745 Austria further strengthened its diplomatic position with the [[Treaty of Warsaw (1745)|Treaty of Warsaw]], which established a new \"Quadruple Alliance\" between Austria, Britain\u2013Hanover, Saxony, and the [[Dutch Republic]], aimed at opposing the League of Frankfurt and restoring the traditional borders of the Habsburg Monarchy.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\">{{Harvp|Clifford|1914|p=3105}}</ref> Prince-Elector [[Augustus III of Poland|Frederick Augustus II]] of Poland\u2013Saxony now committed 30,000 troops to the cause in return for cash subsidies from the British and Dutch.<ref>{{Harvp|Hochedlinger|2003|p=259}}</ref> This publicly defensive alliance was soon followed by a secret offensive agreement between Austria and Saxony, signed on 18 May in [[Leipzig]], which envisioned a territorial partition of Prussia.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-VI\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter VI \u2013 Valori Goes on an Electioneering Mission to Dresden|pages=88\u201390, 96\u201397|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA88}}</ref> Meanwhile, as Austrian forces withdrew from Bavaria to respond to the Prussian invasion of Bohemia, Emperor Charles Albert recovered control of his capital at [[Munich]], only to die shortly after relocating there on 20 January, destroying the rationale behind Frederick's alliance.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-V\"/> These events combined to produce a major shift in the direction of the war in Germany.<ref>{{Harvp|Simms|2009|pp=336\u2013337}}</ref>\n\nWith Prussia's forces driven out of Bohemia, Austria renewed its offensive against Bavaria in March 1745, swiftly over-running the defences that had been reestablished there during the winter. On 15 April the Austrians under [[K\u00e1roly J\u00f3zsef Batthy\u00e1ny|Count Batthy\u00e1ny]] decisively defeated the Franco-Bavarian army at the [[Battle of Pfaffenhofen]] and drove the allied forces entirely out of Bavaria.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-VI\"/> After this defeat, [[Maximilian III Joseph, Elector of Bavaria|Maximilian III of Bavaria]] (the son of the late Emperor Charles Albert) made peace with Maria Theresa by the [[Treaty of F\u00fcssen]] on 22 April.<ref name=\"Holborn 216\">{{Harvp|Holborn|1982|p=216}}</ref> In the treaty, Maximilian abandoned his father's claims on Austrian lands and promised to support Francis Stephen of Lorraine in the forthcoming imperial election; in return, Maria Theresa retroactively recognised Charles Albert's legitimacy as Holy Roman Emperor. This closed the Bavarian theatre of the War of the Austrian Succession, allowing Austria to concentrate its forces on the remaining fronts in Silesia, Italy, and the Netherlands.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-VI\"/>\n\n===Mid-1745: Battles of Hohenfriedberg and Soor===\n[[File:Preu\u00dfische Grenadier-Bataillone schlagen die Sachsische Garde.jpg|thumb|alt=Painting of Prussian grenadiers chasing Saxon soldiers across a marshy field at the Battle of Hohenfriedberg|Prussian [[grenadier]]s over-running Saxon forces during the [[Battle of Hohenfriedberg]], as depicted by [[Carl R\u00f6chling]]|upright=1.2]]\nHaving made peace with Bavaria, in late April Austria prepared for a large-scale invasion of Silesia, moving the army of Charles of Lorraine into Moravia, while a Saxon army organised near Leipzig. Frederick abandoned the mountainous southern tip of Upper Silesia to the Austrian [[vanguard]] of [[pandur]]s,<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-IX\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter IX \u2013 The Austrian\u2013Saxon Army Invades Silesia, across the Mountains|pages=127\u2013128, 142\u2013143|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA127}}</ref> concentrating his defences around the town of [[Z\u0105bkowice \u015al\u0105skie|Frankenstein]] in the valley of the [[Eastern Neisse]].<ref>{{Harvp|Asprey|1986|p=317}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[Leopold I, Prince of Anhalt-Dessau|Leopold I of Anhalt-Dessau]] was put in command of a smaller force in Brandenburg to prevent a Saxon invasion. At the end of May, the Austrian\u2013Saxon force crossed through the Giant Mountains and camped around the Silesian village of [[Dobromierz, Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Hohenfriedberg]], where Frederick staged a surprise attack on the morning of 4 June.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-IX\"/> The ensuing [[Battle of Hohenfriedberg]] ended in a decisive Prussian victory, sending Prince Charles's army retreating in disarray back into the mountains.<ref name=\"Showalter 84-88\">{{Harvp|Showalter|2012|pp=84\u201388}}</ref>\n\nAustria's reversal at Hohenfriedberg removed any immediate prospect of recovering Silesia.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=178}}</ref> The Prussians followed the retreating Austrian\u2013Saxon army into Bohemia, harassing its rear as far as [[K\u00f6niggr\u00e4tz]], where the two forces camped on opposite sides of the Elbe. The armies faced off but fought little during the next two months,<ref>Luvaas, from {{Harvp|Friedrich II, King of Prussia|2009|p=5}}</ref> while Frederick pursued a peace agreement that would again guarantee his control of Silesia.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XI\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XI \u2013 Camp of Chlum: Friedrich Cannot Achieve Peace|pages=153\u2013156, 169\u2013170, 171\u2013172|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA153}}</ref> Britain's willingness to subsidise Austria's war against Prussia was greatly reduced by the outbreak of a new [[Jacobite rising of 1745|Jacobite uprising]], and on 26 August Britain and Prussia agreed to the [[Convention of Hanover (1745)|Convention of Hanover]], in which both sides recognised each other's German possessions (including Prussian Silesia), and Prussia committed not to seek territorial gains in Bohemia or Saxony in any eventual peace agreement.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=185\u2013186}}</ref>\n\nOn the Austrian side, Maria Theresa negotiated through the middle of the year with the German [[prince-elector]]s to make her husband Holy Roman Emperor, now that the Bavarian emperor had died.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XI\"/> The [[1745 Imperial election]] was held on 13 September in Frankfurt, where Francis Stephen of Lorraine was indeed named Emperor Francis I (despite dissenting votes from Prussia and the Palatinate), achieving one of Maria Theresa's major goals in the war.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\"/> Meanwhile, supplies had run low in the Prussian camp in Bohemia, and Prussia's forces were gradually pushed back by Austrian probes.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XI\"/> On 29 September Prince Charles's army staged a surprise attack on Frederick's camp near the village of [[Hajnice|Soor]]; the resulting [[Battle of Soor]] ended in a Prussian victory, despite the Austrian surprise and superior numbers.<ref name=\"Holborn 216\"/><ref name=\"Showalter 84-88\"/> The Prussian's supplies were exhausted, however, and they withdrew again into Upper Silesia for the winter, driving out the Austrian light troops that had entered the region ahead of Prince Charles's main force.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XII \u2013 Battle of Sohr|page=188|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA188}}</ref>\n\n===Late 1745: Battles of Hennersdorf and Kesselsdorf===\n[[File:Friedrich2 jung.jpg|thumb|alt=Portrait painting of a young Frederick the Great|[[Frederick the Great]] of Prussia in 1745, by [[Antoine Pesne]]]]\nPrussia and Britain hoped that the Austrian defeats at Hohenfreidberg and Soor would persuade Austria to come to terms and concentrate its efforts against France, but Maria Theresa was resolved to fight on. On 29 August Austria and Saxony had agreed on a more offensive alliance aimed at seizing Prussian territory,<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=186}}</ref> and in early November they began a new offensive from multiple directions toward Brandenburg.<ref name=\"Holborn 216\"/><ref name=\"Showalter 84-88\"/> Prince Charles's Austrian army marched north from Bohemia toward Lusatia, while the main Saxon army under [[Frederick Augustus Rutowsky]] prepared to attack from western Saxony, hoping together to seize [[Berlin]] and end the war outright. On 8 November Frederick was informed of these movements and ordered Leopold I to prepare his troops in western Brandenburg, while Frederick himself departed for [[Lower Silesia]] to gather forces to meet Charles's advance.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XIII \u2013 Saxony and Austria Make a Surprising Last Attempt|pages=192\u2013197|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA192}}</ref>\n\nPrussian forces quietly paralleled Prince Charles's march through Lusatia, until the Austrians had come nearly to the Brandenburg border. There, on 23 November Frederick launched a successful surprise attack on Charles's camp at [[Katholisch Hennersdorf]]; this [[Battle of Hennersdorf]] ended with the Saxon elements of the allied army destroyed and the larger Austrian force confused and scattered. Charles and his remnants were forced to retreat back into central Saxony and Bohemia, leaving Lusatia under Prussian control.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=194}}</ref> Meanwhile, Leopold I's army advanced into western Saxony on 29 November against minimal resistance, progressing as far as Leipzig by the next day and occupying that city. From there, his army and Frederick's converged toward Dresden in early December.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XIV\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XIV \u2013 Battle of Kesselsdorf|pages=210\u2013213|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA210}}</ref>\n\nFrederick's force attempted to come between the Saxon capital and Prince Charles's Austrians, while Leopold's army advanced directly upon Rutowsky's Saxons, who were entrenched beside the village of [[Kesselsdorf]].<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XIV\"/> On 15 December Leopold's force attacked and destroyed Rutowsky's army in the [[Battle of Kesselsdorf]], opening the way to Dresden, as Prince Charles and the remaining Saxon soldiers retreated through the Ore Mountains into Bohemia.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\"/> The Prussians occupied Dresden on 18 December,<ref name=\"Fraser 196\">{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=196}}</ref> after which Frederick once again sent envoys to Maria Theresa and Frederick Augustus II to propose peace.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XV\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XV \u2013 Peace of Dresden: Friedrich Does March Home|pages=220\u2013221|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA220}}</ref>\n\n===Treaty of Dresden===\nAustrian and Saxon delegates and British mediators joined the Prussians in Dresden, where they quickly negotiated a peace treaty. Under the resulting agreement, Maria Theresa acknowledged Prussia's control of Silesia and Glatz, and Frederick retroactively recognised Francis I as Holy Roman Emperor and agreed to the Pragmatic Sanction,<ref name=\"Fraser 196\"/> while also committing to neutrality for the remainder of the War of the Austrian Succession.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\"/> For its part in the Austrian alliance, Saxony was compelled to pay one million [[rixdollar]]s in reparations to Prussia. The region's border were thus confirmed at the ''[[status quo ante bellum]]'', which had been Prussia's principal goal.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XV\"/> This [[Treaty of Dresden]] was signed on 25 December 1745, ending the Second Silesian War between Austria, Saxony, and Prussia.<ref name=\"Fraser 196\"/>\n\n==Outcomes==\n[[File:Europe 1748-1766 en.png|thumb|alt=Map of European political borders in 1748|Europe in the years after the [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748)]], with [[Kingdom of Prussia|Brandenburg\u2013Prussia]] in violet and the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] in gold|upright=1.2]]\nThe First and Second Silesian Wars have been described as campaigns within one continuous War of the Austrian Succession.<ref>{{Harvp|Levy|1988|p=183}}</ref> Partly for this reason, contemporaries and later historians have consistently viewed the Second Silesian War's conclusion as a victory for Prussia, which defended its seizure of Silesia.<ref>{{Harvp|Browning|2005|p=530}}</ref> Prussia's intervention in Bohemia also seriously impeded the Austrian war effort against France.<ref name=\"Holborn 215\"/> However, by making another separate peace while the French continued to fight the wider War of the Austrian Succession, Frederick damaged his own diplomatic credibility.<ref name=\"Holborn 213\"/> The Treaty of Dresden also deepened Austria and Saxony's hostility toward Prussia,<ref name=\"Holborn 214-215\">{{Harvp|Holborn|1982|pp=214\u2013215}}</ref> leading them into the anti-Prussian alliance that would spark the [[Third Silesian War]] in the following decade.<ref name=\"Fraser 310\">{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=310}}</ref>\n\n===Prussia===\nBy again defeating Austria, Prussia confirmed its acquisition of Silesia, a densely industrialised region with a large population and substantial tax yields.<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|p=192}}</ref> The small kingdom's unexpected victories over the Habsburg Monarchy marked the beginning of Prussia's rise toward the status of a European [[great power]], as it began to leave German rivals such as Bavaria and Saxony behind.<ref name=\"Clark 196\">{{Harvp|Clark|2006|p=196}}</ref> His series of battlefield victories in 1745 won Frederick general acclaim as a brilliant military commander; it was at the end of this war that he began to be spoken of as \"Frederick the Great.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864b|volume=Book XVI|title=Chapter I \u2013 Sans-Souci|page=239|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA239}}</ref><ref>Luvaas, from {{Harvp|Friedrich II, King of Prussia|2009|p=6}}</ref>\n\nThe seizure of Silesia made Prussia and Austria into lasting and determined enemies, beginning the [[Austria\u2013Prussia rivalry]] that would come to dominate German politics over the next century.<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|p=216}}</ref> Saxony, envious of Prussia's ascendancy and threatened by Prussian Silesia's geostrategic position, also turned its foreign policy firmly against Prussia.<ref name=\"Holborn 214-215\"/> Frederick's repeated unilateral withdrawal from his alliances in the War of the Austrian Succession deepened the French royal court's distrust of him,<ref name=\"Holborn 213\"/> and his next perceived \"betrayal\" (a defensive alliance with Britain under the 1756 [[Convention of Westminster]]) accelerated France's eventual realignment toward Austria in the [[Diplomatic Revolution]] of the 1750s.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=297\u2013301}}</ref>\n\n===Austria===\nThe Second Silesian War was a disappointment for Austria, whose armed forces proved surprisingly ineffective against smaller Prussian armies.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=133}}</ref> The Treaty of Dresden formalised the loss of the Habsburg Monarchy's wealthiest province,<ref name=\"Clark 196\"/> and defeat by a lesser German prince significantly dented Habsburg prestige.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=134\u2013135}}</ref> The rest of the Habsburg patrimony in Central Europe was preserved intact, however, and Maria Theresa did win Prussia's retroactive support for her husband's election as Holy Roman Emperor.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\"/>\n\nDespite its defeat, Austria was reluctant to recognise Prussia as a rival power and refused to accept the loss of Silesia.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=197\u2013198}}</ref> When the [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]] finally ended the wider War of the Austrian Succession in 1748, Maria Theresa's government refused to sign the peace agreement because it guaranteed Prussian sovereignty in the conquered province. Instead, she began a general reform of Austria's military and a review of its diplomatic policy, all aimed at one day recovering Silesia and relegating Prussia to the status of a lesser power.<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|pp=196\u2013197}}</ref> This policy eventually led to the formation of a broad anti-Prussian alliance between Austria, France and Russia, followed by the outbreak of the Third Silesian War and the wider [[Seven Years' War]] in 1756.<ref name=\"Fraser 310\"/> The struggle with Prussia would become the driving factor behind wide-ranging efforts to modernise the Habsburg Monarchy over the next half century.<ref>{{Harvp|Hochedlinger|2003|p=267}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|last=Asprey|first=Robert B.|author-link=Robert B. Asprey|title=Frederick the Great: The Magnificent Enigma|publisher=[[Ticknor and Fields]]|location=New York|year=1986|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Frederick_the_Great.html?id=VhtoAAAAMAAJ|isbn=978-0-89919-352-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite encyclopedia|first=Robert Nisbet|last=Bain|author-link=Robert Nisbet Bain|title=Bestuzhev-Ryumin, Alexius Petrovich, Count|editor-first=Hugh|editor-last=Chisholm|editor-link=Hugh Chisholm|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|edition=11th|volume=3|year=1911|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|location=Cambridge|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/Bestuzhev-Ryumin,_Alexius_Petrovich,_Count|oclc=873076959|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Jeremy|last=Black|author-link=Jeremy Black (historian)|title=European Warfare, 1660\u20131815|year=1994|publisher=[[UCL Press]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-85728-172-9|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/_/wLm_swEACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Jeremy|last=Black|title=European International Relations 1648\u20131815|year=2002|publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]]|location=London|isbn=978-0-333-96450-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OT-ttAEACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Browning|first=Reed|author-link=Reed Browning|year=1993|title=The War of the Austrian Succession|location=New York|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|isbn=978-0-312-09483-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Browning|first=Reed|title=New Views on the Silesian Wars|journal=[[Journal of Military History]]|date=April 2005|volume=69|issue=2|pages=521\u2013534|doi=10.1353/jmh.2005.0077|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|work=History of Friedrich II of Prussia, Called Frederick the Great|first=Thomas|last=Carlyle|authorlink=Thomas Carlyle|year=1862a|volume=III|title=Book XIII \u2013 First Silesian War, Leaving the General European One Ablaze All Round, Gets Ended \u2013 May 1741 \u2013 July 1742|publisher=[[Chapman & Hall]]|location=London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-VTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA399|oclc=1045538020}}\n* {{Cite book|work=History of Friedrich II of Prussia, Called Frederick the Great|first=Thomas|last=Carlyle|year=1862b|volume=III|title=Book XIV \u2013 The Surrounding European War Does Not End \u2013 August 1742 \u2013 July 1744|publisher=Chapman & Hall|location=London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-VTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA589|oclc=1045538020}}\n* {{Cite book|work=History of Friedrich II of Prussia, Called Frederick the Great|first=Thomas|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=IV|title=Book XV \u2013 Second Silesian War, Important Episode in the General European One \u2013 15th August 1744 \u2013 25th December 1745|publisher=Chapman & Hall|location=London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA1|oclc=1045538020}}\n* {{Cite book|work=History of Friedrich II of Prussia, Called Frederick the Great|first=Thomas|last=Carlyle|year=1864b|volume=IV|title=Book XVI \u2013 The Ten Years of Peace \u2013 1746\u20131756|publisher=Chapman & Hall|location=London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA233|oclc=1045538020}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Iron Kingdom: The Rise and Downfall of Prussia, 1600\u20131947|first=Christopher|last=Clark|author-link=Christopher Clark|year=2006|publisher=[[Belknap Press]]|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|isbn=978-0-674-02385-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FGYsAAAAYAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|title=The Standard History of the World, by Great Historians|volume=Volume 5|first=John Herbert|last=Clifford|publisher=University Society|location=New York|year=1914|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=855IAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA3100|oclc=867881191|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Creveld|first=Martin van|authorlink=Martin van Creveld|title=Supplying War: Logistics from Wallenstein to Patton|year=1977|location=Cambridge|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=978-0-521-21730-9|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/_/x6zCMnmr8-EC|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=David|last=Fraser|author-link=David Fraser (British Army officer)|title=Frederick the Great: King of Prussia|location=London|publisher=[[Allen Lane]]|year=2000|isbn=978-0-7139-9377-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sR5oAAAAMAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|author=Friedrich II, King of Prussia|author-link=Frederick the Great|editor-first=Jay|editor-last=Luvaas|editor-link=Jay Luvaas|title=Frederick the Great on the Art of War|publisher=[[Da Capo Press]]|location=New York|year=2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iS4vE33il3gC|isbn=978-0-7867-4977-5|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|title=Austria's Wars of Emergence: War, State and Society in the Habsburg Monarchy, 1683\u20131797|first=Michael|last=Hochedlinger|year=2003|publisher=[[Longman]]|isbn=978-0-582-29084-6|location=London|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mppnAAAAMAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|title=A History of Modern Germany: 1648\u20131840|first=Hajo|last=Holborn|author-link=Hajo Holborn|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]|location=Princeton, New Jersey|year=1982|isbn=978-0-691-00796-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yeXYMV3CZ0IC|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Levy|first=Jack S.|title=Analytic Problems in the Identification of Wars|journal=[[International Interactions]]|volume=14|number=2|year=1988|pages=181\u2013186|doi=10.1080/03050628808434702|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Dennis E.|last=Showalter|author-link=Dennis E. Showalter|title=Frederick the Great: A Military History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WvpiFTmWnaQC|date=2012|publisher=[[Frontline Books]]|location=Barnsley, England|isbn=978-1-78303-479-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Simms|first=Brendan|author-link=Brendan Simms|title=Three Victories and a Defeat: The Rise and Fall of the First British Empire|publisher=[[Basic Books]]|location=New York|year=2009|isbn=978-0-465-01332-6|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=izhwqC3W23UC|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Austrian Succession, War of the|first=David McDowall|last=Hannay|authorlink=David Hannay (historian)}}\n\n{{Silesia topics}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n[[Category:Silesian Wars]]\n[[Category:Frederick the Great]]\n[[Category:War of the Austrian Succession]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Short description|18th-century war between Prussia and Austria}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Second Silesian War\n| partof      = the [[War of the Austrian Succession]] and the [[Silesian Wars]]\n| image       = Hohenfriedeberg - Attack of Prussian Infantry - 1745.jpg\n| alt         = Painting of Prussian infantry marching in formation across a field at the Battle of Hohenfriedberg\n| caption     = A Prussian infantry advance during the [[Battle of Hohenfriedberg]], as depicted by [[Carl R\u00f6chling]]\n| date        = 15 August 1744&nbsp;\u2013 25 December 1745\n| place       = [[Silesia]], [[Bohemia]], [[Upper Saxony]]\n| coordinates =\n| map_type    =\n| map_relief  =\n| latitude    =\n| longitude   =\n| map_size    =\n| map_marksize =\n| map_caption =\n| map_label   =\n| result      = Prussian victory\n| territory   =\n| combatant1  = {{flagcountry|Prussia|1750}}\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|Habsburg Monarchy|empire}}<br />{{flagcountry|Electorate of Saxony}}\n| commander1  = {{flagicon|Prussia|1750}} [[Frederick II of Prussia|King Frederick II]]\n* [[Kurt Christoph Graf von Schwerin|Count Kurt von Schwerin]]\n* [[Leopold I, Prince of Anhalt-Dessau|Prince Leopold I of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n* [[Leopold II, Prince of Anhalt-Dessau|Prince Leopold II of Anhalt-Dessau]]\n| commander2  = {{flagicon|Habsburg Monarchy|empire}} [[Maria Theresa I of Austria|Archduchess Maria Theresa]]\n* [[Prince Charles Alexander of Lorraine|Prince Charles of Lorraine]]\n* [[Otto Ferdinand von Abensberg und Traun|Otto Ferdinand von Traun]]\n{{flagicon|Electorate of Saxony}} [[Augustus III of Poland|Prince-Elector Frederick Augustus II]]\n* [[Frederick Augustus Rutowsky|Count Frederick Augustus Rutowsky]]\n| strength1   =\n| strength2   =\n| casualties1 =\n| casualties2 =\n| notes       =\n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Silesian Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox War of the Austrian Succession}}\n}}\nThe '''Second Silesian War''' ({{lang-de|Zweiter Schlesischer Krieg|links=no}}) was a conflict between [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] and [[Archduchy of Austria|Austria]] that lasted from 1744 to 1745 and confirmed Prussia's control of the region of [[Silesia]] (now in south-western Poland). The war was fought mainly in Silesia, [[Bohemia]], and [[Upper Saxony]] and formed one [[theatre (warfare)|theatre]] of the wider [[War of the Austrian Succession]]. It was the second of three [[Silesian Wars]] fought between [[Frederick the Great]]'s Prussia and [[Maria Theresa]]'s Austria in the mid-18th century, all three of which ended in Prussian control of Silesia.\n\nThe conflict has been viewed as a continuation of the [[First Silesian War]], which had concluded only two years before. After the [[Treaty of Berlin (1742)|Treaty of Berlin]] ended hostilities between Austria and Prussia in 1742, the [[Habsburg Monarchy]]'s fortunes improved greatly in the continuing War of the Austrian Succession. As Austria expanded its alliances with the 1743 [[Treaty of Worms (1743)|Treaty of Worms]], Prussia entered a renewed alliance with Austria's enemies in the [[League of Frankfurt]] and rejoined the war, hoping to prevent a resurgent Austria from taking back Silesia.\n\nThe war began with a Prussian invasion of Habsburg Bohemia in mid-1744, and ended in a Prussian victory with the [[Treaty of Dresden]] in December 1745, which confirmed Prussian control of Silesia. Continuing conflict over Silesia would draw Austria and Prussia into a [[Third Silesian War]] a decade later. The Second Silesian War repeated the defeat of the Habsburg Monarchy by a lesser German power and contributed to the [[Austria\u2013Prussia rivalry]] that shaped German politics for more than a century.\n\n==Context and causes==\n===First Silesian War===\n{{Main|First Silesian War}}\n[[File:Maria Theresia of Austria Tuerkisch.jpg|thumb|alt=Portrait painting of a young Maria Theresa|[[Maria Theresa]] of Austria {{circa|1744}}, by [[Martin van Meytens]]]]\n[[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor Charles VI]] of [[House of Habsburg|Habsburg]] died in 1740 without a male heir; he was succeeded by his eldest daughter, who became ruler of the [[Archduchy of Austria]], as well as of the [[Lands of the Bohemian Crown|Bohemian]] and [[Kingdom of Hungary (1526\u20131867)|Hungarian]] lands within the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], as Archduchess [[Maria Theresa]].<ref>{{Harvp|Asprey|1986|p=24}}</ref> During Emperor Charles VI's lifetime, this female succession was generally acknowledged by the [[imperial state]]s, but when he died it was promptly contested by several parties.<ref>{{Harvp|Clifford|1914|p=3100}}</ref> The newly crowned King [[Frederick the Great|Frederick II]] of [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]] took this Austrian succession crisis as an opportunity to press his dynasty's territorial claims in the Habsburg [[crown land]] of [[Silesia]], invading in December 1740 and beginning the [[First Silesian War]].<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|p=183}}</ref>\n\nAfter early Prussian successes, other powers were emboldened to attack the beleaguered Habsburg realm, widening the conflict into what became the [[War of the Austrian Succession]].<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|pp=193\u2013194}}</ref> Prussia, [[Kingdom of France|France]], [[Spanish Empire|Spain]], [[Electorate of Bavaria|Bavaria]] and others formed an alliance known as the [[League of Nymphenburg]] to support each other's efforts to seize Habsburg territory and Bavaria's bid for the [[imperial election of 1742|imperial election]]. The allies invaded on multiple fronts in mid-1741, soon occupying Austrian [[Tyrol]], [[Upper Austria]] and [[Bohemia]], and even threatening [[Vienna]].<ref>{{Harvp|Black|2002|pp=102\u2013103}}</ref> Faced with a potential war of [[Partition (politics)|partition]], Austria negotiated a secret [[armistice]] with Prussia in October and redeployed its forces to face its other enemies.<ref name=\"Holborn 213\">{{Harvp|Holborn|1982|p=213}}</ref>\n\nPrussian forces resumed offensive operations in December, invading [[Moravia]] and blocking an Austrian drive toward [[Prague]] in early 1742.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1862a|volume=Book XIII|title=Chapter XIII \u2013 Battle of Chotusitz|pages=574\u2013579|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-VTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA574}}</ref> Elector [[Charles VII, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles Albert of Bavaria]] won the [[1742 Imperial election]] and became [[Holy Roman Emperor]].<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=106}}</ref> In July 1742 Prussia and Austria made a [[separate peace]] in the [[Treaty of Berlin (1742)|Treaty of Berlin]], under which Austria [[Cession|ceded]] the majority of Silesia to Prussia in return for Prussia's neutrality in the continuing war.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1862a|volume=Book XIII|title=Chapter XIV \u2013 Peace of Breslau|pages=581\u2013586|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-VTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA581}}</ref> In late 1742, while Prussia enjoyed the restored peace and worked to assimilate Silesia into its administration and economy,<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=130\u2013131}}</ref> Austria fought on against Bavaria and France, reversing its losses from 1741.<ref name=\"Clifford 3103\">{{Harvp|Clifford|1914|p=3103}}</ref> By the middle of 1743 Austria had recovered control of Bohemia, driven the French back across the [[Rhine]] into [[Alsace]], and occupied Bavaria, exiling Emperor Charles Albert to [[Frankfurt]].<ref name=\"Clifford 3103\"/> Prussia's withdrawal from the War of the Austrian Succession under a separate peace embittered its erstwhile allies,<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=135\u2013136}}</ref> and the diplomatic position shifted in Austria's favour.<ref name=\"Fraser 143\">{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=143}}</ref>\n\n===Preparations for a second war===\n{{Further|War of the Austrian Succession}}\n[[File:CharlesVIIEmperor.JPG|thumb|alt=Portrait painting of Emperor Charles VII|[[Charles VII, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles Albert of Bavaria]] as Holy Roman Emperor, by [[Georg Desmar\u00e9es]]]]\nIn September 1743 Austria, [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Britain]]\u2013[[Electorate of Hanover|Hanover]], and [[Kingdom of Sardinia|Savoy\u2013Sardinia]] concluded a new alliance under the [[Treaty of Worms (1743)|Treaty of Worms]]; Britain had previously recognised Prussia's acquisition of Silesia as the mediator of the Treaty of Berlin, but this new alliance made no mention of that guarantee.<ref name=\"Fraser 143\"/> Meanwhile, the [[Russo-Swedish War (1741\u20131743)|Russo-Swedish War]] that had paralleled the First Silesian War ended in August 1743, freeing [[Russian Empire|Russia]] to potentially take Austria's side in the ongoing succession war. The following year, Empress [[Elizabeth of Russia]] appointed as her chancellor [[Alexey Bestuzhev-Ryumin|Alexey Bestuzhev]], a proponent of a pro-British and anti-French policy that entailed friendship to Austria and enmity to Prussia.<ref>{{Harvp|Bain|1911|pp=824\u2013826}}</ref> Prussia sought warmer relations with Russia and briefly won a minor defensive agreement, but Russia posed a growing threat to Prussia's eastern frontier.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=144}}</ref>\n\nFrederick was apprehensive that an irresistible anti-Prussian coalition might soon develop between Britain\u2013Hanover, [[Electorate of Saxony|Saxony]], Russia and Austria.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=148}}</ref> He viewed the Peace of Breslau as little more than another armistice with Austria, and he needed to prevent Maria Theresa from taking revenge at her convenience when the war elsewhere was concluded.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=163\u2013164}}</ref> Frederick decided that Prussia must restore its French alliance, build an anti-Austrian coalition with as many other German princes as possible, and then re-enter the war by striking first against Austria.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=152\u2013153}}</ref> So, in late 1743 and early 1744 Prussia conducted negotiations with France, Bavaria and other German princes to build a coalition to support the Emperor.<ref name=\"Carlyle XIV-VII\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1862b|volume=Book XIV|title=Chapter VII \u2013 Friedrich Makes Treaty With France; and Silently Gets Ready|pages=725\u2013729|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y-VTAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA725}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 May 1744 Prussia formed an alliance with Bavaria, Sweden, [[Hesse\u2013Kassel]] and the [[Electoral Palatinate]] known as the [[League of Frankfurt]], whose announced aim was to recover and defend the territories of Emperor Charles Albert, including Bohemia (where he had been proclaimed king in 1742).<ref name=\"Clifford 3104\">{{Harvp|Clifford|1914|p=3104}}</ref> A parallel treaty with France was concluded on 5 June, under which France committed to support the League and attack the [[Austrian Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Carlyle XIV-VII\"/><ref>{{Harvp|Hochedlinger|2003|p=257}}</ref> Prussia would champion the Emperor's cause by invading Bohemia from the north, a service for which the Emperor committed to cede the portions of Bohemia northeast of the [[Elbe]] to Prussia.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=153, 159}}</ref> Meanwhile, the main Austrian force under [[Prince Charles Alexander of Lorraine|Prince Charles of Lorraine]] would be occupied by the French in Alsace, where the French would counterattack on the opposite front as Prince Charles's army was pulled in two directions.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-I\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter I \u2013 Preliminary: How the Moment Arrived|pages=11\u201313|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA11}}</ref><ref name=\"Holborn 215\">{{Harvp|Holborn|1982|p=215}}</ref>\n\nMaria Theresa pursued the same goals she had from the beginning of the War of the Austrian Succession: first, she needed to compel a general recognition of the [[Pragmatic Sanction of 1713]] and her right to rule the Habsburg lands; second, she wanted to achieve the election of her husband, [[Francis I, Holy Roman Emperor|Francis Stephen of Lorraine]], as Holy Roman Emperor; third, she hoped to recover and preserve control of the contested Habsburg crown lands of Bohemia and Silesia.<ref name=\"Carlyle XIV-VII\"/> As soon as the Franco\u2013Bavarian threat from the west could be defeated, Austria intended to resume hostilities in Silesia and drive out the Prussians, restoring the borders of the territories Maria Theresa had inherited.<ref>{{Harvp|Asprey|1986|p=290}}</ref><ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=150}}</ref> On 7 August Prussia declared its intervention in the Austrian war on behalf of Emperor Charles Albert, beginning the Second Silesian War.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-I\"/>\n\n===Methods and technologies===\n{{Further|Early modern warfare}}\nEuropean warfare in the [[early modern period]] was characterised by the widespread adoption of [[firearm]]s in combination with more traditional [[bladed weapons]]. Eighteenth-century European armies were built around units of massed [[infantry]] armed with [[smoothbore]] [[flintlock musket]]s and [[bayonet]]s. [[Cavalry]] units of various weights armed with [[sabre]]s and [[pistol]]s were used for [[reconnaissance]] and [[shock tactics]]. Smoothbore [[artillery]] provided [[fire support]] and played the leading role in [[siege warfare]].<ref name=\"Black 38\">{{Harvp|Black|1994|pp=38\u201352}}</ref> Strategic warfare in this period centred around control of key [[fortification]]s positioned so as to command the surrounding regions and roads, with lengthy sieges a common feature of armed conflict. Decisive field battles were relatively rare, though they played a larger part in Frederick's theory of warfare than was typical among his contemporary rivals.<ref>{{Harvp|Black|1994|pp=67\u201380}}</ref>\n\nThe Silesian Wars and most European wars of the eighteenth century were fought as so-called [[cabinet wars]] in which disciplined [[regular armies]] were equipped and supplied by the state to conduct warfare on behalf of the sovereign's interests. Occupied enemy territories were regularly taxed and extorted for funds, but large-scale atrocities against civilian populations were rare compared with conflicts in the previous century.<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|209}}</ref> [[Military logistics]] was the decisive factor in many wars, as armies had grown too large to support themselves on prolonged campaigns by foraging and plunder alone. Military supplies were stored in centralised [[Supply depot|magazines]] and distributed by [[baggage train]]s that were highly vulnerable to enemy raids.<ref>{{Harvp|Creveld|1977|pp=26\u201328}}</ref> Armies were generally unable to sustain combat operations during winter and normally established [[Cantonment|winter quarters]] in the cold season, resuming their campaigns with the return of spring.<ref name=\"Black 38\"/>\n\n==Course==\n[[File:Map for the Silesian and Seven Years Wars.jpg|thumb|alt=Map of Central Europe with coloured territories|The Central European borders of [[Kingdom of Prussia|Brandenburg\u2013Prussia]] (blue-green) and the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] (red) after Prussia's seizure of Silesia in the [[First Silesian War]]|upright=1.2]]\n\n===Bohemian campaign of 1744===\nFrederick led Prussian soldiers across the frontier into Bohemia on 15 August 1744.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-II\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter II \u2013 Friedrich Marches upon Prag, Captures Prag|pages=16\u201327|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA16}}</ref> The invading army of around 70,000 men<ref name=\"Clifford 3104\"/> entered Bohemia in three columns: the eastern column, led by [[Kurt Christoph Graf von Schwerin|Count Kurt von Schwerin]], advanced from Silesia through [[Kladsko|Glatz]] and across the [[Giant Mountains]]; the central column, led by [[Leopold II, Prince of Anhalt-Dessau|Prince Leopold II of Anhalt-Dessau]], marched through Saxony (with an order from the Emperor guaranteeing [[safe conduct]]), passing through [[Lusatia]] and advancing to [[Leitmeritz]]; the western column, led by Frederick himself, advanced up the Elbe through [[Dresden]] and across the [[Ore Mountains]] to Leitmeritz.<ref name=\"Browning 181\">{{Harvp|Browning|1993|p=181}}</ref> After entering Bohemia, all three forces converged on Prague by the beginning of September, surrounding and besieging the Bohemian capital. The city underwent a week of heavy [[artillery]] bombardment, eventually surrendering to the Prussians on 16 September.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-II\"/>\n\nFrederick left a modest garrison in Prague and quickly marched on to the south, occupying [[T\u00e1bor|Tabor]], [[Budweis]] and [[Hlubok\u00e1 nad Vltavou|Frauenberg]].<ref>{{Harvp|Asprey|1986|pp=293\u2013294}}</ref> As expected, this new threat drew the Austrian army under Prince Charles back from Alsace through Bavaria; the French, however, failed to harass and disrupt the Austrian redeployment as they had promised,<ref name=\"Holborn 215\"/> owing in part to [[Louis XV of France|King Louis XV]]'s falling seriously ill while overseeing the defence at [[Metz]].<ref name=\"Clifford 3104\"/> Consequently, Prince Charles's army was able to return to Bohemia quickly, in good order and at full strength, though it was forced to abandon control of Alsace and Bavaria.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter III \u2013 Friedrich, Diligent in His Bohemian Conquests, Unexpectedly Comes upon Prince Karl, with No French Attending Him|pages=35\u201336|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA35}}</ref> Austrian diplomats also persuaded Saxony to re-enter the conflict on Austria's side, though in a strictly defensive role.<ref name=\"Browning 181\"/> By early October the Austrians were advancing through southwestern Bohemia toward Prague, while a Saxon army marched from the northwest to support them.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-IV\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter IV \u2013 Friedrich Reduced to Straits; Cannot Maintain His Moldau Conquests Against Prince Karl|pages=42\u201354|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA42}}</ref>\n\nLearning of the Austrians' rapid approach and unexpected strength, Frederick began pulling his forces back from south-eastern Bohemia to face the oncoming foes. Frederick tried repeatedly to force a decisive engagement, but Austrian commander [[Otto Ferdinand von Abensberg und Traun|Otto Ferdinand von Traun]] manoeuvred away from all Prussian advances while continually harassing the invaders' supply lines, and the Prussians' supplies ran low in the hostile province. By early November the Prussians were forced to retreat to Prague and the Elbe, and after some weeks of manoeuvre an Austrian\u2013Saxon force crossed the Elbe on 19 November.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-IV\"/> At this point the Prussians abandoned Prague and gave up Bohemia, retreating in poor morale into [[Upper Silesia]], which they defended through the winter against Austrian incursions.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-V\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter V \u2013 Friedrich, under Difficulties, Prepares for a New Campaign|pages=61\u201362,79\u201380|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA61}}</ref>\n\n===Early 1745: Bavarian defeat===\n[[File:Louis de Silvestre - Portrait of Augustus III of Poland - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|alt=Portrait painting of Frederick Augustus II|[[Augustus III of Poland|Frederick Augustus II]] of Saxony and Poland, by [[Louis de Silvestre]]]]\nOn 8 January 1745 Austria further strengthened its diplomatic position with the [[Treaty of Warsaw (1745)|Treaty of Warsaw]], which established a new \"Quadruple Alliance\" between Austria, Britain\u2013Hanover, Saxony, and the [[Dutch Republic]], aimed at opposing the League of Frankfurt and restoring the traditional borders of the Habsburg Monarchy.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\">{{Harvp|Clifford|1914|p=3105}}</ref> Prince-Elector [[Augustus III of Poland|Frederick Augustus II]] of Poland\u2013Saxony now committed 30,000 troops to the cause in return for cash subsidies from the British and Dutch.<ref>{{Harvp|Hochedlinger|2003|p=259}}</ref> This publicly defensive alliance was soon followed by a secret offensive agreement between Austria and Saxony, signed on 18 May in [[Leipzig]], which envisioned a territorial partition of Prussia.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-VI\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter VI \u2013 Valori Goes on an Electioneering Mission to Dresden|pages=88\u201390, 96\u201397|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA88}}</ref> Meanwhile, as Austrian forces withdrew from Bavaria to respond to the Prussian invasion of Bohemia, Emperor Charles Albert recovered control of his capital at [[Munich]], only to die shortly after relocating there on 20 January, destroying the rationale behind Frederick's alliance.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-V\"/> These events combined to produce a major shift in the direction of the war in Germany.<ref>{{Harvp|Simms|2009|pp=336\u2013337}}</ref>\n\nWith Prussia's forces driven out of Bohemia, Austria renewed its offensive against Bavaria in March 1745, swiftly over-running the defences that had been reestablished there during the winter. On 15 April the Austrians under [[K\u00e1roly J\u00f3zsef Batthy\u00e1ny|Count Batthy\u00e1ny]] decisively defeated the Franco-Bavarian army at the [[Battle of Pfaffenhofen]] and drove the allied forces entirely out of Bavaria.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-VI\"/> After this defeat, [[Maximilian III Joseph, Elector of Bavaria|Maximilian III of Bavaria]] (the son of the late Emperor Charles Albert) made peace with Maria Theresa by the [[Treaty of F\u00fcssen]] on 22 April.<ref name=\"Holborn 216\">{{Harvp|Holborn|1982|p=216}}</ref> In the treaty, Maximilian abandoned his father's claims on Austrian lands and promised to support Francis Stephen of Lorraine in the forthcoming imperial election; in return, Maria Theresa retroactively recognised Charles Albert's legitimacy as Holy Roman Emperor. This closed the Bavarian theatre of the War of the Austrian Succession, allowing Austria to concentrate its forces on the remaining fronts in Silesia, Italy, and the Netherlands.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-VI\"/>\n\n===Mid-1745: Battles of Hohenfriedberg and Soor===\n[[File:Preu\u00dfische Grenadier-Bataillone schlagen die Sachsische Garde.jpg|thumb|alt=Painting of Prussian grenadiers chasing Saxon soldiers across a marshy field at the Battle of Hohenfriedberg|Prussian [[grenadier]]s over-running Saxon forces during the [[Battle of Hohenfriedberg]], as depicted by [[Carl R\u00f6chling]]|upright=1.2]]\nHaving made peace with Bavaria, in late April Austria prepared for a large-scale invasion of Silesia, moving the army of Charles of Lorraine into Moravia, while a Saxon army organised near Leipzig. Frederick abandoned the mountainous southern tip of Upper Silesia to the Austrian [[vanguard]] of [[pandur]]s,<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-IX\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter IX \u2013 The Austrian\u2013Saxon Army Invades Silesia, across the Mountains|pages=127\u2013128, 142\u2013143|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA127}}</ref> concentrating his defences around the town of [[Z\u0105bkowice \u015al\u0105skie|Frankenstein]] in the valley of the [[Eastern Neisse]].<ref>{{Harvp|Asprey|1986|p=317}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[Leopold I, Prince of Anhalt-Dessau|Leopold I of Anhalt-Dessau]] was put in command of a smaller force in Brandenburg to prevent a Saxon invasion. At the end of May, the Austrian\u2013Saxon force crossed through the Giant Mountains and camped around the Silesian village of [[Dobromierz, Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Hohenfriedberg]], where Frederick staged a surprise attack on the morning of 4 June.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-IX\"/> The ensuing [[Battle of Hohenfriedberg]] ended in a decisive Prussian victory, sending Prince Charles's army retreating in disarray back into the mountains.<ref name=\"Showalter 84-88\">{{Harvp|Showalter|2012|pp=84\u201388}}</ref>\n\nAustria's reversal at Hohenfriedberg removed any immediate prospect of recovering Silesia.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=178}}</ref> The Prussians followed the retreating Austrian\u2013Saxon army into Bohemia, harassing its rear as far as [[K\u00f6niggr\u00e4tz]], where the two forces camped on opposite sides of the Elbe. The armies faced off but fought little during the next two months,<ref>Luvaas, from {{Harvp|Friedrich II, King of Prussia|2009|p=5}}</ref> while Frederick pursued a peace agreement that would again guarantee his control of Silesia.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XI\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XI \u2013 Camp of Chlum: Friedrich Cannot Achieve Peace|pages=153\u2013156, 169\u2013170, 171\u2013172|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA153}}</ref> Britain's willingness to subsidise Austria's war against Prussia was greatly reduced by the outbreak of a new [[Jacobite rising of 1745|Jacobite uprising]], and on 26 August Britain and Prussia agreed to the [[Convention of Hanover (1745)|Convention of Hanover]], in which both sides recognised each other's German possessions (including Prussian Silesia), and Prussia committed not to seek territorial gains in Bohemia or Saxony in any eventual peace agreement.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=185\u2013186}}</ref>\n\nOn the Austrian side, Maria Theresa negotiated through the middle of the year with the German [[prince-elector]]s to make her husband Holy Roman Emperor, now that the Bavarian emperor had died.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XI\"/> The [[1745 Imperial election]] was held on 13 September in Frankfurt, where Francis Stephen of Lorraine was indeed named Emperor Francis I (despite dissenting votes from Prussia and the Palatinate), achieving one of Maria Theresa's major goals in the war.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\"/> Meanwhile, supplies had run low in the Prussian camp in Bohemia, and Prussia's forces were gradually pushed back by Austrian probes.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XI\"/> On 29 September Prince Charles's army staged a surprise attack on Frederick's camp near the village of [[Hajnice|Soor]]; the resulting [[Battle of Soor]] ended in a Prussian victory, despite the Austrian surprise and superior numbers.<ref name=\"Holborn 216\"/><ref name=\"Showalter 84-88\"/> The Prussian's supplies were exhausted, however, and they withdrew again into Upper Silesia for the winter, driving out the Austrian light troops that had entered the region ahead of Prince Charles's main force.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XII \u2013 Battle of Sohr|page=188|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA188}}</ref>\n\n===Late 1745: Battles of Hennersdorf and Kesselsdorf===\n[[File:Friedrich2 jung.jpg|thumb|alt=Portrait painting of a young Frederick the Great|[[Frederick the Great]] of Prussia in 1745, by [[Antoine Pesne]]]]\nPrussia and Britain hoped that the Austrian defeats at Hohenfreidberg and Soor would persuade Austria to come to terms and concentrate its efforts against France, but Maria Theresa was resolved to fight on. On 29 August Austria and Saxony had agreed on a more offensive alliance aimed at seizing Prussian territory,<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=186}}</ref> and in early November they began a new offensive from multiple directions toward Brandenburg.<ref name=\"Holborn 216\"/><ref name=\"Showalter 84-88\"/> Prince Charles's Austrian army marched north from Bohemia toward Lusatia, while the main Saxon army under [[Frederick Augustus Rutowsky]] prepared to attack from western Saxony, hoping together to seize [[Berlin]] and end the war outright. On 8 November Frederick was informed of these movements and ordered Leopold I to prepare his troops in western Brandenburg, while Frederick himself departed for [[Lower Silesia]] to gather forces to meet Charles's advance.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XIII \u2013 Saxony and Austria Make a Surprising Last Attempt|pages=192\u2013197|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA192}}</ref>\n\nPrussian forces quietly paralleled Prince Charles's march through Lusatia, until the Austrians had come nearly to the Brandenburg border. There, on 23 November Frederick launched a successful surprise attack on Charles's camp at [[Katholisch Hennersdorf]]; this [[Battle of Hennersdorf]] ended with the Saxon elements of the allied army destroyed and the larger Austrian force confused and scattered. Charles and his remnants were forced to retreat back into central Saxony and Bohemia, leaving Lusatia under Prussian control.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=194}}</ref> Meanwhile, Leopold I's army advanced into western Saxony on 29 November against minimal resistance, progressing as far as Leipzig by the next day and occupying that city. From there, his army and Frederick's converged toward Dresden in early December.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XIV\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XIV \u2013 Battle of Kesselsdorf|pages=210\u2013213|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA210}}</ref>\n\nFrederick's force attempted to come between the Saxon capital and Prince Charles's Austrians, while Leopold's army advanced directly upon Rutowsky's Saxons, who were entrenched beside the village of [[Kesselsdorf]].<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XIV\"/> On 15 December Leopold's force attacked and destroyed Rutowsky's army in the [[Battle of Kesselsdorf]], opening the way to Dresden, as Prince Charles and the remaining Saxon soldiers retreated through the Ore Mountains into Bohemia.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\"/> The Prussians occupied Dresden on 18 December,<ref name=\"Fraser 196\">{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=196}}</ref> after which Frederick once again sent envoys to Maria Theresa and Frederick Augustus II to propose peace.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XV\">{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864a|volume=Book XV|title=Chapter XV \u2013 Peace of Dresden: Friedrich Does March Home|pages=220\u2013221|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA220}}</ref>\n\n===Treaty of Dresden===\nAustrian and Saxon delegates and British mediators joined the Prussians in Dresden, where they quickly negotiated a peace treaty. Under the resulting agreement, Maria Theresa recognised Prussia's sovereignty in Silesia and Glatz, and Frederick retroactively acknowledged Francis I as Holy Roman Emperor and agreed to the Pragmatic Sanction,<ref name=\"Fraser 196\"/> while also committing to neutrality for the remainder of the War of the Austrian Succession.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\"/> For its part in the Austrian alliance, Saxony was compelled to pay one million [[rixdollar]]s in reparations to Prussia. The region's border were thus confirmed at the ''[[status quo ante bellum]]'', which had been Prussia's principal goal.<ref name=\"Carlyle XV-XV\"/> This [[Treaty of Dresden]] was signed on 25 December 1745, ending the Second Silesian War between Austria, Saxony, and Prussia.<ref name=\"Fraser 196\"/>\n\n==Outcomes==\n[[File:Europe 1748-1766 en.png|thumb|alt=Map of European political borders in 1748|Europe in the years after the [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748)]], with [[Kingdom of Prussia|Brandenburg\u2013Prussia]] in violet and the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] in gold|upright=1.2]]\nThe First and Second Silesian Wars have been described as campaigns within one continuous War of the Austrian Succession.<ref>{{Harvp|Levy|1988|p=183}}</ref> Partly for this reason, contemporaries and later historians have consistently viewed the Second Silesian War's conclusion as a victory for Prussia, which defended its seizure of Silesia.<ref>{{Harvp|Browning|2005|p=530}}</ref> Prussia's intervention in Bohemia also seriously impeded the Austrian war effort against France.<ref name=\"Holborn 215\"/> However, by making another separate peace while the French continued to fight the wider War of the Austrian Succession, Frederick damaged his own diplomatic credibility.<ref name=\"Holborn 213\"/> The Treaty of Dresden also deepened Austria and Saxony's hostility toward Prussia,<ref name=\"Holborn 214-215\">{{Harvp|Holborn|1982|pp=214\u2013215}}</ref> leading them into the anti-Prussian alliance that would spark the [[Third Silesian War]] in the following decade.<ref name=\"Fraser 310\">{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=310}}</ref>\n\n===Prussia===\nBy again defeating Austria, Prussia confirmed its acquisition of Silesia, a densely industrialised region with a large population and substantial tax yields.<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|p=192}}</ref> The small kingdom's unexpected victories over the Habsburg Monarchy marked the beginning of Prussia's rise toward the status of a European [[great power]], as it began to leave German rivals such as Bavaria and Saxony behind.<ref name=\"Clark 196\">{{Harvp|Clark|2006|p=196}}</ref> His series of battlefield victories in 1745 won Frederick general acclaim as a brilliant military commander; it was at the end of this war that he began to be spoken of as \"Frederick the Great.\"<ref>{{Cite book|last=Carlyle|year=1864b|volume=Book XVI|title=Chapter I \u2013 Sans-Souci|page=239|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p5ZkJQeYlk0C&pg=PA239}}</ref><ref>Luvaas, from {{Harvp|Friedrich II, King of Prussia|2009|p=6}}</ref>\n\nThe seizure of Silesia made Prussia and Austria into lasting and determined enemies, beginning the [[Austria\u2013Prussia rivalry]] that would come to dominate German politics over the next century.<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|p=216}}</ref> Saxony, envious of Prussia's ascendancy and threatened by Prussian Silesia's geostrategic position, also turned its foreign policy firmly against Prussia.<ref name=\"Holborn 214-215\"/> Frederick's repeated unilateral withdrawal from his alliances in the War of the Austrian Succession deepened the French royal court's distrust of him,<ref name=\"Holborn 213\"/> and his next perceived \"betrayal\" (a defensive alliance with Britain under the 1756 [[Convention of Westminster]]) accelerated France's eventual realignment toward Austria in the [[Diplomatic Revolution]] of the 1750s.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=297\u2013301}}</ref>\n\n===Austria===\nThe Second Silesian War was a disappointment for Austria, whose armed forces proved surprisingly ineffective against smaller Prussian armies.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|p=133}}</ref> The Treaty of Dresden formalised the loss of the Habsburg Monarchy's wealthiest province,<ref name=\"Clark 196\"/> and defeat by a lesser German prince significantly dented Habsburg prestige.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=134\u2013135}}</ref> The rest of the Habsburg patrimony in Central Europe was preserved intact, however, and Maria Theresa did win Prussia's retroactive support for her husband's election as Holy Roman Emperor.<ref name=\"Clifford 3105\"/>\n\nDespite its defeat, Austria was reluctant to recognise Prussia as a rival power and refused to accept the loss of Silesia.<ref>{{Harvp|Fraser|2000|pp=197\u2013198}}</ref> When the [[Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle (1748)|Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle]] finally ended the wider War of the Austrian Succession in 1748, Maria Theresa's government refused to sign the peace agreement because it guaranteed Prussian sovereignty in the conquered province. Instead, she began a general reform of Austria's military and a review of its diplomatic policy, all aimed at one day recovering Silesia and relegating Prussia to the status of a lesser power.<ref>{{Harvp|Clark|2006|pp=196\u2013197}}</ref> This policy eventually led to the formation of a broad anti-Prussian alliance between Austria, France and Russia, followed by the outbreak of the Third Silesian War and the wider [[Seven Years' War]] in 1756.<ref name=\"Fraser 310\"/> The struggle with Prussia would become the driving factor behind wide-ranging efforts to modernise the Habsburg Monarchy over the next half century.<ref>{{Harvp|Hochedlinger|2003|p=267}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|last=Asprey|first=Robert B.|author-link=Robert B. Asprey|title=Frederick the Great: The Magnificent Enigma|publisher=[[Ticknor and Fields]]|location=New York|year=1986|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Frederick_the_Great.html?id=VhtoAAAAMAAJ|isbn=978-0-89919-352-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite encyclopedia|first=Robert Nisbet|last=Bain|author-link=Robert Nisbet Bain|title=Bestuzhev-Ryumin, Alexius Petrovich, Count|editor-first=Hugh|editor-last=Chisholm|editor-link=Hugh Chisholm|encyclopedia=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|edition=11th|volume=3|year=1911|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|location=Cambridge|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/1911_Encyclop%C3%A6dia_Britannica/Bestuzhev-Ryumin,_Alexius_Petrovich,_Count|oclc=873076959|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Jeremy|last=Black|author-link=Jeremy Black (historian)|title=European Warfare, 1660\u20131815|year=1994|publisher=[[UCL Press]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-85728-172-9|url=https://www.google.com/books/edition/_/wLm_swEACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|first=Jeremy|last=Black|title=European International Relations 1648\u20131815|year=2002|publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]]|location=London|isbn=978-0-333-96450-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OT-ttAEACAAJ|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Browning|first=Reed|author-link=Reed Browning|year=1993|title=The War of the Austrian Succession|location=New York|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|isbn=978-0-312-09483-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{Ci